quoteText:
The Signora had no business to do it, no business
at all. She promised us south rooms with a view close together, instead
of which here are north rooms, looking into a courtyard, and a long way
apart. Oh, Lucy!
subQuotationList:
['The Signora had no business to do it,', 'no business
at all. She promised us south rooms with a view close together, instead
of which here are north rooms, looking into a courtyard, and a long way
apart. Oh, Lucy!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: And a Cockney, besides! It might be London.
subQuotationList: ['And a Cockney, besides!', 'It might be London.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Charlotte, don't you feel,
too, that we might be in London? I can hardly believe that all kinds of
other things are just outside. I suppose it is one's being so tired.
subQuotationList: ["Charlotte, don't you feel,\ntoo, that we might be in London? I can hardly believe that all kinds of\nother things are just outside. I suppose it is one's being so tired."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: This meat has surely been used for soup,
subQuotationList: ['This meat has surely been used for soup,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I want so to see the Arno. The rooms the Signora promised us in her
letter would have looked over the Arno. The Signora had no business to
do it at all. Oh, it is a shame!
subQuotationList: ['I want so to see the Arno. The rooms the Signora promised us in her\nletter would have looked over the Arno. The Signora had no business to\ndo it at all. Oh, it is a shame!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Any nook does for me, but it does seem hard
that you shouldn't have a view.
subQuotationList: ['Any nook does for me,', "but it does seem hard\nthat you shouldn't have a view."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Charlotte, you mustn't spoil me:
of course, you must look over the Arno, too. I meant that. The first
vacant room in the front--
subQuotationList: ["Charlotte, you mustn't spoil me:\nof course, you must look over the Arno, too. I meant that. The first\nvacant room in the front--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: You must have it,
subQuotationList: ['You must have it,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: No, no. You must have it.
subQuotationList: ['No, no. You must have it.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I insist on it. Your mother would never forgive me, Lucy.
subQuotationList: ['I insist on it. Your mother would never forgive me, Lucy.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: She would never forgive me.
subQuotationList: ['She would never forgive me.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I have a view, I have a view.
subQuotationList: ['I have a view, I have a view.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: A view? Oh, a view! How delightful a view is!
subQuotationList: ['A view? Oh, a view! How delightful a view is!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: she assumed a dazed expression when he spoke to her and then said

quoteText:
This is my son, his name's George. He has a view
too.
subQuotationList: ['This is my son,', "his name's George. He has a view\ntoo."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Ah,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
What I mean, is that you can have our rooms, and we'll
have yours. We'll change.
subQuotationList: ['What I mean,', "is that you can have our rooms, and we'll\nhave yours. We'll change."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Thank you very much indeed; that is out of the
question.
subQuotationList: ['Thank you very much indeed; that is out of the\nquestion.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett in reply opened her mouth as little as possible and said

quoteText: Why?
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Because it is quite out of the question, thank you.
subQuotationList: ['Because it is quite out of the question, thank you.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: You see, we don't like to take--
subQuotationList: ["You see, we don't like to take--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: But why? Women like looking at a view; men don't.
subQuotationList: ['But why?', "Women like looking at a view; men don't."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: George, persuade them!
subQuotationList: ['George, persuade them!']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
referringExpression: he thumped with his fists like a naughty child and turned to his son saying

quoteText:
It's so obvious they should have the rooms, There's
nothing else to say.
subQuotationList: ["It's so obvious they should have the rooms,", "There's\nnothing else to say."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Eat your dinner, dear,
subQuotationList: ['Eat your dinner, dear,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Eat your dinner, dear. This pension is a failure. To-morrow we will
make a change.
subQuotationList: ['Eat your dinner, dear. This pension is a failure. To-morrow we will\nmake a change.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Oh, oh! Why, it's
Mr. Beebe! Oh, how perfectly lovely! Oh, Charlotte, we must stop now,
however bad the rooms are. Oh!
subQuotationList: ["Oh, oh! Why, it's\nMr. Beebe! Oh, how perfectly lovely! Oh, Charlotte, we must stop now,\nhowever bad the rooms are. Oh!"]
speaker: Lucy
referringExpression: Lucy who had not yet acquired decency at once rose to her feet exclaiming

quoteText:
How do you do, Mr. Beebe? I expect that you have forgotten us: Miss
Bartlett and Miss Honeychurch, who were at Tunbridge Wells when you
helped the Vicar of St. Peter's that very cold Easter.
subQuotationList: ["How do you do, Mr. Beebe? I expect that you have forgotten us: Miss\nBartlett and Miss Honeychurch, who were at Tunbridge Wells when you\nhelped the Vicar of St. Peter's that very cold Easter."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionTextsList: [['you', 'Mr. Beebe', 'you', 'us', 'Miss\nBartlett', 'Miss Honeychurch', 'you', "the Vicar of St. Peter's"]]
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Beebe'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ["Vicar Of St. Peter'S"]]]

quoteText:
I AM so glad to see you, Just fancy how small the world is. Summer
Street, too, makes it so specially funny.
subQuotationList: ['I AM so glad to see you,', 'Just fancy how small the world is. Summer\nStreet, too, makes it so specially funny.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Miss Honeychurch lives in the parish of Summer Street, and she happened to tell me in the course
of conversation that you have just accepted the living--
subQuotationList: ['Miss Honeychurch lives in the parish of Summer Street,', 'and she happened to tell me in the course\nof conversation that you have just accepted the living--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Yes, I heard from mother so last week. She didn't know that I knew you
at Tunbridge Wells; but I wrote back at once, and I said: 'Mr. Beebe
is--'
subQuotationList: ["Yes, I heard from mother so last week. She didn't know that I knew you\nat Tunbridge Wells; but I wrote back at once, and I said: 'Mr. Beebe\nis--'"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Quite right, I move into the Rectory at Summer
Street next June. I am lucky to be appointed to such a charming
neighbourhood.
subQuotationList: ['Quite right,', 'I move into the Rectory at Summer\nStreet next June. I am lucky to be appointed to such a charming\nneighbourhood.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Oh, how glad I am! The name of our house is Windy Corner.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, how glad I am! The name of our house is Windy Corner.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
There is mother and me generally, and my brother, though it's not often
we get him to ch---- The church is rather far off, I mean.
subQuotationList: ["There is mother and me generally, and my brother, though it's not often\nwe get him to ch---- The church is rather far off, I mean."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy, dearest, let Mr. Beebe eat his dinner.
subQuotationList: ['Lucy, dearest, let Mr. Beebe eat his dinner.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I am eating it, thank you, and enjoying it.
subQuotationList: ['I am eating it, thank you, and enjoying it.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Don't neglect the country round, The first fine afternoon drive up to Fiesole, and round by
Settignano, or something of that sort.
subQuotationList: ["Don't neglect the country round,", 'The first fine afternoon drive up to Fiesole, and round by\nSettignano, or something of that sort.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
No! Mr. Beebe, you are
wrong. The first fine afternoon your ladies must go to Prato.
subQuotationList: ['No!', 'Mr. Beebe, you are\nwrong. The first fine afternoon your ladies must go to Prato.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
That lady looks so clever, We
are in luck.
subQuotationList: ['That lady looks so clever,', 'We\nare in luck.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: whispered Miss Bartlett to her cousin

quoteText:
Prato! They must go to Prato. That place is
too sweetly squalid for words. I love it; I revel in shaking off the
trammels of respectability, as you know.
subQuotationList: ['Prato! They must go to Prato. That place is\ntoo sweetly squalid for words. I love it; I revel in shaking off the\ntrammels of respectability, as you know.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
We are most grateful to you, The first evening means so much. When you arrived we were in for a
peculiarly mauvais quart d'heure.
subQuotationList: ['We are most grateful to you,', "The first evening means so much. When you arrived we were in for a\npeculiarly mauvais quart d'heure."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Do you, by any chance, know the name of an old man who sat opposite us
at dinner?
subQuotationList: ['Do you, by any chance, know the name of an old man who sat opposite us\nat dinner?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionTextsList: [['you', 'an old man who sat opposite us\nat dinner']]

quoteText: Emerson.
subQuotationList: ['Emerson.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Is he a friend of yours?
subQuotationList: ['Is he a friend of yours?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: We are friendly--as one is in pensions.
subQuotationList: ['We are friendly--as one is in pensions.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Then I will say no more.
subQuotationList: ['Then I will say no more.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I am, as it were, the chaperon of my young cousin,
Lucy, and it would be a serious thing if I put her under an obligation
to people of whom we know nothing. His manner was somewhat unfortunate.
I hope I acted for the best.
subQuotationList:
['I am, as it were,', 'the chaperon of my young cousin,
Lucy, and it would be a serious thing if I put her under an obligation
to people of whom we know nothing. His manner was somewhat unfortunate.
I hope I acted for the best.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: You acted very naturally,
subQuotationList: ['You acted very naturally,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
All the same, I don't think much harm would have
come of accepting.
subQuotationList: ["All the same, I don't think much harm would have\ncome of accepting."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: He seemed thoughtful and after a few moments added

quoteText: No harm, of course. But we could not be under an obligation.
subQuotationList: ['No harm, of course. But we could not be under an obligation.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
He is rather a peculiar man. I think he would not take advantage of your acceptance, nor expect you
to show gratitude. He has the merit--if it is one--of saying exactly
what he means. He has rooms he does not value, and he thinks you would
value them. He no more thought of putting you under an obligation than
he thought of being polite. It is so difficult--at least, I find it
difficult--to understand people who speak the truth.
subQuotationList:
['He is rather a peculiar man.', 'I think he would not take advantage of your acceptance, nor expect you
to show gratitude. He has the merit--if it is one--of saying exactly
what he means. He has rooms he does not value, and he thinks you would
value them. He no more thought of putting you under an obligation than
he thought of being polite. It is so difficult--at least, I find it
difficult--to understand people who speak the truth.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson']], [['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy']]]

quoteText:
I was hoping that he was nice; I do so
always hope that people will be nice.
subQuotationList: ['I was hoping that he was nice; I do so\nalways hope that people will be nice.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I think he is; nice and tiresome. I differ from him on almost every
point of any importance, and so, I expect--I may say I hope--you will
differ. But his is a type one disagrees with rather than deplores. When
he first came here he not unnaturally put people's backs up. He has no
tact and no manners--I don't mean by that that he has bad manners--and
he will not keep his opinions to himself. We nearly complained about
him to our depressing Signora, but I am glad to say we thought better of
it.
subQuotationList:
["I think he is; nice and tiresome. I differ from him on almost every
point of any importance, and so, I expect--I may say I hope--you will
differ. But his is a type one disagrees with rather than deplores. When
he first came here he not unnaturally put people's backs up. He has no
tact and no manners--I don't mean by that that he has bad manners--and
he will not keep his opinions to himself. We nearly complained about
him to our depressing Signora, but I am glad to say we thought better of
it."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Beebe', 'Miss Catherine Alan', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Signora Bertolini'], ['Mr. Beebe', 'Miss Catherine Alan', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

quoteText: Am I to conclude, that he is a Socialist?
subQuotationList: ['Am I to conclude,', 'that he is a Socialist?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: And presumably he has brought up his son to be a Socialist, too?
subQuotationList: ['And presumably he has brought up his son to be a Socialist, too?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I hardly know George, for he hasn't learnt to talk yet. He seems a nice
creature, and I think he has brains. Of course, he has all his father's
mannerisms, and it is quite possible that he, too, may be a Socialist.
subQuotationList: ["I hardly know George, for he hasn't learnt to talk yet. He seems a nice\ncreature, and I think he has brains. Of course, he has all his father's\nmannerisms, and it is quite possible that he, too, may be a Socialist."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Oh, you relieve me, So you think I ought to
have accepted their offer? You feel I have been narrow-minded and
suspicious?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, you relieve me,', 'So you think I ought to\nhave accepted their offer? You feel I have been narrow-minded and\nsuspicious?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Not at all, I never suggested that.
subQuotationList: ['Not at all,', 'I never suggested that.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: But ought I not to apologize, at all events, for my apparent rudeness?
subQuotationList: ['But ought I not to apologize, at all events, for my apparent rudeness?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Was I a bore? Why
didn't you talk, Lucy? He prefers young people, I'm sure. I do hope I
haven't monopolized him. I hoped you would have him all the evening, as
well as all dinner-time.
subQuotationList:
['Was I a bore?', "Why
didn't you talk, Lucy? He prefers young people, I'm sure. I do hope I
haven't monopolized him. I hoped you would have him all the evening, as
well as all dinner-time."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
He is nice, Just what I remember. He seems to see
good in everyone. No one would take him for a clergyman.
subQuotationList: ['He is nice,', 'Just what I remember. He seems to see\ngood in everyone. No one would take him for a clergyman.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: My dear Lucia--
subQuotationList: ['My dear Lucia--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Well, you know what I mean. And you know how clergymen generally laugh;
Mr. Beebe laughs just like an ordinary man.
subQuotationList: ['Well, you know what I mean. And you know how clergymen generally laugh;\nMr. Beebe laughs just like an ordinary man.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Funny girl! How you do remind me of your mother. I wonder if she will
approve of Mr. Beebe.
subQuotationList: ['Funny girl! How you do remind me of your mother. I wonder if she will\napprove of Mr. Beebe.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I'm sure she will; and so will Freddy.
subQuotationList: ["I'm sure she will; and so will Freddy."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I think everyone at Windy Corner will approve; it is the fashionable
world. I am used to Tunbridge Wells, where we are all hopelessly behind
the times.
subQuotationList: ['I think everyone at Windy Corner will approve; it is the fashionable\nworld. I am used to Tunbridge Wells, where we are all hopelessly behind\nthe times.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Yes,
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I am
afraid you are finding me a very depressing companion.
subQuotationList: ['I am\nafraid you are finding me a very depressing companion.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett sedulously denied disapproving of any one and added

quoteText:
I must have been selfish or unkind; I must
be more careful. It is so dreadful for Charlotte, being poor.
subQuotationList: ['I must have been selfish or unkind; I must\nbe more careful. It is so dreadful for Charlotte, being poor.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
But here you are as safe as in England. Signora Bertolini is so
English.
subQuotationList: ['But here you are as safe as in England. Signora Bertolini is so\nEnglish.']
speaker: The Little Old Lady

quoteText: Yet our rooms smell, We dread going to bed.
subQuotationList: ['Yet our rooms smell,', 'We dread going to bed.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Ah, then you look into the court.
subQuotationList: ['Ah, then you look into the court.']
speaker: The Little Old Lady

quoteText:
If only Mr. Emerson was
more tactful! We were so sorry for you at dinner.
subQuotationList: ['If only Mr. Emerson was\nmore tactful! We were so sorry for you at dinner.']
speaker: The Little Old Lady

quoteText: I think he was meaning to be kind.
subQuotationList: ['I think he was meaning to be kind.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Undoubtedly he was,
subQuotationList: ['Undoubtedly he was,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Mr. Beebe has just been scolding me for my suspicious nature. Of
course, I was holding back on my cousin's account.
subQuotationList: ["Mr. Beebe has just been scolding me for my suspicious nature. Of\ncourse, I was holding back on my cousin's account."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
About old Mr. Emerson--I hardly know. No, he is not tactful; yet, have
you ever noticed that there are people who do things which are most
indelicate, and yet at the same time--beautiful?
subQuotationList: ['About old Mr. Emerson--I hardly know. No, he is not tactful; yet, have\nyou ever noticed that there are people who do things which are most\nindelicate, and yet at the same time--beautiful?']
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'The Little Old Lady']]]

quoteText:
Beautiful? Are not beauty
and delicacy the same?
subQuotationList: ['Beautiful?', 'Are not beauty\nand delicacy the same?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
So one would have thought, But things are
so difficult, I sometimes think.
subQuotationList: ['So one would have thought,', 'But things are\nso difficult, I sometimes think.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Miss Bartlett, it's all right about the rooms. I'm so glad.
Mr. Emerson was talking about it in the smoking-room, and knowing what
I did, I encouraged him to make the offer again. He has let me come and
ask you. He would be so pleased.
subQuotationList:
['Miss Bartlett,', "it's all right about the rooms. I'm so glad.
Mr. Emerson was talking about it in the smoking-room, and knowing what
I did, I encouraged him to make the offer again. He has let me come and
ask you. He would be so pleased."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Bartlett']], [['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Oh, Charlotte, we must have the rooms now.
The old man is just as nice and kind as he can be.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Charlotte,', 'we must have the rooms now.\nThe old man is just as nice and kind as he can be.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I fear, that I have been officious. I
must apologize for my interference.
subQuotationList: ['I fear,', 'that I have been officious. I\nmust apologize for my interference.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
My own wishes, dearest Lucy, are unimportant in comparison with
yours. It would be hard indeed if I stopped you doing as you liked at
Florence, when I am only here through your kindness. If you wish me to
turn these gentlemen out of their rooms, I will do it. Would you then,
Mr. Beebe, kindly tell Mr. Emerson that I accept his kind offer, and
then conduct him to me, in order that I may thank him personally?
subQuotationList:
['My own wishes, dearest Lucy, are unimportant in comparison with
yours. It would be hard indeed if I stopped you doing as you liked at
Florence, when I am only here through your kindness. If you wish me to
turn these gentlemen out of their rooms, I will do it. Would you then,
Mr. Beebe, kindly tell Mr. Emerson that I accept his kind offer, and
then conduct him to me, in order that I may thank him personally?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Remember, Lucy, I alone am implicated in this. I do not wish the
acceptance to come from you. Grant me that, at all events.
subQuotationList: ['Remember, Lucy, I alone am implicated in this. I do not wish the\nacceptance to come from you. Grant me that, at all events.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Mr. Emerson is engaged, but here is his son instead.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Emerson is engaged, but here is his son instead.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
My father, is in his bath, so you cannot thank him
personally. But any message given by you to me will be given by me to
him as soon as he comes out.
subQuotationList: ['My father,', 'is in his bath, so you cannot thank him\npersonally. But any message given by you to me will be given by me to\nhim as soon as he comes out.']
speaker: George Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson']], [['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText: Poor young man!
subQuotationList: ['Poor young man!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
How angry he is with his father about the rooms! It is all he can do to
keep polite.
subQuotationList: ['How angry he is with his father about the rooms! It is all he can do to\nkeep polite.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: In half an hour or so your rooms will be ready,
subQuotationList: ['In half an hour or so your rooms will be ready,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I think one might venture now. No, Lucy, do not stir. I will
superintend the move.
subQuotationList: ['I think one might venture now. No, Lucy, do not stir. I will\nsuperintend the move.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett rose with a sigh and said

quoteText: How you do do everything,
subQuotationList: ['How you do do everything,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Naturally, dear. It is my affair.
subQuotationList: ['Naturally, dear. It is my affair.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: But I would like to help you.
subQuotationList: ['But I would like to help you.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: No, dear.
subQuotationList: ['No, dear.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I want to explain, why it is that I have taken
the largest room. Naturally, of course, I should have given it to you;
but I happen to know that it belongs to the young man, and I was sure
your mother would not like it.
subQuotationList:
['I want to explain,', 'why it is that I have taken
the largest room. Naturally, of course, I should have given it to you;
but I happen to know that it belongs to the young man, and I was sure
your mother would not like it.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
If you are to accept a favour it is more suitable you should be under
an obligation to his father than to him. I am a woman of the world, in
my small way, and I know where things lead to. However, Mr. Beebe is a
guarantee of a sort that they will not presume on this.
subQuotationList:
['If you are to accept a favour it is more suitable you should be under
an obligation to his father than to him. I am a woman of the world, in
my small way, and I know where things lead to. However, Mr. Beebe is a
guarantee of a sort that they will not presume on this.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Mother wouldn't mind I'm sure,
subQuotationList: ["Mother wouldn't mind I'm sure,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What does it mean?
subQuotationList: ['What does it mean?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
If it is Mrs. Grundy who is troubling you, I do assure you that you
can neglect the good person. Being English, Miss Honeychurch will be
perfectly safe. Italians understand. A dear friend of mine, Contessa
Baroncelli, has two daughters, and when she cannot send a maid to school
with them, she lets them go in sailor-hats instead. Every one takes
them for English, you see, especially if their hair is strained tightly
behind.
subQuotationList:
['If it is Mrs. Grundy who is troubling you, I do assure you that you
can neglect the good person. Being English, Miss Honeychurch will be
perfectly safe. Italians understand. A dear friend of mine, Contessa
Baroncelli, has two daughters, and when she cannot send a maid to school
with them, she lets them go in sailor-hats instead. Every one takes
them for English, you see, especially if their hair is strained tightly
behind.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
I will take you by a dear dirty back way, Miss Honeychurch, and if you
bring me luck, we shall have an adventure.
subQuotationList: ['I will take you by a dear dirty back way, Miss Honeychurch, and if you\nbring me luck, we shall have an adventure.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Tut, tut! Miss Lucy! I hope we shall soon emancipate you from Baedeker.
He does but touch the surface of things. As to the true Italy--he does
not even dream of it. The true Italy is only to be found by patient
observation.
subQuotationList:
['Tut, tut! Miss Lucy! I hope we shall soon emancipate you from Baedeker.
He does but touch the surface of things. As to the true Italy--he does
not even dream of it. The true Italy is only to be found by patient
observation.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
A smell! a true Florentine smell! Every city, let me teach you, has its
own smell.
subQuotationList: ['A smell! a true Florentine smell! Every city, let me teach you, has its\nown smell.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Is it a very nice smell?
subQuotationList: ['Is it a very nice smell?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: One doesn't come to Italy for niceness,
subQuotationList: ["One doesn't come to Italy for niceness,"]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
one comes for
life. Buon giorno! Buon giorno!
subQuotationList: ['one comes for\nlife. Buon giorno! Buon giorno!']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Look at that
adorable wine-cart! How the driver stares at us, dear, simple soul!
subQuotationList: ['Look at that\nadorable wine-cart! How the driver stares at us, dear, simple soul!']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Buon giorno! Take the word of an old woman, Miss Lucy: you will
never repent of a little civility to your inferiors. That is the
true democracy. Though I am a real Radical as well. There, now you're
shocked.
subQuotationList:
["Buon giorno! Take the word of an old woman, Miss Lucy: you will
never repent of a little civility to your inferiors. That is the
true democracy. Though I am a real Radical as well. There, now you're
shocked."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Indeed, I'm not! We are Radicals, too, out and out.
My father always voted for Mr. Gladstone, until he was so dreadful about
Ireland.
subQuotationList: ["Indeed, I'm not!", 'We are Radicals, too, out and out.\nMy father always voted for Mr. Gladstone, until he was so dreadful about\nIreland.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I see, I see. And now you have gone over to the enemy.
subQuotationList: ['I see, I see. And now you have gone over to the enemy.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Oh, please--! If my father was alive, I am sure he would vote Radical
again now that Ireland is all right. And as it is, the glass over our
front door was broken last election, and Freddy is sure it was the
Tories; but mother says nonsense, a tramp.
subQuotationList:
['Oh, please--! If my father was alive, I am sure he would vote Radical
again now that Ireland is all right. And as it is, the glass over our
front door was broken last election, and Freddy is sure it was the
Tories; but mother says nonsense, a tramp.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Shameful! A manufacturing district, I suppose?
subQuotationList: ['Shameful! A manufacturing district, I suppose?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
No--in the Surrey hills. About five miles from Dorking, looking over
the Weald.
subQuotationList: ['No--in the Surrey hills. About five miles from Dorking, looking over\nthe Weald.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
What a delightful part; I know it so well. It is full of the very
nicest people. Do you know Sir Harry Otway--a Radical if ever there
was?
subQuotationList: ['What a delightful part; I know it so well. It is full of the very\nnicest people. Do you know Sir Harry Otway--a Radical if ever there\nwas?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Very well indeed.
subQuotationList: ['Very well indeed.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And old Mrs. Butterworth the philanthropist?
subQuotationList: ['And old Mrs. Butterworth the philanthropist?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Why, she rents a field of us! How funny!
subQuotationList: ['Why, she rents a field of us! How funny!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, you
have property in Surrey?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, you\nhave property in Surrey?']
speaker: Miss Lavish
referringExpression: Miss Lavish looked at the narrow ribbon of sky and murmured

quoteText:
Hardly any, Only thirty
acres--just the garden, all downhill, and some fields.
subQuotationList: ['Hardly any,', 'Only thirty\nacres--just the garden, all downhill, and some fields.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Bless us! Bless us and save us! We've lost the way.
subQuotationList: ["Bless us! Bless us and save us! We've lost the way."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Lost! lost! My dear Miss Lucy, during our political diatribes we have
taken a wrong turning. How those horrid Conservatives would jeer at us!
What are we to do? Two lone females in an unknown town. Now, this is
what I call an adventure.
subQuotationList:
['Lost! lost! My dear Miss Lucy, during our political diatribes we have
taken a wrong turning. How those horrid Conservatives would jeer at us!
What are we to do? Two lone females in an unknown town. Now, this is
what I call an adventure.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Oh, but that is the word of a craven! And no, you are not, not, NOT to
look at your Baedeker. Give it to me; I shan't let you carry it. We will
simply drift.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, but that is the word of a craven! And no, you are not, not, NOT to\nlook at your Baedeker. Give it to me; I shan't let you carry it. We will\nsimply drift."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Stop a minute; let those two people go on, or I shall have to speak to
them. I do detest conventional intercourse. Nasty! they are going into
the church, too. Oh, the Britisher abroad!
subQuotationList: ['Stop a minute; let those two people go on, or I shall have to speak to\nthem. I do detest conventional intercourse. Nasty! they are going into\nthe church, too. Oh, the Britisher abroad!']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
We sat opposite them at dinner last night. They have given us their
rooms. They were so very kind.
subQuotationList: ['We sat opposite them at dinner last night. They have given us their\nrooms. They were so very kind.']
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Look at their figures! They walk through my
Italy like a pair of cows. It's very naughty of me, but I would like
to set an examination paper at Dover, and turn back every tourist who
couldn't pass it.
subQuotationList:
['Look at their figures!', "They walk through my
Italy like a pair of cows. It's very naughty of me, but I would like
to set an examination paper at Dover, and turn back every tourist who
couldn't pass it."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: What would you ask us?
subQuotationList: ['What would you ask us?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: There goes my local-colour box! I must have a word with him!
subQuotationList: ['There goes my local-colour box! I must have a word with him!']
speaker: Miss Lavish
referringExpression: Miss Lavish stopped squeaked flung up her arms and cried

quoteText:
Hateful bishop! Hard in life, hard in death. Go out into the sunshine,
little boy, and kiss your hand to the sun, for that is where you ought
to be. Intolerable bishop!
subQuotationList: ['Hateful bishop!', 'Hard in life, hard in death. Go out into the sunshine,\nlittle boy, and kiss your hand to the sun, for that is where you ought\nto be. Intolerable bishop!']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
referringExpression: exclaimed the voice of old Mr Emerson

quoteText:
Look at him! Here's a mess: a baby hurt,
cold, and frightened! But what else can you expect from a church?
subQuotationList: ['Look at him!', "Here's a mess: a baby hurt,\ncold, and frightened! But what else can you expect from a church?"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
You are a clever woman, You have done more than
all the relics in the world. I am not of your creed, but I do believe in
those who make their fellow-creatures happy. There is no scheme of the
universe--
subQuotationList:
['You are a clever woman,', 'You have done more than
all the relics in the world. I am not of your creed, but I do believe in
those who make their fellow-creatures happy. There is no scheme of the
universe--']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Niente,
subQuotationList: ['Niente,']
speaker: Italian Lady

quoteText: I'm not sure she understands English,
subQuotationList: ["I'm not sure she understands English,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
That woman understands everything, But what
are you doing here? Are you doing the church? Are you through with the
church?
subQuotationList: ['That woman understands everything,', 'But what\nare you doing here? Are you doing the church? Are you through with the\nchurch?']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
No, I came here with Miss
Lavish, who was to explain everything; and just by the door--it is too
bad!--she simply ran away, and after waiting quite a time, I had to come
in by myself.
subQuotationList:
['No,', 'I came here with Miss
Lavish, who was to explain everything; and just by the door--it is too
bad!--she simply ran away, and after waiting quite a time, I had to come
in by myself.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Why shouldn't you?
subQuotationList: ["Why shouldn't you?"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Yes, why shouldn't you come by yourself?
subQuotationList: ["Yes, why shouldn't you come by yourself?"]
speaker: George Emerson
referringExpression: the son addressing the young lady

quoteText: But Miss Lavish has even taken away Baedeker.
subQuotationList: ['But Miss Lavish has even taken away Baedeker.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Baedeker? I'm glad it's THAT you minded. It's worth
minding, the loss of a Baedeker. THAT'S worth minding.
subQuotationList: ['Baedeker?', "I'm glad it's THAT you minded. It's worth\nminding, the loss of a Baedeker. THAT'S worth minding."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: If you've no Baedeker, you'd better join us.
subQuotationList: ["If you've no Baedeker,", "you'd better join us."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Thank you very much, but I could not think of that. I hope you do not
suppose that I came to join on to you. I really came to help with the
child, and to thank you for so kindly giving us your rooms last night. I
hope that you have not been put to any great inconvenience.
subQuotationList:
['Thank you very much, but I could not think of that. I hope you do not
suppose that I came to join on to you. I really came to help with the
child, and to thank you for so kindly giving us your rooms last night. I
hope that you have not been put to any great inconvenience.']
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText:
My dear, I think that you are repeating what
you have heard older people say. You are pretending to be touchy; but
you are not really. Stop being so tiresome, and tell me instead what
part of the church you want to see. To take you to it will be a real
pleasure.
subQuotationList:
['My dear,', 'I think that you are repeating what
you have heard older people say. You are pretending to be touchy; but
you are not really. Stop being so tiresome, and tell me instead what
part of the church you want to see. To take you to it will be a real
pleasure.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
I am not touchy, I hope. It is the Giottos that I want to see, if you
will kindly tell me which they are.
subQuotationList: ['I am not touchy, I hope. It is the Giottos that I want to see, if you\nwill kindly tell me which they are.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Remember, the facts about this church of Santa Croce;
how it was built by faith in the full fervour of medievalism, before
any taint of the Renaissance had appeared. Observe how Giotto in these
frescoes--now, unhappily, ruined by restoration--is untroubled by the
snares of anatomy and perspective. Could anything be more majestic, more
pathetic, beautiful, true? How little, we feel, avails knowledge and
technical cleverness against a man who truly feels!
subQuotationList:
['Remember,', 'the facts about this church of Santa Croce;
how it was built by faith in the full fervour of medievalism, before
any taint of the Renaissance had appeared. Observe how Giotto in these
frescoes--now, unhappily, ruined by restoration--is untroubled by the
snares of anatomy and perspective. Could anything be more majestic, more
pathetic, beautiful, true? How little, we feel, avails knowledge and
technical cleverness against a man who truly feels!']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
No! Remember nothing of the sort! Built by faith indeed! That simply means
the workmen weren't paid properly. And as for the frescoes, I see no
truth in them. Look at that fat man in blue! He must weigh as much as I
do, and he is shooting into the sky like an air balloon.
subQuotationList:
['No!', "Remember nothing of the sort! Built by faith indeed! That simply means
the workmen weren't paid properly. And as for the frescoes, I see no
truth in them. Look at that fat man in blue! He must weigh as much as I
do, and he is shooting into the sky like an air balloon."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Now, did this happen, or didn't it? Yes or no?
subQuotationList: ["Now, did this happen, or didn't it? Yes or no?"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
It happened like this, if it happened at all. I would rather go up to
heaven by myself than be pushed by cherubs; and if I got there I should
like my friends to lean out of it, just as they do here.
subQuotationList: ['It happened like this, if it happened at all. I would rather go up to\nheaven by myself than be pushed by cherubs; and if I got there I should\nlike my friends to lean out of it, just as they do here.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
You will never go up, You and I, dear boy, will
lie at peace in the earth that bore us, and our names will disappear as
surely as our work survives.
subQuotationList: ['You will never go up,', 'You and I, dear boy, will\nlie at peace in the earth that bore us, and our names will disappear as\nsurely as our work survives.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson']], [['George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Some of the people can only see the empty grave, not the saint, whoever
he is, going up. It did happen like that, if it happened at all.
subQuotationList: ['Some of the people can only see the empty grave, not the saint, whoever\nhe is, going up. It did happen like that, if it happened at all.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Pardon me, The chapel is somewhat small for two
parties. We will incommode you no longer.
subQuotationList: ['Pardon me,', 'The chapel is somewhat small for two\nparties. We will incommode you no longer.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Miss Catherine Alan', 'Ms. Teresa', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lucy', 'George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText: Stop! There's plenty of room for us all. Stop!
subQuotationList: ['Stop!', "There's plenty of room for us all. Stop!"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Catherine Alan', 'Ms. Teresa']]]

quoteText: George, I do believe that clergyman is the Brixton curate.
subQuotationList: ['George, I do believe that clergyman is the Brixton curate.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Perhaps he is. I
don't remember.
subQuotationList: ["Perhaps he is. I\ndon't remember."]
speaker: George Emerson
referringExpression: George went into the next chapel and returned saying

quoteText:
Then I had better speak to him and remind him who I am. It's that Mr.
Eager. Why did he go? Did we talk too loud? How vexatious. I shall go
and say we are sorry. Hadn't I better? Then perhaps he will come back.
subQuotationList: ["Then I had better speak to him and remind him who I am. It's that Mr.\nEager. Why did he go? Did we talk too loud? How vexatious. I shall go\nand say we are sorry. Hadn't I better? Then perhaps he will come back."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

quoteText: He will not come back,
subQuotationList: ['He will not come back,']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
My father has that effect on nearly everyone, He
will try to be kind.
subQuotationList: ['My father has that effect on nearly everyone,', 'He\nwill try to be kind.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I hope we all try,
subQuotationList: ['I hope we all try,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Because we think it improves our characters. But he is kind to people
because he loves them; and they find him out, and are offended, or
frightened.
subQuotationList: ['Because we think it improves our characters. But he is kind to people\nbecause he loves them; and they find him out, and are offended, or\nfrightened.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
How silly of them! I
think that a kind action done tactfully--
subQuotationList: ['How silly of them!', 'I\nthink that a kind action done tactfully--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Tact!
subQuotationList: ['Tact!']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Were you snubbed?
subQuotationList: ['Were you snubbed?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
But we have spoilt the pleasure of I don't know how many people. They
won't come back.
subQuotationList: ["But we have spoilt the pleasure of I don't know how many people. They\nwon't come back."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Catherine Alan', 'Ms. Teresa']]]

quoteText:
...full of innate sympathy...quickness to perceive good in
others...vision of the brotherhood of man...
subQuotationList: ['...full of innate sympathy...quickness to perceive good in\nothers...vision of the brotherhood of man...']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Don't let us spoil yours, Have you looked at
those saints?
subQuotationList: ["Don't let us spoil yours,", 'Have you looked at\nthose saints?']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Yes, They are lovely. Do you know which is the tombstone
that is praised in Ruskin?
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', 'They are lovely. Do you know which is the tombstone\nthat is praised in Ruskin?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Why will he look at that fresco? I saw nothing in
it.
subQuotationList: ['Why will he look at that fresco?', 'I saw nothing in\nit.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
I like Giotto, It is so wonderful what they say about
his tactile values. Though I like things like the Della Robbia babies
better.
subQuotationList: ['I like Giotto,', 'It is so wonderful what they say about\nhis tactile values. Though I like things like the Della Robbia babies\nbetter.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
So you ought. A baby is worth a dozen saints. And my baby's worth the
whole of Paradise, and as far as I can see he lives in Hell.
subQuotationList: ["So you ought. A baby is worth a dozen saints. And my baby's worth the\nwhole of Paradise, and as far as I can see he lives in Hell."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: In Hell, He's unhappy.
subQuotationList: ['In Hell,', "He's unhappy."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Oh, dear!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, dear!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
How can he be unhappy when he is strong and alive? What more is one
to give him? And think how he has been brought up--free from all the
superstition and ignorance that lead men to hate one another in the name
of God. With such an education as that, I thought he was bound to grow
up happy.
subQuotationList:
['How can he be unhappy when he is strong and alive? What more is one
to give him? And think how he has been brought up--free from all the
superstition and ignorance that lead men to hate one another in the name
of God. With such an education as that, I thought he was bound to grow
up happy.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
What are we to do with him? He comes out for his holiday to
Italy, and behaves--like that; like the little child who ought to have
been playing, and who hurt himself upon the tombstone. Eh? What did you
say?
subQuotationList:
['What are we to do with him?', 'He comes out for his holiday to
Italy, and behaves--like that; like the little child who ought to have
been playing, and who hurt himself upon the tombstone. Eh? What did you
say?']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Now don't be stupid over this. I don't require you to fall in love with
my boy, but I do think you might try and understand him. You are nearer
his age, and if you let yourself go I am sure you are sensible. You
might help me. He has known so few women, and you have the time.
You stop here several weeks, I suppose? But let yourself go. You are
inclined to get muddled, if I may judge from last night. Let yourself
go. Pull out from the depths those thoughts that you do not understand,
and spread them out in the sunlight and know the meaning of them. By
understanding George you may learn to understand yourself. It will be
good for both of you.
subQuotationList:
["Now don't be stupid over this. I don't require you to fall in love with
my boy, but I do think you might try and understand him. You are nearer
his age, and if you let yourself go I am sure you are sensible. You
might help me. He has known so few women, and you have the time.
You stop here several weeks, I suppose? But let yourself go. You are
inclined to get muddled, if I may judge from last night. Let yourself
go. Pull out from the depths those thoughts that you do not understand,
and spread them out in the sunlight and know the meaning of them. By
understanding George you may learn to understand yourself. It will be
good for both of you."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: I only know what it is that's wrong with him; not why it is.
subQuotationList: ["I only know what it is that's wrong with him; not why it is."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: And what is it?
subQuotationList: ['And what is it?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The old trouble; things won't fit.
subQuotationList: ["The old trouble; things won't fit."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: What things?
subQuotationList: ['What things?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The things of the universe. It is quite true. They don't.
subQuotationList: ["The things of the universe. It is quite true. They don't."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: Oh, Mr. Emerson, whatever do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Mr. Emerson, whatever do you mean?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
George and I both know this, but why does it distress him? We know that
we come from the winds, and that we shall return to them; that all life
is perhaps a knot, a tangle, a blemish in the eternal smoothness. But
why should this make us unhappy? Let us rather love one another, and
work and rejoice. I don't believe in this world sorrow.
subQuotationList:
["George and I both know this, but why does it distress him? We know that
we come from the winds, and that we shall return to them; that all life
is perhaps a knot, a tangle, a blemish in the eternal smoothness. But
why should this make us unhappy? Let us rather love one another, and
work and rejoice. I don't believe in this world sorrow."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Then make my boy think like us. Make him realize that by the side of
the everlasting Why there is a Yes--a transitory Yes if you like, but a
Yes.
subQuotationList: ['Then make my boy think like us. Make him realize that by the side of\nthe everlasting Why there is a Yes--a transitory Yes if you like, but a\nYes.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: I'm very sorry, You'll think me unfeeling, but--but--
subQuotationList: ["I'm very sorry,", "You'll think me unfeeling, but--but--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, but your son wants employment. Has he no
particular hobby? Why, I myself have worries, but I can generally forget
them at the piano; and collecting stamps did no end of good for my
brother. Perhaps Italy bores him; you ought to try the Alps or the
Lakes.
subQuotationList:
['Oh, but your son wants employment. Has he no
particular hobby? Why, I myself have worries, but I can generally forget
them at the piano; and collecting stamps did no end of good for my
brother. Perhaps Italy bores him; you ought to try the Alps or the
Lakes.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Miss Bartlett.
subQuotationList: ['Miss Bartlett.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Oh, good gracious me! Where? Where?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, good gracious me!', 'Where? Where?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: In the nave.
subQuotationList: ['In the nave.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I see. Those gossiping little Miss Alans must have--
subQuotationList: ['I see. Those gossiping little Miss Alans must have--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Poor girl! Poor girl!
subQuotationList: ['Poor girl!', 'Poor girl!']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Poor girl? I fail to understand the point of that remark. I think
myself a very fortunate girl, I assure you. I'm thoroughly happy, and
having a splendid time. Pray don't waste time mourning over me. There's
enough sorrow in the world, isn't there, without trying to invent it.
Good-bye. Thank you both so much for all your kindness. Ah, yes! there
does come my cousin. A delightful morning! Santa Croce is a wonderful
church.
subQuotationList:
["Poor girl? I fail to understand the point of that remark. I think
myself a very fortunate girl, I assure you. I'm thoroughly happy, and
having a splendid time. Pray don't waste time mourning over me. There's
enough sorrow in the world, isn't there, without trying to invent it.
Good-bye. Thank you both so much for all your kindness. Ah, yes! there
does come my cousin. A delightful morning! Santa Croce is a wonderful
church."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Who is she?
subQuotationList: ['Who is she?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Cousin of one of my parishioners. I do not consider her choice of a
piece happy. Beethoven is so usually simple and direct in his appeal
that it is sheer perversity to choose a thing like that, which, if
anything, disturbs.
subQuotationList:
['Cousin of one of my parishioners. I do not consider her choice of a
piece happy. Beethoven is so usually simple and direct in his appeal
that it is sheer perversity to choose a thing like that, which, if
anything, disturbs.']
speaker: The Vicar

quoteText: Introduce me.
subQuotationList: ['Introduce me.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
She will be delighted. She and Miss Bartlett are full of the praises of
your sermon.
subQuotationList: ['She will be delighted. She and Miss Bartlett are full of the praises of\nyour sermon.']
speaker: The Vicar

quoteText: My sermon? Why ever did she listen to it?
subQuotationList: ['My sermon?', 'Why ever did she listen to it?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
If Miss Honeychurch ever takes to live as she plays, it will be very
exciting both for us and for her.
subQuotationList: ['If Miss Honeychurch ever takes to live as she plays, it will be very\nexciting both for us and for her.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: he made a remark to the vicar which he now made to Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, what a funny thing! Some one said just the same to mother, and she
said she trusted I should never live a duet.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, what a funny thing! Some one said just the same to mother, and she\nsaid she trusted I should never live a duet.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Doesn't Mrs. Honeychurch like music?
subQuotationList: ["Doesn't Mrs. Honeychurch like music?"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
She doesn't mind it. But she doesn't like one to get excited over
anything; she thinks I am silly about it. She thinks--I can't make
out. Once, you know, I said that I liked my own playing better than any
one's. She has never got over it. Of course, I didn't mean that I played
well; I only meant--
subQuotationList:
["She doesn't mind it. But she doesn't like one to get excited over
anything; she thinks I am silly about it. She thinks--I can't make
out. Once, you know, I said that I liked my own playing better than any
one's. She has never got over it. Of course, I didn't mean that I played
well; I only meant--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Of course,
subQuotationList: ['Of course,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Music--
subQuotationList: ['Music--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What about music?
subQuotationList: ['What about music?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Poor Charlotte will be sopped,
subQuotationList: ['Poor Charlotte will be sopped,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Miss Lavish has led your cousin astray. She hopes to find the true
Italy in the wet I believe.
subQuotationList: ['Miss Lavish has led your cousin astray. She hopes to find the true\nItaly in the wet I believe.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Miss Lavish is so original,
subQuotationList: ['Miss Lavish is so original,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Is it true, that Miss Lavish is
writing a book?
subQuotationList: ['Is it true,', 'that Miss Lavish is\nwriting a book?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: They do say so.
subQuotationList: ['They do say so.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: What is it about?
subQuotationList: ['What is it about?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It will be a novel, dealing with modern Italy.
Let me refer you for an account to Miss Catharine Alan, who uses words
herself more admirably than any one I know.
subQuotationList: ['It will be a novel,', 'dealing with modern Italy.\nLet me refer you for an account to Miss Catharine Alan, who uses words\nherself more admirably than any one I know.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I wish Miss Lavish would tell me herself. We started such friends. But
I don't think she ought to have run away with Baedeker that morning in
Santa Croce. Charlotte was most annoyed at finding me practically alone,
and so I couldn't help being a little annoyed with Miss Lavish.
subQuotationList:
["I wish Miss Lavish would tell me herself. We started such friends. But
I don't think she ought to have run away with Baedeker that morning in
Santa Croce. Charlotte was most annoyed at finding me practically alone,
and so I couldn't help being a little annoyed with Miss Lavish."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The two ladies, at all events, have made it up.
subQuotationList: ['The two ladies, at all events, have made it up.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, dear Miss Honeychurch, you will catch a chill! And Mr. Beebe here
besides. Who would suppose this is Italy? There is my sister actually
nursing the hot-water can; no comforts or proper provisions.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, dear Miss Honeychurch, you will catch a chill! And Mr. Beebe here\nbesides. Who would suppose this is Italy? There is my sister actually\nnursing the hot-water can; no comforts or proper provisions.']
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
I could hear your beautiful playing, Miss Honeychurch, though I was in
my room with the door shut. Doors shut; indeed, most necessary. No one
has the least idea of privacy in this country. And one person catches it
from another.
subQuotationList:
['I could hear your beautiful playing, Miss Honeychurch, though I was in
my room with the door shut. Doors shut; indeed, most necessary. No one
has the least idea of privacy in this country. And one person catches it
from another.']
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText: Fa niente, sono vecchia.
subQuotationList: ['Fa niente, sono vecchia.']
speaker: The Chambermaid
referringExpression: the chambermaid burst in upon him in his bath exclaiming

quoteText:
I quite agree with you, Miss Alan. The Italians
are a most unpleasant people. They pry everywhere, they see everything,
and they know what we want before we know it ourselves. We are at their
mercy. They read our thoughts, they foretell our desires. From the
cab-driver down to--to Giotto, they turn us inside out, and I resent
it. Yet in their heart of hearts they are--how superficial! They have no
conception of the intellectual life. How right is Signora Bertolini, who
exclaimed to me the other day:
subQuotationList:
['I quite agree with you, Miss Alan. The Italians
are a most unpleasant people. They pry everywhere, they see everything,
and they know what we want before we know it ourselves. We are at their
mercy. They read our thoughts, they foretell our desires. From the

it. Yet in their heart of hearts they are--how superficial! They have no
conception of the intellectual life. How right is Signora Bertolini, who

speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Catherine Alan'], ['Miss Catherine Alan'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe']]]

quoteText:
That belongs to Lavish. A good fellow, Lavish,
but I wish she'd start a pipe.
subQuotationList: ['That belongs to Lavish.', "A good fellow, Lavish,\nbut I wish she'd start a pipe."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, Mr. Beebe, Indeed,
though it is dreadful for her to smoke, it is not quite as dreadful as
you suppose. She took to it, practically in despair, after her
life's work was carried away in a landslip. Surely that makes it more
excusable.
subQuotationList:
['Oh, Mr. Beebe,', "Indeed,
though it is dreadful for her to smoke, it is not quite as dreadful as
you suppose. She took to it, practically in despair, after her
life's work was carried away in a landslip. Surely that makes it more
excusable."]
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText: What was that?
subQuotationList: ['What was that?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It was
a novel--and I am afraid, from what I can gather, not a very nice novel.
It is so sad when people who have abilities misuse them, and I must say
they nearly always do. Anyhow, she left it almost finished in the Grotto
of the Calvary at the Capuccini Hotel at Amalfi while she went for a
little ink. She said: But you know
what Italians are, and meanwhile the Grotto fell roaring on to the
beach, and the saddest thing of all is that she cannot remember what she
has written. The poor thing was very ill after it, and so got tempted
into cigarettes. It is a great secret, but I am glad to say that she is
writing another novel. She told Teresa and Miss Pole the other day that
she had got up all the local colour--this novel is to be about modern
Italy; the other was historical--but that she could not start till she
had an idea. First she tried Perugia for an inspiration, then she came
here--this must on no account get round. And so cheerful through it all!
I cannot help thinking that there is something to admire in everyone,
even if you do not approve of them.
subQuotationList:
['It was

speaker: Miss Catherine Alan
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish']], [['Lucy'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Pole'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish']]]

quoteText:
All the same, she is a little too--I hardly like to say unwomanly, but
she behaved most strangely when the Emersons arrived.
subQuotationList: ['All the same, she is a little too--I hardly like to say unwomanly, but\nshe behaved most strangely when the Emersons arrived.']
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
I don't know, Miss Honeychurch, if you have noticed that Miss Pole, the
lady who has so much yellow hair, takes lemonade. That old Mr. Emerson,
who puts things very strangely--
subQuotationList: ["I don't know, Miss Honeychurch, if you have noticed that Miss Pole, the\nlady who has so much yellow hair, takes lemonade. That old Mr. Emerson,\nwho puts things very strangely--"]
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
Stomach. He warned Miss Pole of her stomach-acidity, he called it--and
he may have meant to be kind. I must say I forgot myself and laughed; it
was so sudden. As Teresa truly said, it was no laughing matter. But the
point is that Miss Lavish was positively ATTRACTED by his mentioning
S., and said she liked plain speaking, and meeting different grades of
thought. She thought they were commercial travellers-- was the
word she used--and all through dinner she tried to prove that England,
our great and beloved country, rests on nothing but commerce. Teresa was
very much annoyed, and left the table before the cheese, saying as she
did so: and pointed to that beautiful picture of Lord Tennyson. Then Miss
Lavish said: Just imagine! 'Tut! The early
Victorians.' My sister had gone, and I felt bound to speak. I said It was horrible
speaking. I reminded her how the Queen had been to Ireland when she did
not want to go, and I must say she was dumbfounded, and made no reply.
But, unluckily, Mr. Emerson overheard this part, and called in his deep
voice: The
woman! I tell things so badly; but you see what a tangle we were in
by this time, all on account of S. having been mentioned in the first
place. But that was not all. After dinner Miss Lavish actually came up
and said: Needless to say, I refused such an unsuitable
invitation, and she had the impertinence to tell me that it would
broaden my ideas, and said that she had four brothers, all University
men, except one who was in the army, who always made a point of talking
to commercial travellers.
