quoteText: Let me finish the story,
subQuotationList: ['Let me finish the story,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Miss Lavish tried Miss Pole, myself, everyone, and finally said:
subQuotationList: ['Miss Lavish tried Miss Pole, myself, everyone, and finally said:']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
She went. At the end of five minutes she returned
unobtrusively with a green baize board, and began playing patience.
subQuotationList: ['She went. At the end of five minutes she returned\nunobtrusively with a green baize board, and began playing patience.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Whatever happened?
subQuotationList: ['Whatever happened?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No one knows. No one will ever know. Miss Lavish will never dare to
tell, and Mr. Emerson does not think it worth telling.
subQuotationList: ['No one knows. No one will ever know. Miss Lavish will never dare to\ntell, and Mr. Emerson does not think it worth telling.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Mr. Beebe--old Mr. Emerson, is he nice or not nice? I do so want to
know.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Beebe--old Mr. Emerson, is he nice or not nice? I do so want to\nknow.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No; but it is so difficult. Sometimes he is so silly, and then I do not
mind him. Miss Alan, what do you think? Is he nice?
subQuotationList: ['No; but it is so difficult. Sometimes he is so silly, and then I do not\nmind him. Miss Alan, what do you think? Is he nice?']
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Catherine Alan'], ['Miss Catherine Alan'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText:
I consider that you are bound to class him as nice, Miss Alan, after
that business of the violets.
subQuotationList: ['I consider that you are bound to class him as nice, Miss Alan, after\nthat business of the violets.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: Mr Beebe whom the conversation amused stirred her up by saying

quoteText:
Violets? Oh, dear! Who told you about the violets? How do things get
round? A pension is a bad place for gossips. No, I cannot forget how
they behaved at Mr. Eager's lecture at Santa Croce. Oh, poor Miss
Honeychurch! It really was too bad. No, I have quite changed. I do NOT
like the Emersons. They are not nice.
subQuotationList:
["Violets? Oh, dear! Who told you about the violets? How do things get
round? A pension is a bad place for gossips. No, I cannot forget how
they behaved at Mr. Eager's lecture at Santa Croce. Oh, poor Miss
Honeychurch! It really was too bad. No, I have quite changed. I do NOT
like the Emersons. They are not nice."]
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText: But aren't they always waylaying you to go out with them, dear?
subQuotationList: ["But aren't they always waylaying you to go out with them, dear?"]
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
Only once. Charlotte didn't like it, and said something--quite
politely, of course.
subQuotationList: ["Only once. Charlotte didn't like it, and said something--quite\npolitely, of course."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Most right of her. They don't understand our ways. They must find their
level.
subQuotationList: ["Most right of her. They don't understand our ways. They must find their\nlevel."]
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
Too late to go out, All the
galleries are shut.
subQuotationList: ['Too late to go out,', 'All the\ngalleries are shut.']
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText:
I think I shall go out, I want to go round the town in the
circular tram--on the platform by the driver.
subQuotationList: ['I think I shall go out,', 'I want to go round the town in the\ncircular tram--on the platform by the driver.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I wish we could. Unluckily I have letters. If you do want to go out
alone, won't you be better on your feet?
subQuotationList: ["I wish we could. Unluckily I have letters. If you do want to go out\nalone, won't you be better on your feet?"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: Mr Beebe who felt responsible for her in the absence of Miss Bartlett ventured to say

quoteText: Italians, dear, you know,
subQuotationList: ['Italians, dear, you know,']
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

quoteText: Perhaps I shall meet someone who reads me through and through!
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps I shall meet someone who reads me through and through!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
She oughtn't really to go at all, and she knows it. I put it down to too much
Beethoven.
subQuotationList: ["She oughtn't really to go at all,", 'and she knows it. I put it down to too much\nBeethoven.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
The world, is certainly full
of beautiful things, if only I could come across them.
subQuotationList: ['The world,', 'is certainly full\nof beautiful things, if only I could come across them.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Nothing ever happens to me,
subQuotationList: ['Nothing ever happens to me,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Oh, what have I done?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, what have I done?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Oh, what have I done?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, what have I done?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Oh, what have I done?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, what have I done?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: You fainted.
subQuotationList: ['You fainted.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I--I am very sorry.
subQuotationList: ['I--I am very sorry.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: How are you now?
subQuotationList: ['How are you now?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Perfectly well--absolutely well.
subQuotationList: ['Perfectly well--absolutely well.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Then let us come home. There's no point in our stopping.
subQuotationList: ["Then let us come home. There's no point in our stopping."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
How very kind you have been! I might have hurt myself falling. But now
I am well. I can go alone, thank you.
subQuotationList: ['How very kind you have been! I might have hurt myself falling. But now\nI am well. I can go alone, thank you.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Oh, my photographs!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, my photographs!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What photographs?
subQuotationList: ['What photographs?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
I bought some photographs at Alinari's. I must have dropped them out
there in the square.
subQuotationList: ["I bought some photographs at Alinari's. I must have dropped them out\nthere in the square."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Would you add to
your kindness by fetching them?
subQuotationList: ['Would you add to\nyour kindness by fetching them?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Miss Honeychurch!
subQuotationList: ['Miss Honeychurch!']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: You sit still; you aren't fit to go home alone.
subQuotationList: ["You sit still; you aren't fit to go home alone."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Yes, I am, thank you so very much.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, I am, thank you so very much.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: No, you aren't. You'd go openly if you were.
subQuotationList: ["No, you aren't. You'd go openly if you were."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: But I had rather--
subQuotationList: ['But I had rather--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Then I don't fetch your photographs.
subQuotationList: ["Then I don't fetch your photographs."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I had rather be alone.
subQuotationList: ['I had rather be alone.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
The man is dead--the man is probably dead; sit
down till you are rested. And
don't move till I come back.
subQuotationList: ['The man is dead--the man is probably dead; sit\ndown till you are rested.', "And\ndon't move till I come back."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Oh, what have I done?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, what have I done?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
And the murderer tried to kiss him, you say--how very odd Italians
are!--and gave himself up to the police! Mr. Beebe was saying that
Italians know everything, but I think they are rather childish. When my
cousin and I were at the Pitti yesterday--What was that?
subQuotationList:
['And the murderer tried to kiss him, you say--how very odd Italians
are!--and gave himself up to the police! Mr. Beebe was saying that
Italians know everything, but I think they are rather childish. When my
cousin and I were at the Pitti yesterday--What was that?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What did you throw in?
subQuotationList: ['What did you throw in?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Things I didn't want,
subQuotationList: ["Things I didn't want,"]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Mr. Emerson!
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Emerson!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Well?
subQuotationList: ['Well?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Where are the photographs?
subQuotationList: ['Where are the photographs?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I believe it was my photographs that you threw away.
subQuotationList: ['I believe it was my photographs that you threw away.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I didn't know what to do with them, They were covered with blood. There! I'm glad I've told you; and all
the time we were making conversation I was wondering what to do with
them. They've gone. I did mind them so, and one is so foolish, it seemed better
that they should go out to the sea--I don't know; I may just mean that
they frightened me. For something
tremendous has happened; I must face it without getting muddled. It
isn't exactly that a man has died.
subQuotationList:
["I didn't know what to do with them,", "They were covered with blood. There! I'm glad I've told you; and all
the time we were making conversation I was wondering what to do with
them.", "They've gone.", "I did mind them so, and one is so foolish, it seemed better
that they should go out to the sea--I don't know; I may just mean that
they frightened me.", "For something
tremendous has happened; I must face it without getting muddled. It
isn't exactly that a man has died."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: It has happened, and I mean to find out what it is.
subQuotationList: ['It has happened,', 'and I mean to find out what it is.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Mr. Emerson--
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Emerson--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I want to ask you something before we go in.
subQuotationList: ['I want to ask you something before we go in.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I have behaved ridiculously.
subQuotationList: ['I have behaved ridiculously.']
speaker: Lucy
referringExpression: She moved her elbows before saying

quoteText:
I was never so much ashamed of myself in my life; I cannot think what
came over me.
subQuotationList: ['I was never so much ashamed of myself in my life; I cannot think what\ncame over me.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I nearly fainted myself,
subQuotationList: ['I nearly fainted myself,']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Well, I owe you a thousand apologies.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I owe you a thousand apologies.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Oh, all right.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, all right.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
And--this is the real point--you know how silly people are
gossiping--ladies especially, I am afraid--you understand what I mean?
subQuotationList: ['And--this is the real point--you know how silly people are\ngossiping--ladies especially, I am afraid--you understand what I mean?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I'm afraid I don't.
subQuotationList: ["I'm afraid I don't."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I mean, would you not mention it to any one, my foolish behaviour?
subQuotationList: ['I mean, would you not mention it to any one, my foolish behaviour?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Your behaviour? Oh, yes, all right--all right.
subQuotationList: ['Your behaviour? Oh, yes, all right--all right.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Thank you so much. And would you--
subQuotationList: ['Thank you so much. And would you--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Well, thank you so much, How quickly these accidents do
happen, and then one returns to the old life!
subQuotationList: ['Well, thank you so much,', 'How quickly these accidents do\nhappen, and then one returns to the old life!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I don't.
subQuotationList: ["I don't."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I shall probably want to live.
subQuotationList: ['I shall probably want to live.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: But why, Mr. Emerson? What do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['But why, Mr. Emerson? What do you mean?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I shall want to live, I say.
subQuotationList: ['I shall want to live, I say.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Too much
Beethoven.
subQuotationList: ['Too much\nBeethoven.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: Mr Beebe indeed noticing her startled eyes at dinnertime had again passed to himself the remark of

quoteText:
No, Charlotte! It's very kind of
Mr. Beebe, but I am certainly coming with you. I had much rather.
subQuotationList: ['No, Charlotte!', "It's very kind of\nMr. Beebe, but I am certainly coming with you. I had much rather."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Very well, dear,
subQuotationList: ['Very well, dear,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
How I do wish Freddy and
your mother could see this, too!
subQuotationList: ['How I do wish Freddy and\nyour mother could see this, too!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: She then made her usual remark

quoteText:
Look, Lucia! Oh, you are watching for the Torre del Gallo party. I
feared you would repent you of your choice.
subQuotationList: ['Look, Lucia! Oh, you are watching for the Torre del Gallo party. I\nfeared you would repent you of your choice.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Oh, let me congratulate you! After your despair
of yesterday! What a fortunate thing!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, let me congratulate you!', 'After your despair\nof yesterday! What a fortunate thing!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Aha! Miss Honeychurch, come you here I am in luck. Now, you are to tell
me absolutely everything that you saw from the beginning.
subQuotationList: ['Aha! Miss Honeychurch, come you here I am in luck. Now, you are to tell\nme absolutely everything that you saw from the beginning.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: But perhaps you would rather not?
subQuotationList: ['But perhaps you would rather not?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: I'm sorry--if you could manage without it, I think I would rather not.
subQuotationList: ["I'm sorry--if you could manage without it, I think I would rather not."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It is I who am sorry, literary hacks are shameless
creatures. I believe there's no secret of the human heart into which we
wouldn't pry.
subQuotationList: ['It is I who am sorry,', "literary hacks are shameless\ncreatures. I believe there's no secret of the human heart into which we\nwouldn't pry."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: What is the heroine's name?
subQuotationList: ["What is the heroine's name?"]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Leonora,
subQuotationList: ['Leonora,']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: I do hope she's nice.
subQuotationList: ["I do hope she's nice."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: And what is the plot?
subQuotationList: ['And what is the plot?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I hope you will excuse me for boring on like this, It is so tempting to talk to really sympathetic people.
Of course, this is the barest outline. There will be a deal of local
colouring, descriptions of Florence and the neighbourhood, and I shall
also introduce some humorous characters. And let me give you all fair
warning: I intend to be unmerciful to the British tourist.
subQuotationList:
['I hope you will excuse me for boring on like this,', 'It is so tempting to talk to really sympathetic people.
Of course, this is the barest outline. There will be a deal of local
colouring, descriptions of Florence and the neighbourhood, and I shall
also introduce some humorous characters. And let me give you all fair
warning: I intend to be unmerciful to the British tourist.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Oh, you wicked woman, I am sure you are thinking
of the Emersons.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, you wicked woman,', 'I am sure you are thinking\nof the Emersons.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I confess that in Italy my sympathies are not with my own countrymen.
It is the neglected Italians who attract me, and whose lives I am going
to paint so far as I can. For I repeat and I insist, and I have always
held most strongly, that a tragedy such as yesterday's is not the less
tragic because it happened in humble life.
subQuotationList:
["I confess that in Italy my sympathies are not with my own countrymen.
It is the neglected Italians who attract me, and whose lives I am going
to paint so far as I can. For I repeat and I insist, and I have always
held most strongly, that a tragedy such as yesterday's is not the less
tragic because it happened in humble life."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
She is my idea of a really clever woman, That
last remark struck me as so particularly true. It should be a most
pathetic novel.
subQuotationList: ['She is my idea of a really clever woman,', 'That\nlast remark struck me as so particularly true. It should be a most\npathetic novel.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
She is emancipated, but only in the very best sense of the word, None but the superficial would be
shocked at her. We had a long talk yesterday. She believes in justice
and truth and human interest. She told me also that she has a high
opinion of the destiny of woman--Mr. Eager! Why, how nice! What a
pleasant surprise!
subQuotationList:
['She is emancipated, but only in the very best sense of the word,', 'None but the superficial would be
shocked at her. We had a long talk yesterday. She believes in justice
and truth and human interest. She told me also that she has a high
opinion of the destiny of woman--Mr. Eager! Why, how nice! What a
pleasant surprise!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Lavish']], [['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Mr Eager']]]

quoteText:
Ah, not for me, for I have been watching
you and Miss Honeychurch for quite a little time.
subQuotationList: ['Ah, not for me,', 'for I have been watching\nyou and Miss Honeychurch for quite a little time.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: We were chatting to Miss Lavish.
subQuotationList: ['We were chatting to Miss Lavish.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: So I saw. Were you indeed? Andate via! sono occupato!
subQuotationList: ['So I saw. Were you indeed? Andate via! sono occupato!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
I am about to venture a suggestion. Would you and
Miss Honeychurch be disposed to join me in a drive some day this week--a
drive in the hills? We might go up by Fiesole and back by Settignano.
There is a point on that road where we could get down and have an
hour's ramble on the hillside. The view thence of Florence is most
beautiful--far better than the hackneyed view of Fiesole. It is the view
that Alessio Baldovinetti is fond of introducing into his pictures. That
man had a decided feeling for landscape. Decidedly. But who looks at it
to-day? Ah, the world is too much for us.
subQuotationList:
["I am about to venture a suggestion. Would you and
Miss Honeychurch be disposed to join me in a drive some day this week--a
drive in the hills? We might go up by Fiesole and back by Settignano.
There is a point on that road where we could get down and have an
hour's ramble on the hillside. The view thence of Florence is most

that Alessio Baldovinetti is fond of introducing into his pictures. That
man had a decided feeling for landscape. Decidedly. But who looks at it
to-day? Ah, the world is too much for us."]
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
So we shall be a partie carree, In these days of
toil and tumult one has great needs of the country and its message of
purity. Andate via! andate presto, presto! Ah, the town! Beautiful as it
is, it is the town.
subQuotationList:
['So we shall be a partie carree,', 'In these days of
toil and tumult one has great needs of the country and its message of
purity. Andate via! andate presto, presto! Ah, the town! Beautiful as it
is, it is the town.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
This very square--so I am told--witnessed yesterday the most sordid of
tragedies. To one who loves the Florence of Dante and Savonarola
there is something portentous in such desecration--portentous and
humiliating.
subQuotationList:
['This very square--so I am told--witnessed yesterday the most sordid of
tragedies. To one who loves the Florence of Dante and Savonarola
there is something portentous in such desecration--portentous and
humiliating.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Humiliating indeed, Miss Honeychurch happened to
be passing through as it happened. She can hardly bear to speak of it.
subQuotationList: ['Humiliating indeed,', 'Miss Honeychurch happened to\nbe passing through as it happened. She can hardly bear to speak of it.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: And how came we to have you here?
subQuotationList: ['And how came we to have you here?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Do
not blame her, please, Mr. Eager. The fault is mine: I left her
unchaperoned.
subQuotationList: ['Do\nnot blame her, please, Mr. Eager. The fault is mine: I left her\nunchaperoned.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: So you were here alone, Miss Honeychurch?
subQuotationList: ['So you were here alone, Miss Honeychurch?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Practically.
subQuotationList: ['Practically.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: One of our pension acquaintances kindly brought her home,
subQuotationList: ['One of our pension acquaintances kindly brought her home,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
For her also it must have been a terrible experience. I trust that
neither of you was at all--that it was not in your immediate proximity?
subQuotationList: ['For her also it must have been a terrible experience. I trust that\nneither of you was at all--that it was not in your immediate proximity?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: He died by the fountain, I believe,
subQuotationList: ['He died by the fountain, I believe,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And you and your friend--
subQuotationList: ['And you and your friend--']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Were over at the Loggia.
subQuotationList: ['Were over at the Loggia.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
That must have saved you much. You have not, of course, seen the
disgraceful illustrations which the gutter Press--This man is a public
nuisance; he knows that I am a resident perfectly well, and yet he goes
on worrying me to buy his vulgar views.
subQuotationList:
['That must have saved you much. You have not, of course, seen the
disgraceful illustrations which the gutter Press--This man is a public
nuisance; he knows that I am a resident perfectly well, and yet he goes
on worrying me to buy his vulgar views.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: This is too much!
subQuotationList: ['This is too much!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Willingly would I purchase--
subQuotationList: ['Willingly would I purchase--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Ignore him,
subQuotationList: ['Ignore him,']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: How wonderfully people rise in these days!
subQuotationList: ['How wonderfully people rise in these days!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Generally, one has only sympathy for their
success. The desire for education and for social advance--in these
things there is something not wholly vile. There are some working men
whom one would be very willing to see out here in Florence--little as
they would make of it.
subQuotationList:
['Generally,', 'one has only sympathy for their
success. The desire for education and for social advance--in these
things there is something not wholly vile. There are some working men
whom one would be very willing to see out here in Florence--little as
they would make of it.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Is he a journalist now?
subQuotationList: ['Is he a journalist now?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: He is not; he made an advantageous marriage.
subQuotationList: ['He is not; he made an advantageous marriage.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Oh, so he has a wife.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, so he has a wife.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Dead, Miss Bartlett, dead. I wonder--yes I wonder how he has the
effrontery to look me in the face, to dare to claim acquaintance with
me. He was in my London parish long ago. The other day in Santa Croce,
when he was with Miss Honeychurch, I snubbed him. Let him beware that he
does not get more than a snub.
subQuotationList:
['Dead, Miss Bartlett, dead. I wonder--yes I wonder how he has the
effrontery to look me in the face, to dare to claim acquaintance with
me. He was in my London parish long ago. The other day in Santa Croce,

mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Bartlett'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText: What?
subQuotationList: ['What?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Exposure!
subQuotationList: ['Exposure!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Do you mean, that he is an irreligious man? We know that
already.
subQuotationList: ['Do you mean,', 'that he is an irreligious man? We know that\nalready.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy, dear--
subQuotationList: ['Lucy, dear--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I should be astonished if you knew all. The boy--an innocent child at
the time--I will exclude. God knows what his education and his inherited
qualities may have made him.
subQuotationList: ['I should be astonished if you knew all. The boy--an innocent child at\nthe time--I will exclude. God knows what his education and his inherited\nqualities may have made him.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Perhaps, it is something that we had better not
hear.
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps,', 'it is something that we had better not\nhear.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: To speak plainly, it is. I will say no more.
subQuotationList: ['To speak plainly,', 'it is. I will say no more.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: You have said very little.
subQuotationList: ['You have said very little.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: It was my intention to say very little,
subQuotationList: ['It was my intention to say very little,']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Murder, if you want to know, That man murdered his
wife!
subQuotationList: ['Murder, if you want to know,', 'That man murdered his\nwife!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: How?
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
To all intents and purposes he murdered her. That day in Santa
Croce--did they say anything against me?
subQuotationList: ['To all intents and purposes he murdered her. That day in Santa\nCroce--did they say anything against me?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Not a word, Mr. Eager--not a single word.
subQuotationList: ['Not a word, Mr. Eager--not a single word.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, I thought they had been libelling me to you. But I suppose it is
only their personal charms that makes you defend them.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, I thought they had been libelling me to you. But I suppose it is\nonly their personal charms that makes you defend them.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText: I'm not defending them, They're nothing to me.
subQuotationList: ["I'm not defending them,", "They're nothing to me."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: How could you think she was defending them?
subQuotationList: ['How could you think she was defending them?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
She will find it difficult. For that man has murdered his wife in the
sight of God.
subQuotationList: ['She will find it difficult. For that man has murdered his wife in the\nsight of God.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: I must be going,
subQuotationList: ['I must be going,']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Drive? Oh, is our drive to come off?
subQuotationList: ['Drive? Oh, is our drive to come off?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Bother the drive! It
is just the drive we had arranged with Mr. Beebe without any fuss at
all. Why should he invite us in that absurd manner? We might as well
invite him. We are each paying for ourselves.
subQuotationList:
['Bother the drive!', 'It
is just the drive we had arranged with Mr. Beebe without any fuss at
all. Why should he invite us in that absurd manner? We might as well
invite him. We are each paying for ourselves.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
If that is so, dear--if the drive we and Mr. Beebe are going with Mr.
Eager is really the same as the one we are going with Mr. Beebe, then I
foresee a sad kettle of fish.
subQuotationList: ['If that is so, dear--if the drive we and Mr. Beebe are going with Mr.\nEager is really the same as the one we are going with Mr. Beebe, then I\nforesee a sad kettle of fish.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: How?
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Because Mr. Beebe has asked Eleanor Lavish to come, too.
subQuotationList: ['Because Mr. Beebe has asked Eleanor Lavish to come, too.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: That will mean another carriage.
subQuotationList: ['That will mean another carriage.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Far worse. Mr. Eager does not like Eleanor. She knows it herself. The
truth must be told; she is too unconventional for him.
subQuotationList: ['Far worse. Mr. Eager does not like Eleanor. She knows it herself. The\ntruth must be told; she is too unconventional for him.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Miss Lavish'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

quoteText: where things might lead to,
subQuotationList: ['where things might lead to,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Whether it is Mr. Beebe who forgot to tell Mr. Eager, or Mr.
Eager who forgot when he told us, or whether they have decided to leave
Eleanor out altogether--which they could scarcely do--but in any case
we must be prepared. It is you they really want; I am only asked for
appearances. You shall go with the two gentlemen, and I and Eleanor will
follow behind. A one-horse carriage would do for us. Yet how difficult
it is!
subQuotationList:
['Whether it is Mr. Beebe who forgot to tell Mr. Eager, or Mr.
Eager who forgot when he told us, or whether they have decided to leave

quoteText: It is indeed,
subQuotationList: ['It is indeed,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What do you think about it?
subQuotationList: ['What do you think about it?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I don't know what I think, nor what I want.
subQuotationList: ["I don't know what I think, nor what I want."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, dear, Lucy! I do hope Florence isn't boring you. Speak the word,
and, as you know, I would take you to the ends of the earth to-morrow.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, dear, Lucy! I do hope Florence isn't boring you. Speak the word,\nand, as you know, I would take you to the ends of the earth to-morrow."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Thank you, Charlotte,
subQuotationList: ['Thank you, Charlotte,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And the news?
subQuotationList: ['And the news?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Mrs. Vyse and her son have gone to Rome, Do you know the Vyses?
subQuotationList: ['Mrs. Vyse and her son have gone to Rome,', 'Do you know the Vyses?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, not that way back. We can never have too much of the dear Piazza
Signoria.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, not that way back. We can never have too much of the dear Piazza\nSignoria.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
They're nice people, the Vyses. So clever--my idea of what's really
clever. Don't you long to be in Rome?
subQuotationList: ["They're nice people, the Vyses. So clever--my idea of what's really\nclever. Don't you long to be in Rome?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I die for it!
subQuotationList: ['I die for it!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Charlotte! Here's an idea. What if we popped
off to Rome to-morrow--straight to the Vyses' hotel? For I do know what
I want. I'm sick of Florence. No, you said you'd go to the ends of the
earth! Do! Do!
subQuotationList:
['Charlotte!', "Here's an idea. What if we popped
off to Rome to-morrow--straight to the Vyses' hotel? For I do know what
I want. I'm sick of Florence. No, you said you'd go to the ends of the
earth! Do! Do!"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, you droll person! Pray, what would become of your drive in the
hills?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, you droll person! Pray, what would become of your drive in the\nhills?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett with equal vivacity replied

quoteText: So, Miss Honeychurch, you are travelling? As a student of art?
subQuotationList: ['So, Miss Honeychurch, you are travelling? As a student of art?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Oh, dear me, no--oh, no!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, dear me, no--oh, no!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Perhaps as a student of human nature, like
myself?
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps as a student of human nature,', 'like\nmyself?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Oh, no. I am here as a tourist.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, no. I am here as a tourist.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, indeed, Are you indeed? If you will not think me
rude, we residents sometimes pity you poor tourists not a little--handed
about like a parcel of goods from Venice to Florence, from Florence to
Rome, living herded together in pensions or hotels, quite unconscious
of anything that is outside Baedeker, their one anxiety to get 'done'
or 'through' and go on somewhere else. The result is, they mix up towns,
rivers, palaces in one inextricable whirl. You know the American girl
in Punch who says: And the father
replies: There's travelling for you. Ha! ha! ha!
subQuotationList:
['Oh, indeed,', "Are you indeed? If you will not think me
rude, we residents sometimes pity you poor tourists not a little--handed
about like a parcel of goods from Venice to Florence, from Florence to
Rome, living herded together in pensions or hotels, quite unconscious
of anything that is outside Baedeker, their one anxiety to get 'done'
or 'through' and go on somewhere else. The result is, they mix up towns,
rivers, palaces in one inextricable whirl. You know the American girl
in Punch who says:", 'And the father
replies:', "There's travelling for you. Ha! ha! ha!"]
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
I quite agree, The narrowness and superficiality of the
Anglo-Saxon tourist is nothing less than a menace.
subQuotationList: ['I quite agree,', 'The narrowness and superficiality of the\nAnglo-Saxon tourist is nothing less than a menace.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Quite so. Now, the English colony at Florence, Miss Honeychurch--and it
is of considerable size, though, of course, not all equally--a few are
here for trade, for example. But the greater part are students. Lady
Helen Laverstock is at present busy over Fra Angelico. I mention her
name because we are passing her villa on the left. No, you can only see
it if you stand--no, do not stand; you will fall. She is very proud of
that thick hedge. Inside, perfect seclusion. One might have gone back
six hundred years. Some critics believe that her garden was the scene of
The Decameron, which lends it an additional interest, does it not?
subQuotationList:
['Quite so. Now, the English colony at Florence, Miss Honeychurch--and it
is of considerable size, though, of course, not all equally--a few are
here for trade, for example. But the greater part are students. Lady
Helen Laverstock is at present busy over Fra Angelico. I mention her
name because we are passing her villa on the left. No, you can only see

that thick hedge. Inside, perfect seclusion. One might have gone back

speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy'], ['Lady Helen Laverstock'], ['Lady Helen Laverstock'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lady Helen Laverstock'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lady Helen Laverstock'], ['Lady Helen Laverstock']]]

quoteText:
It does indeed! Tell me, where do they place the
scene of that wonderful seventh day?
subQuotationList: ['It does indeed!', 'Tell me, where do they place the\nscene of that wonderful seventh day?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Doubtless you know
her monographs in the series of 'Mediaeval Byways'? He is working at
Gemistus Pletho. Sometimes as I take tea in their beautiful grounds I
hear, over the wall, the electric tram squealing up the new road with
its loads of hot, dusty, unintelligent tourists who are going to 'do'
Fiesole in an hour in order that they may say they have been there, and
I think--think--I think how little they think what lies so near them.
subQuotationList:
["Doubtless you know
her monographs in the series of 'Mediaeval Byways'? He is working at
Gemistus Pletho. Sometimes as I take tea in their beautiful grounds I
hear, over the wall, the electric tram squealing up the new road with
its loads of hot, dusty, unintelligent tourists who are going to 'do'
Fiesole in an hour in order that they may say they have been there, and
I think--think--I think how little they think what lies so near them."]
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
referringExpression: Mr Eager proceeded to tell Miss Honeychurch

quoteText: Piano! piano!
subQuotationList: ['Piano! piano!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: Va bene, signore, va bene, va bene,
subQuotationList: ['Va bene, signore, va bene, va bene,']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: She is my sister,
subQuotationList: ['She is my sister,']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText:
Most certainly I would let them be, But I dare say I
shall receive scant support. I have always flown in the face of the
conventions all my life. This is what I call an adventure.
subQuotationList: ['Most certainly I would let them be,', 'But I dare say I\nshall receive scant support. I have always flown in the face of the\nconventions all my life. This is what I call an adventure.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
We must not submit, I knew he was trying it on. He is
treating us as if we were a party of Cook's tourists.
subQuotationList: ['We must not submit,', "I knew he was trying it on. He is\ntreating us as if we were a party of Cook's tourists."]
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

subQuotationList: ['Surely no!']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Leave them alone, Do we find happiness so often that we should turn it off the
box when it happens to sit there? To be driven by lovers--A king might
envy us, and if we part them it's more like sacrilege than anything I
know.
subQuotationList:
['Leave them alone,', "Do we find happiness so often that we should turn it off the

quoteText: Signorina!

quoteText: Victory at last!
subQuotationList: ['Victory at last!']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
It is not victory, It is defeat. You have parted
two people who were happy.
subQuotationList: ['It is not victory,', 'It is defeat. You have parted\ntwo people who were happy.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
We have tried to buy what cannot be bought with money. He has bargained
to drive us, and he is doing it. We have no rights over his soul.
subQuotationList: ['We have tried to buy what cannot be bought with money. He has bargained\nto drive us, and he is doing it. We have no rights over his soul.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

quoteText: He was not driving us well, He jolted us.
subQuotationList: ['He was not driving us well,', 'He jolted us.']
speaker: Miss Lavish
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Driver'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager']], [['The Driver'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

quoteText:
That I deny. It was as restful as sleeping. Aha! he is jolting us now.
Can you wonder? He would like to throw us out, and most certainly he is
justified. And if I were superstitious I'd be frightened of the girl,
too. It doesn't do to injure young people. Have you ever heard of
Lorenzo de Medici?
subQuotationList:
["That I deny. It was as restful as sleeping. Aha! he is jolting us now.
Can you wonder? He would like to throw us out, and most certainly he is
justified. And if I were superstitious I'd be frightened of the girl,
too. It doesn't do to injure young people. Have you ever heard of
Lorenzo de Medici?"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Driver'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['The Driver'], ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['The Driver'], ['Persephone']]]

quoteText:
Most certainly I have. Do you refer to Lorenzo il Magnifico, or to
Lorenzo, Duke of Urbino, or to Lorenzo surnamed Lorenzino on account of
his diminutive stature?
subQuotationList: ['Most certainly I have. Do you refer to Lorenzo il Magnifico, or to\nLorenzo, Duke of Urbino, or to Lorenzo surnamed Lorenzino on account of\nhis diminutive stature?']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
The Lord knows. Possibly he does know, for I refer to Lorenzo the poet.
He wrote a line--so I heard yesterday--which runs like this: 'Don't go
fighting against the Spring.'
subQuotationList: ["The Lord knows. Possibly he does know, for I refer to Lorenzo the poet.\nHe wrote a line--so I heard yesterday--which runs like this: 'Don't go\nfighting against the Spring.'"]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
would
render a correct meaning.
subQuotationList: ['would\nrender a correct meaning.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: The point is, we have warred with it. Look.
subQuotationList: ['The point is, we have warred with it. Look.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Fifty miles of Spring, and we've come up to admire them. Do you suppose
there's any difference between Spring in nature and Spring in man? But
there we go, praising the one and condemning the other as improper,
ashamed that the same laws work eternally through both.
subQuotationList:
["Fifty miles of Spring, and we've come up to admire them. Do you suppose
there's any difference between Spring in nature and Spring in man? But
there we go, praising the one and condemning the other as improper,
ashamed that the same laws work eternally through both."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: the railway.
subQuotationList: ['the railway.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
The railway! Oh, but I shall die! Of course it
was the railway! He is the image of a
porter--on, on the South-Eastern.
subQuotationList: ['The railway!', 'Oh, but I shall die! Of course it\nwas the railway!', 'He is the image of a\nporter--on, on the South-Eastern.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Eleanor, be quiet, Hush! They'll
hear--the Emersons--
subQuotationList: ['Eleanor, be quiet,', "Hush! They'll\nhear--the Emersons--"]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I can't stop. Let me go my wicked way. A porter--
subQuotationList: ["I can't stop. Let me go my wicked way. A porter--"]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Eleanor!
subQuotationList: ['Eleanor!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I'm sure it's all right, The Emersons won't hear, and
they wouldn't mind if they did.
subQuotationList: ["I'm sure it's all right,", "The Emersons won't hear, and\nthey wouldn't mind if they did."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Miss Honeychurch listening! Pouf! Wouf! You
naughty girl! Go away!
subQuotationList: ['Miss Honeychurch listening!', 'Pouf! Wouf! You\nnaughty girl! Go away!']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText: Oh, Lucy, you ought to be with Mr. Eager, I'm sure.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, Lucy, you ought to be with Mr. Eager, I'm sure."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I can't find them now, and I don't want to either.
subQuotationList: ["I can't find them now, and I don't want to either."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Mr. Eager will be offended. It is your party.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Eager will be offended. It is your party.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Please, I'd rather stop here with you.
subQuotationList: ["Please, I'd rather stop here with you."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, I agree, It's like a school feast; the boys
have got separated from the girls. Miss Lucy, you are to go. We wish to
converse on high topics unsuited for your ear.
subQuotationList: ['No, I agree,', "It's like a school feast; the boys\nhave got separated from the girls. Miss Lucy, you are to go. We wish to\nconverse on high topics unsuited for your ear."]
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
How tired one gets, Oh, I do wish Freddy and your
mother could be here.
subQuotationList: ['How tired one gets,', 'Oh, I do wish Freddy and your\nmother could be here.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Then sit you down, Observe my foresight.
subQuotationList: ['Then sit you down,', 'Observe my foresight.']
speaker: Miss Lavish

quoteText:
Lucy; without a moment's doubt, Lucy. The ground will do for me. Really
I have not had rheumatism for years. If I do feel it coming on I shall
stand. Imagine your mother's feelings if I let you sit in the wet
in your white linen.
subQuotationList:
["Lucy; without a moment's doubt, Lucy. The ground will do for me. Really
I have not had rheumatism for years. If I do feel it coming on I shall
stand. Imagine your mother's feelings if I let you sit in the wet
in your white linen."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

subQuotationList: ["Here we are, all settled delightfully. Even if my\ndress is thinner it will not show so much, being brown. Sit down, dear;\nyou are too unselfish; you don't assert yourself enough."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Now don't be alarmed; this isn't a cold. It's the tiniest
cough, and I have had it three days. It's nothing to do with sitting
here at all.
subQuotationList: ["Now don't be alarmed; this isn't a cold. It's the tiniest\ncough, and I have had it three days. It's nothing to do with sitting\nhere at all."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Dove?
subQuotationList: ['Dove?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Dove buoni uomini?
subQuotationList: ['Dove buoni uomini?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Uno--piu--piccolo, Has the cigar been
given to you by Mr. Beebe, the smaller of the two good men?
subQuotationList: ['Uno--piu--piccolo,', 'Has the cigar been\ngiven to you by Mr. Beebe, the smaller of the two good men?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: would she like to see them?
subQuotationList: ['would she like to see them?']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: Ma buoni uomini.
subQuotationList: ['Ma buoni uomini.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What is that?
subQuotationList: ['What is that?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Eccolo!
subQuotationList: ['Eccolo!']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: Courage! Courage and love.
subQuotationList: ['Courage!', 'Courage and love.']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: Lucy! Lucy! Lucy!
subQuotationList: ['Lucy! Lucy! Lucy!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Let us go
immediately, The signorino will walk.
subQuotationList: ['Let us go\nimmediately,', 'The signorino will walk.']
speaker: The Driver
addressees: ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe']
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe']], [['George Emerson']]]

quoteText: All the way? He will be hours,
subQuotationList: ['All the way? He will be hours,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
addressees: ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'The Driver', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett']

quoteText: Apparently. I told him it was unwise.
subQuotationList: ['Apparently. I told him it was unwise.']
speaker: The Driver
addressees: ['Lucy', 'Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe']

quoteText:
Courage, Miss Honeychurch, courage and faith. If I might say so, there
is something almost blasphemous in this horror of the elements. Are we
seriously to suppose that all these clouds, all this immense electrical
display, is simply called into existence to extinguish you or me?
subQuotationList:
['Courage, Miss Honeychurch, courage and faith. If I might say so, there
is something almost blasphemous in this horror of the elements. Are we
seriously to suppose that all these clouds, all this immense electrical
display, is simply called into existence to extinguish you or me?']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: No--of course--
subQuotationList: ['No--of course--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Even from the scientific standpoint the chances against our being
struck are enormous. The steel knives, the only articles which might
attract the current, are in the other carriage. And, in any case, we are
infinitely safer than if we were walking. Courage--courage and faith.
subQuotationList:
['Even from the scientific standpoint the chances against our being
struck are enormous. The steel knives, the only articles which might
attract the current, are in the other carriage. And, in any case, we are
infinitely safer than if we were walking. Courage--courage and faith.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText:
Mr. Eager! We want your assistance. Will you
interpret for us?
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Eager!', 'We want your assistance. Will you\ninterpret for us?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rev. Cuthbert Eager']], [['Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Mr Eager'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'Miss Lavish', 'Mr. Beebe']]]

quoteText:
George! Ask your driver which way George went. The
boy may lose his way. He may be killed.
subQuotationList: ['George!', 'Ask your driver which way George went. The\nboy may lose his way. He may be killed.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Go, Mr. Eager, don't ask our driver; our driver is
no help. Go and support poor Mr. Beebe--, he is nearly demented.
subQuotationList: ['Go, Mr. Eager,', "don't ask our driver; our driver is\nno help. Go and support poor Mr. Beebe--, he is nearly demented."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: He may be killed! He may be killed!
subQuotationList: ['He may be killed!', 'He may be killed!']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Typical behaviour, In
the presence of reality that kind of person invariably breaks down.
subQuotationList: ['Typical behaviour,', 'In\nthe presence of reality that kind of person invariably breaks down.']
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

quoteText: What does he know? Charlotte, how much does Mr. Eager know?
subQuotationList: ['What does he know?', 'Charlotte, how much does Mr. Eager know?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Nothing, dearest; he knows nothing. But--
subQuotationList: ['Nothing, dearest; he knows nothing. But--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: HE knows everything. Dearest, had we better? Shall I?
subQuotationList: ['HE knows everything. Dearest, had we better? Shall I?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
It is dreadful to be entangled with low-class people.
He saw it all.
subQuotationList: ['It is dreadful to be entangled with low-class people.\nHe saw it all.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Silenzio!
subQuotationList: ['Silenzio!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Va bene,
subQuotationList: ['Va bene,']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText:
Charlotte, dear Charlotte, kiss me. Kiss me again. Only you can
understand me. You warned me to be careful. And I--I thought I was
developing.
subQuotationList: ['Charlotte, dear Charlotte, kiss me. Kiss me again. Only you can\nunderstand me. You warned me to be careful. And I--I thought I was\ndeveloping.']
speaker: Lucy
referringExpression: Lucy poured out hers to her cousin

quoteText: Do not cry, dearest. Take your time.
subQuotationList: ['Do not cry, dearest. Take your time.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I have been obstinate and silly--worse than you know, far worse. Once
by the river--Oh, but he isn't killed--he wouldn't be killed, would he?
subQuotationList: ["I have been obstinate and silly--worse than you know, far worse. Once\nby the river--Oh, but he isn't killed--he wouldn't be killed, would he?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I trust not. One would always pray against that.
subQuotationList: ['I trust not. One would always pray against that.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
He is really--I think he was taken by surprise, just as I was before.
But this time I'm not to blame; I want you to believe that. I simply
slipped into those violets. No, I want to be really truthful. I am a
little to blame. I had silly thoughts. The sky, you know, was gold,
and the ground all blue, and for a moment he looked like someone in a
book.
subQuotationList:
["He is really--I think he was taken by surprise, just as I was before.
But this time I'm not to blame; I want you to believe that. I simply
slipped into those violets. No, I want to be really truthful. I am a
little to blame. I had silly thoughts. The sky, you know, was gold,
and the ground all blue, and for a moment he looked like someone in a
book."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: In a book?
subQuotationList: ['In a book?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Heroes--gods--the nonsense of schoolgirls.
subQuotationList: ['Heroes--gods--the nonsense of schoolgirls.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And then?
subQuotationList: ['And then?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: But, Charlotte, you know what happened then.
subQuotationList: ['But, Charlotte, you know what happened then.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I want to be truthful, It is so hard to be absolutely
truthful.
subQuotationList: ['I want to be truthful,', 'It is so hard to be absolutely\ntruthful.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Don't be troubled, dearest. Wait till you are calmer. We will talk it
over before bed-time in my room.
subQuotationList: ["Don't be troubled, dearest. Wait till you are calmer. We will talk it\nover before bed-time in my room."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
At last, I shall understand myself. I shan't again
be troubled by things that come out of nothing, and mean I don't know
what.
subQuotationList: ['At last,', "I shall understand myself. I shan't again\nbe troubled by things that come out of nothing, and mean I don't know\nwhat."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Well, dear, I at all events am ready for Bedfordshire. Come into my
room, and I will give a good brush to your hair.
subQuotationList: ['Well, dear, I at all events am ready for Bedfordshire. Come into my\nroom, and I will give a good brush to your hair.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett had recovered her luggage and could say

quoteText: So what is to be done?
subQuotationList: ['So what is to be done?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: What is to be done? A point, dearest, which you alone can settle.
subQuotationList: ['What is to be done? A point, dearest, which you alone can settle.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: It has been raining for nearly four hours,
subQuotationList: ['It has been raining for nearly four hours,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: How do you propose to silence him?
subQuotationList: ['How do you propose to silence him?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: The driver?
subQuotationList: ['The driver?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: My dear girl, no; Mr. George Emerson.
subQuotationList: ['My dear girl, no; Mr. George Emerson.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I don't understand,
subQuotationList: ["I don't understand,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: How are you going to stop him talking about it?
subQuotationList: ['How are you going to stop him talking about it?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I have a feeling that talk is a thing he will never do.
subQuotationList: ['I have a feeling that talk is a thing he will never do.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I, too, intend to judge him charitably. But unfortunately I have met
the type before. They seldom keep their exploits to themselves.
subQuotationList: ['I, too, intend to judge him charitably. But unfortunately I have met\nthe type before. They seldom keep their exploits to themselves.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Exploits?
subQuotationList: ['Exploits?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
My poor dear, did you suppose that this was his first? Come here
and listen to me. I am only gathering it from his own remarks. Do you
remember that day at lunch when he argued with Miss Alan that liking one
person is an extra reason for liking another?
subQuotationList:
['My poor dear, did you suppose that this was his first? Come here
and listen to me. I am only gathering it from his own remarks. Do you
remember that day at lunch when he argued with Miss Alan that liking one
person is an extra reason for liking another?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Well, I am no prude. There is no need to call him a wicked young man,
but obviously he is thoroughly unrefined. Let us put it down to his
deplorable antecedents and education, if you wish. But we are no farther
on with our question. What do you propose to do?
subQuotationList:
['Well, I am no prude. There is no need to call him a wicked young man,
but obviously he is thoroughly unrefined. Let us put it down to his
deplorable antecedents and education, if you wish. But we are no farther
on with our question. What do you propose to do?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Lucy']]]

quoteText: I propose to speak to him,
subQuotationList: ['I propose to speak to him,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You see, Charlotte, your kindness--I shall never forget it. But--as you
said--it is my affair. Mine and his.
subQuotationList: ['You see, Charlotte, your kindness--I shall never forget it. But--as you\nsaid--it is my affair. Mine and his.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And you are going to IMPLORE him, to BEG him to keep silence?
subQuotationList: ['And you are going to IMPLORE him, to BEG him to keep silence?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Certainly not. There would be no difficulty. Whatever you ask him he
answers, yes or no; then it is over. I have been frightened of him. But
now I am not one little bit.
subQuotationList: ['Certainly not. There would be no difficulty. Whatever you ask him he\nanswers, yes or no; then it is over. I have been frightened of him. But\nnow I am not one little bit.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
But we fear him for you, dear. You are so young and inexperienced, you
have lived among such nice people, that you cannot realize what men can
be--how they can take a brutal pleasure in insulting a woman whom her
sex does not protect and rally round. This afternoon, for example, if I
had not arrived, what would have happened?
subQuotationList:
['But we fear him for you, dear. You are so young and inexperienced, you
have lived among such nice people, that you cannot realize what men can
be--how they can take a brutal pleasure in insulting a woman whom her
sex does not protect and rally round. This afternoon, for example, if I
had not arrived, what would have happened?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I can't think,
subQuotationList: ["I can't think,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What would have happened if I hadn't arrived?
subQuotationList: ["What would have happened if I hadn't arrived?"]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I can't think,
subQuotationList: ["I can't think,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: When he insulted you, how would you have replied?
subQuotationList: ['When he insulted you, how would you have replied?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I hadn't time to think. You came.
subQuotationList: ["I hadn't time to think. You came."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Yes, but won't you tell me now what you would have done?
subQuotationList: ["Yes, but won't you tell me now what you would have done?"]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I should have--
subQuotationList: ['I should have--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Come away from the window, dear, You will be seen
from the road.
subQuotationList: ['Come away from the window, dear,', 'You will be seen\nfrom the road.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Oh, for a real man! We are only two women, you and I. Mr. Beebe is
hopeless. There is Mr. Eager, but you do not trust him. Oh, for your
brother! He is young, but I know that his sister's insult would rouse
in him a very lion. Thank God, chivalry is not yet dead. There are still
left some men who can reverence woman.
subQuotationList:
["Oh, for a real man! We are only two women, you and I. Mr. Beebe is
hopeless. There is Mr. Eager, but you do not trust him. Oh, for your
brother! He is young, but I know that his sister's insult would rouse
in him a very lion. Thank God, chivalry is not yet dead. There are still
left some men who can reverence woman."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Lucy'], ['Rev. Cuthbert Eager'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy'], ['Lucy'], ['Freddy']]]

quoteText: It will be a push to catch the morning train, but we must try.
subQuotationList: ['It will be a push to catch the morning train, but we must try.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: The train to Rome.
subQuotationList: ['The train to Rome.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

subQuotationList: ['When does the train to Rome go?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: At eight.
subQuotationList: ['At eight.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Signora Bertolini would be upset.
subQuotationList: ['Signora Bertolini would be upset.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: We must face that,
subQuotationList: ['We must face that,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: She will make us pay for a whole week's pension.
subQuotationList: ["She will make us pay for a whole week's pension."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I expect she will. However, we shall be much more comfortable at the
Vyses' hotel. Isn't afternoon tea given there for nothing?
subQuotationList: ["I expect she will. However, we shall be much more comfortable at the\nVyses' hotel. Isn't afternoon tea given there for nothing?"]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Yes, but they pay extra for wine.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, but they pay extra for wine.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Dearest Lucy, how will you ever forgive me?
subQuotationList: ['Dearest Lucy, how will you ever forgive me?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Charlotte dear, what do you mean? As if I have anything to forgive!
subQuotationList: ['Charlotte dear, what do you mean? As if I have anything to forgive!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You have a great deal, and I have a very great deal to forgive myself,
too. I know well how much I vex you at every turn.
subQuotationList: ['You have a great deal, and I have a very great deal to forgive myself,\ntoo. I know well how much I vex you at every turn.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: But no--
subQuotationList: ['But no--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Ah, but yes! I feel that our tour together is hardly the success I had
hoped. I might have known it would not do. You want someone younger
and stronger and more in sympathy with you. I am too uninteresting and
old-fashioned--only fit to pack and unpack your things.
subQuotationList:
['Ah, but yes! I feel that our tour together is hardly the success I had
hoped. I might have known it would not do. You want someone younger
and stronger and more in sympathy with you. I am too uninteresting and
old-fashioned--only fit to pack and unpack your things.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Please--
subQuotationList: ['Please--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
My only consolation was that you found people more to your taste, and
were often able to leave me at home. I had my own poor ideas of what a
lady ought to do, but I hope I did not inflict them on you more than was
necessary. You had your own way about these rooms, at all events.
subQuotationList:
['My only consolation was that you found people more to your taste, and
were often able to leave me at home. I had my own poor ideas of what a
lady ought to do, but I hope I did not inflict them on you more than was

quoteText: You mustn't say these things,
subQuotationList: ["You mustn't say these things,"]
speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['I have been a failure,', 'Failed to make you\nhappy; failed in my duty to your mother. She has been so generous to me;\nI shall never face her again after this disaster.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
But mother will understand. It is not your fault, this trouble, and it
isn't a disaster either.
subQuotationList: ["But mother will understand. It is not your fault, this trouble, and it\nisn't a disaster either."]

quoteText:
It is my fault, it is a disaster. She will never forgive me, and
rightly. For instance, what right had I to make friends with Miss
Lavish?
subQuotationList: ['It is my fault, it is a disaster. She will never forgive me, and\nrightly. For instance, what right had I to make friends with Miss\nLavish?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Every right.
subQuotationList: ['Every right.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
When I was here for your sake? If I have vexed you it is equally true
that I have neglected you. Your mother will see this as clearly as I do,
when you tell her.
subQuotationList: ['When I was here for your sake? If I have vexed you it is equally true\nthat I have neglected you. Your mother will see this as clearly as I do,\nwhen you tell her.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Why need mother hear of it?
subQuotationList: ['Why need mother hear of it?']
speaker: Lucy
referringExpression: Lucy from a cowardly wish to improve the situation said

quoteText: But you tell her everything?
subQuotationList: ['But you tell her everything?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I suppose I do generally.
subQuotationList: ['I suppose I do generally.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I dare not break your confidence. There is something sacred in it.
Unless you feel that it is a thing you could not tell her.
subQuotationList: ['I dare not break your confidence. There is something sacred in it.\nUnless you feel that it is a thing you could not tell her.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Naturally I should have told her. But in case she should blame you in
any way, I promise I will not, I am very willing not to. I will never
speak of it either to her or to any one.
subQuotationList: ['Naturally I should have told her. But in case she should blame you in\nany way, I promise I will not, I am very willing not to. I will never\nspeak of it either to her or to any one.']
speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['I wish one word with you in the drawing-room, Mr. Emerson, please.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Good-night, Mr.
Emerson.
subQuotationList: ['Good-night, Mr.\nEmerson.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

It isn't true. It can't all be true. I want not to be
muddled. I want to grow older quickly.
subQuotationList: ["It isn't true. It can't all be true. I want not to be\nmuddled. I want to grow older quickly."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Go to bed at once, dear. You need all the rest you can get.
subQuotationList: ['Go to bed at once, dear. You need all the rest you can get.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Where aren't they? I
tell you I'm getting fairly sick.
subQuotationList: ["Where aren't they?", "I\ntell you I'm getting fairly sick."]

subQuotationList: ["For goodness' sake go out of my drawing-room, then?"]

subQuotationList: ['I think things are coming to a head,']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Time they did.
subQuotationList: ['Time they did.']
speaker: Freddy

subQuotationList: ['I am glad that Cecil is asking her this once more.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

subQuotationList: ["It's his third go, isn't it?"]
speaker: Freddy

subQuotationList: ['Freddy I do call the way you talk unkind.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I didn't mean to be unkind. But I do think Lucy might
have got this off her chest in Italy. I don't know how girls manage
things, but she can't have said properly before, or she wouldn't
have to say it again now. Over the whole thing--I can't explain--I do
feel so uncomfortable.
subQuotationList:
["I didn't mean to be unkind.", "But I do think Lucy might
have got this off her chest in Italy. I don't know how girls manage
things, but she can't have said", "properly before, or she wouldn't

subQuotationList: ['Do you indeed, dear? How interesting!']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: I feel--never mind.
subQuotationList: ['I feel--never mind.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Just listen to what I have written to Mrs. Vyse. I said: 'Dear Mrs.
Vyse.'
subQuotationList: ["Just listen to what I have written to Mrs. Vyse. I said: 'Dear Mrs.\nVyse.'"]

quoteText: Yes, mother, you told me. A jolly good letter.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, mother, you told me. A jolly good letter.']

quoteText: I said:
subQuotationList: ['I said:']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I was rather amused at Cecil asking my permission at all. He
has always gone in for unconventionality, and parents nowhere, and so
forth. When it comes to the point, he can't get on without me.
subQuotationList: ["I was rather amused at Cecil asking my permission at all. He\nhas always gone in for unconventionality, and parents nowhere, and so\nforth. When it comes to the point, he can't get on without me."]

subQuotationList: ['Nor me.']

speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

subQuotationList: ['He asked me for my permission also.']
speaker: Freddy

Why so? Why shouldn't my permission be

subQuotationList: ['Why so?', "Why shouldn't my permission be\nasked?"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
What do you know about Lucy or girls or anything? What ever did you

subQuotationList: ['What do you know about Lucy or girls or anything? What ever did you\nsay?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: I said to Cecil,
subQuotationList: ['I said to Cecil,']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: What a helpful answer!
subQuotationList: ['What a helpful answer!']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: The bother is this,
subQuotationList: ['The bother is this,']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Freddy, you must come. There they still are!
subQuotationList: ['Freddy, you must come. There they still are!']

quoteText: I don't see you ought to go peeping like that.
subQuotationList: ["I don't see you ought to go peeping like that."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Still page 322?
subQuotationList: ['Still page 322?']

referringExpression: she returned to the writingtable observing

subQuotationList: ['The bother is this: I have put my foot in it with Cecil most awfully.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Not content with 'permission', which I did
give--that is to say, I said,
subQuotationList: ["Not content with 'permission', which I did\ngive--that is to say, I said,"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
--well, not content with
that, he wanted to know whether I wasn't off my head with joy. He
practically put it like this: Wasn't it a splendid thing for Lucy and
for Windy Corner generally if he married her? And he would have an
answer--he said it would strengthen his hand.
subQuotationList:
["--well, not content with
that, he wanted to know whether I wasn't off my head with joy. He
practically put it like this: Wasn't it a splendid thing for Lucy and
for Windy Corner generally if he married her? And he would have an
answer--he said it would strengthen his hand."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I hope you gave a careful answer, dear.
subQuotationList: ['I hope you gave a careful answer, dear.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I answered 'No' There! Fly into a
stew! I can't help it--had to say it. I had to say no. He ought never to
have asked me.
subQuotationList: ["I answered 'No'", "There! Fly into a\nstew! I can't help it--had to say it. I had to say no. He ought never to\nhave asked me."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Ridiculous child! You think you're so holy and
truthful, but really it's only abominable conceit. Do you suppose that
a man like Cecil would take the slightest notice of anything you say? I
hope he boxed your ears. How dare you say no?
subQuotationList:
['Ridiculous child!', "You think you're so holy and
truthful, but really it's only abominable conceit. Do you suppose that

Oh, do keep quiet, mother! I had to say no when I couldn't say yes. I
tried to laugh as if I didn't mean what I said, and, as Cecil laughed
too, and went away, it may be all right. But I feel my foot's in it. Oh,
do keep quiet, though, and let a man do some work.
subQuotationList:
["Oh, do keep quiet, mother! I had to say no when I couldn't say yes. I
tried to laugh as if I didn't mean what I said, and, as Cecil laughed

do keep quiet, though, and let a man do some work."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
No, I shall not keep quiet. You know all that has passed between
them in Rome; you know why he is down here, and yet you deliberately
insult him, and try to turn him out of my house.
subQuotationList: ['No,', 'I shall not keep quiet. You know all that has passed between\nthem in Rome; you know why he is down here, and yet you deliberately\ninsult him, and try to turn him out of my house.']

Not a bit! I only let out I didn't like him. I don't hate
him, but I don't like him. What I mind is that he'll tell Lucy.
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit!', "I only let out I didn't like him. I don't hate\nhim, but I don't like him. What I mind is that he'll tell Lucy."]

Well, I like him, I know his mother; he's
good, he's clever, he's rich, he's well connected--Oh, you needn't kick
the piano! He's well connected--I'll say it again if you like: he's
well connected.
subQuotationList:

subQuotationList: ['And he has beautiful manners.']

I liked him till just now. I suppose it's having him spoiling Lucy's
first week at home; and it's also something that Mr. Beebe said, not
knowing.

Mr. Beebe? I don't
see how Mr. Beebe comes in.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Beebe?', "I don't\nsee how Mr. Beebe comes in."]

You know Mr. Beebe's funny way, when you never quite know what he
means. He said:
subQuotationList: ["You know Mr. Beebe's funny way, when you never quite know what he\nmeans. He said:"]

I was very cute, I
asked him what he meant. He said
subQuotationList: ['I was very cute, I\nasked him what he meant. He said']

I
couldn't make him say any more, but it set me thinking. Since Cecil has

Will this do? Then I put in at the top, I must write
the letter out again-- I
said that because I didn't want Mrs. Vyse to think us old-fashioned. She

Suppose Lucy marries Cecil, would she live in a flat, or in the

No, I'll cross that last bit out--it looks patronizing. I'll
stop at

Or shall I cross that out,

subQuotationList: ['Look out!']

speaker: Mr. Beebe

I should say so. Food is the thing one does get here--Don't sit in that
chair; young Honeychurch has left a bone in it.

quoteText:
I know, I know. I can't think why Mrs. Honeychurch allows

I met Sir Harry Otway as I came up; I have every reason to hope that I
am first in the field. He has bought Cissie and Albert from Mr. Flack!
subQuotationList: ['I met Sir Harry Otway as I came up; I have every reason to hope that I\nam first in the field. He has bought Cissie and Albert from Mr. Flack!']

quoteText: Has he indeed?
subQuotationList: ['Has he indeed?']

quoteText:

quoteText:
I'm shockingly stupid over local affairs, I can't even remember the difference between a Parish
Council and a Local Government Board. Perhaps there is no difference, or
perhaps those aren't the right names. I only go into the country to see
my friends and to enjoy the scenery. It is very remiss of me. Italy and
London are the only places where I don't feel to exist on sufferance.
subQuotationList:
["I'm shockingly stupid over local affairs,", "I can't even remember the difference between a Parish
Council and a Local Government Board. Perhaps there is no difference, or
perhaps those aren't the right names. I only go into the country to see
my friends and to enjoy the scenery. It is very remiss of me. Italy and
London are the only places where I don't feel to exist on sufferance."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Let me see, Mr. Vyse--I forget--what is your profession?
subQuotationList: ['Let me see, Mr. Vyse--I forget--what is your profession?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I have no profession, It is another example of my
decadence. My attitude--quite an indefensible one--is that so long as I
am no trouble to any one I have a right to do as I like. I know I ought
to be getting money out of people, or devoting myself to things I don't
care a straw about, but somehow, I've not been able to begin.
subQuotationList:
['I have no profession,', "It is another example of my
decadence. My attitude--quite an indefensible one--is that so long as I
am no trouble to any one I have a right to do as I like. I know I ought
to be getting money out of people, or devoting myself to things I don't

opportunity, the possession of leisure.
subQuotationList: ['You are very fortunate,', 'It is a wonderful\nopportunity, the possession of leisure.']

I am glad that you approve. I daren't face the healthy person--for
example, Freddy Honeychurch.
subQuotationList: ["I am glad that you approve. I daren't face the healthy person--for\nexample, Freddy Honeychurch."]

quoteText: Oh, Freddy's a good sort, isn't he?
subQuotationList: ["Oh, Freddy's a good sort, isn't he?"]

subQuotationList: ['Admirable. The sort who has made England what she is.']

that she begs your pardon when she hears you perfectly, and kicks the
chair-legs with her feet. The faults of Mary--I forget the faults of
Mary, but they are very grave. Shall we look in the garden?
subQuotationList:
['I suppose Anne never told them you were here. In this house one is so
coached in the servants the day one arrives. The fault of Anne is
that she begs your pardon when she hears you perfectly, and kicks the
chair-legs with her feet. The faults of Mary--I forget the faults of

The fault of Euphemia is that she will not, simply will not, chop the
suet sufficiently small.
