speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: She has none,
subQuotationList: ['She has none,']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: I quite agree. At present she has none.
subQuotationList: ['I quite agree. At present she has none.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: At present?
subQuotationList: ['At present?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I'm not cynical. I'm only thinking of my pet theory about Miss
Honeychurch. Does it seem reasonable that she should play so
wonderfully, and live so quietly? I suspect that one day she will be
wonderful in both. The water-tight compartments in her will break down,
and music and life will mingle. Then we shall have her heroically good,
heroically bad--too heroic, perhaps, to be good or bad.
subQuotationList:
["I'm not cynical. I'm only thinking of my pet theory about Miss
Honeychurch. Does it seem reasonable that she should play so
wonderfully, and live so quietly? I suspect that one day she will be
wonderful in both. The water-tight compartments in her will break down,
and music and life will mingle. Then we shall have her heroically good,
heroically bad--too heroic, perhaps, to be good or bad."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: And at present you think her not wonderful as far as life goes?
subQuotationList: ['And at present you think her not wonderful as far as life goes?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Well, I must say I've only seen her at Tunbridge Wells, where she was
not wonderful, and at Florence. Since I came to Summer Street she has
been away. You saw her, didn't you, at Rome and in the Alps. Oh, I
forgot; of course, you knew her before. No, she wasn't wonderful in
Florence either, but I kept on expecting that she would be.
subQuotationList:
["Well, I must say I've only seen her at Tunbridge Wells, where she was

quoteText: In what way?
subQuotationList: ['In what way?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I could as easily tell you what tune she'll play next. There was simply
the sense that she had found wings, and meant to use them. I can show
you a beautiful picture in my Italian diary: Miss Honeychurch as a
kite, Miss Bartlett holding the string. Picture number two: the string
breaks.
subQuotationList:
["I could as easily tell you what tune she'll play next. There was simply

quoteText: But the string never broke?
subQuotationList: ['But the string never broke?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
No. I mightn't have seen Miss Honeychurch rise, but I should certainly
have heard Miss Bartlett fall.
subQuotationList: ["No. I mightn't have seen Miss Honeychurch rise, but I should certainly\nhave heard Miss Bartlett fall."]

quoteText: It has broken now,
subQuotationList: ['It has broken now,']

quoteText: Broken? What do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['Broken? What do you mean?']

quoteText: I meant, that she is going to marry me.
subQuotationList: ['I meant,', 'that she is going to marry me.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I am sorry; I must apologize. I had no idea you were intimate with her,
or I should never have talked in this flippant, superficial way. Mr.
Vyse, you ought to have stopped me.
subQuotationList: ['I am sorry; I must apologize. I had no idea you were intimate with her,\nor I should never have talked in this flippant, superficial way. Mr.\nVyse, you ought to have stopped me.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I am sorry I have given you a shock, I fear that
Lucy's choice does not meet with your approval.
subQuotationList: ['I am sorry I have given you a shock,', "I fear that\nLucy's choice does not meet with your approval."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Not that. But you ought to have stopped me. I know Miss Honeychurch
only a little as time goes. Perhaps I oughtn't to have discussed her so
freely with any one; certainly not with you.
subQuotationList: ["Not that. But you ought to have stopped me. I know Miss Honeychurch\nonly a little as time goes. Perhaps I oughtn't to have discussed her so\nfreely with any one; certainly not with you."]

quoteText: You are conscious of having said something indiscreet?
subQuotationList: ['You are conscious of having said something indiscreet?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
No, I have said nothing indiscreet. I foresaw at Florence that her
quiet, uneventful childhood must end, and it has ended. I realized dimly
enough that she might take some momentous step. She has taken it. She
has learnt--you will let me talk freely, as I have begun freely--she has
learnt what it is to love: the greatest lesson, some people will tell
you, that our earthly life provides.
subQuotationList:
['No, I have said nothing indiscreet. I foresaw at Florence that her

She has
learnt through you,
subQuotationList: ['She has\nlearnt through you,']

quoteText:
let it be your care that her knowledge is profitable to
her.
subQuotationList: ['let it be your care that her knowledge is profitable to\nher.']

quoteText: Grazie tante!
subQuotationList: ['Grazie tante!']

quoteText: Have you heard? Oh, Mr. Beebe, have you heard the news?
subQuotationList: ['Have you heard?', 'Oh, Mr. Beebe, have you heard the news?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Indeed I have! Mrs. Honeychurch, I'm going to do what I am always supposed to do, but
generally I'm too shy. I want to invoke every kind of blessing on
them, grave and gay, great and small. I want them all their lives to be
supremely good and supremely happy as husband and wife, as father and
mother. And now I want my tea.
subQuotationList:

You only asked for it just in time, How dare you
be serious at Windy Corner?
subQuotationList: ['You only asked for it just in time,', 'How dare you\nbe serious at Windy Corner?']

subQuotationList: ['Fiasco']

quoteText: I am so sorry that you were stranded.
subQuotationList: ['I am so sorry that you were stranded.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Not that, but the congratulations. It is so disgusting, the way an
engagement is regarded as public property--a kind of waste place where
every outsider may shoot his vulgar sentiment. All those old women
smirking!
subQuotationList:
['Not that, but the congratulations. It is so disgusting, the way an
engagement is regarded as public property--a kind of waste place where
every outsider may shoot his vulgar sentiment. All those old women
smirking!']

One has to go through it, I suppose. They won't notice us so much next
time.
subQuotationList: ["One has to go through it, I suppose. They won't notice us so much next\ntime."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
But my point is that their whole attitude is wrong. An
engagement--horrid word in the first place--is a private matter, and
should be treated as such.
subQuotationList: ['But my point is that their whole attitude is wrong. An\nengagement--horrid word in the first place--is a private matter, and\nshould be treated as such.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: How tiresome! Couldn't you have escaped to tennis?
subQuotationList: ['How tiresome!', "Couldn't you have escaped to tennis?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I don't play tennis--at least, not in public. The neighbourhood is
deprived of the romance of me being athletic. Such romance as I have is
that of the Inglese Italianato.
subQuotationList: ["I don't play tennis--at least, not in public. The neighbourhood is\ndeprived of the romance of me being athletic. Such romance as I have is\nthat of the Inglese Italianato."]

subQuotationList: ['Inglese Italianato?']

quoteText:
Well, I cannot help it if they do disapprove of me. There
are certain irremovable barriers between myself and them, and I must
accept them.
subQuotationList: ['Well,', 'I cannot help it if they do disapprove of me. There\nare certain irremovable barriers between myself and them, and I must\naccept them.']

It makes a difference doesn't it, whether we fully fence ourselves in,
or whether we are fenced out by the barriers of others?

Difference? I don't see any
difference. Fences are fences, especially when they are in the same
place.

This is me. That's Windy Corner. The rest of the
pattern is the other people. Motives are all very well, but the fence

Now, a clergyman that I do hate, a clergyman that does have fences, and the most dreadful
ones, is Mr. Eager, the English chaplain at Florence. He was truly
insincere--not merely the manner unfortunate. He was a snob, and so
conceited, and he did say such unkind things.

Well, I did try to sift the thing. Mr. Eager would never come to the

his wife--had murdered her in the sight of God.

I don't know. I hate him. I've heard him lecture on Giotto. I hate him.
Nothing can hide a petty nature. I HATE him.
subQuotationList: ["I don't know. I hate him. I've heard him lecture on Giotto. I hate him.\nNothing can hide a petty nature. I HATE him."]

My goodness gracious me, child! You'll blow
my head off! Whatever is there to shout over? I forbid you and Cecil to
hate any more clergymen.
subQuotationList: ['My goodness gracious me, child!', "You'll blow\nmy head off! Whatever is there to shout over? I forbid you and Cecil to\nhate any more clergymen."]

quoteText:
I count myself a lucky person, When I'm in London I
feel I could never live out of it. When I'm in the country I feel the
same about the country. After all, I do believe that birds and trees and
the sky are the most wonderful things in life, and that the people who
live amongst them must be the best. It's true that in nine cases out of
ten they don't seem to notice anything. The country gentleman and
the country labourer are each in their way the most depressing of
companions. Yet they may have a tacit sympathy with the workings
of Nature which is denied to us of the town. Do you feel that, Mrs.
Honeychurch?

Let us take Mrs. Honeychurch's advice and hate clergymen no

Miss Flack.

and

landlord. But it is such an awkward size. It is too large for the
peasant class and too small for any one the least like ourselves.

a perfect paradise for a bank clerk.

Vyse. It will attract the wrong type of people. The train service has

quoteText:
Indeed you may! Here we are with the difficulty solved
already. How delightful it is! Extra facilities--please tell them they
shall have extra facilities, for I shall have no agents' fees. Oh,
the agents! The appalling people they have sent me! One woman, when
I wrote--a tactful letter, you know--asking her to explain her social
position to me, replied that she would pay the rent in advance. As
if one cares about that! And several references I took up were most
unsatisfactory--people swindlers, or not respectable. And oh, the
deceit! I have seen a good deal of the seamy side this last week. The
deceit of the most promising people. My dear Lucy, the deceit!

quoteText:
My advice, is to have nothing to do with
Lucy and her decayed gentlewomen at all. I know the type. Preserve me
from people who have seen better days, and bring heirlooms with them
that make the house smell stuffy. It's a sad thing, but I'd far rather
let to someone who is going up in the world than to someone who has
come down.

they somehow keep it to themselves. It doesn't spread so. Give me a
man--of course, provided he's clean.

quoteText: I can't help it. It would be wrong not to loathe that man.
subQuotationList: ["I can't help it. It would be wrong not to loathe that man."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: He isn't clever, but really he is nice.
subQuotationList: ["He isn't clever, but really he is nice."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, Lucy, he stands for all that is bad in country life. In London he
would keep his place. He would belong to a brainless club, and his wife
would give brainless dinner parties. But down here he acts the little
god with his gentility, and his patronage, and his sham aesthetics, and
everyone--even your mother--is taken in.
subQuotationList:
['No, Lucy, he stands for all that is bad in country life. In London he
would keep his place. He would belong to a brainless club, and his wife
would give brainless dinner parties. But down here he acts the little
god with his gentility, and his patronage, and his sham aesthetics, and
everyone--even your mother--is taken in.']
speaker: Cecil
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Lucy'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch']]]

quoteText: All that you say is quite true, I wonder whether--whether it matters so very much.
subQuotationList: ['All that you say is quite true,', 'I wonder whether--whether it matters so very much.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It matters supremely. Sir Harry is the essence of that garden-party.
Oh, goodness, how cross I feel! How I do hope he'll get some vulgar
tenant in that villa--some woman so really vulgar that he'll notice
it. GENTLEFOLKS! Ugh! with his bald head and retreating chin! But let's
forget him.
subQuotationList:
["It matters supremely. Sir Harry is the essence of that garden-party.
Oh, goodness, how cross I feel! How I do hope he'll get some vulgar
tenant in that villa--some woman so really vulgar that he'll notice
it. GENTLEFOLKS! Ugh! with his bald head and retreating chin! But let's
forget him."]
speaker: Cecil
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Cecil', 'Lucy'], ['Sir Harry Otway']]]

quoteText: Which way shall we go?
subQuotationList: ['Which way shall we go?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Are there two ways?
subQuotationList: ['Are there two ways?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Perhaps the road is more sensible, as we're got up smart.
subQuotationList: ["Perhaps the road is more sensible, as we're got up smart."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I'd rather go through the wood, Why is it,
Lucy, that you always say the road? Do you know that you have never once
been with me in the fields or the wood since we were engaged?
subQuotationList: ["I'd rather go through the wood,", 'Why is it,\nLucy, that you always say the road? Do you know that you have never once\nbeen with me in the fields or the wood since we were engaged?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Haven't I? The wood, then,
subQuotationList: ["Haven't I? The wood, then,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I had got an idea--I dare say wrongly--that you feel more at home with
me in a room.
subQuotationList: ['I had got an idea--I dare say wrongly--that you feel more at home with\nme in a room.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: A room?
subQuotationList: ['A room?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Yes. Or, at the most, in a garden, or on a road. Never in the real
country like this.
subQuotationList: ['Yes. Or, at the most, in a garden, or on a road. Never in the real\ncountry like this.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Oh, Cecil, whatever do you mean? I have never felt anything of the
sort. You talk as if I was a kind of poetess sort of person.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Cecil, whatever do you mean? I have never felt anything of the\nsort. You talk as if I was a kind of poetess sort of person.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I don't know that you aren't. I connect you with a view--a certain type
of view. Why shouldn't you connect me with a room?
subQuotationList: ["I don't know that you aren't. I connect you with a view--a certain type\nof view. Why shouldn't you connect me with a room?"]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Do you know that you're right? I do. I must be a poetess after all.
When I think of you it's always as in a room. How funny!
subQuotationList: ["Do you know that you're right? I do. I must be a poetess after all.\nWhen I think of you it's always as in a room. How funny!"]
speaker: Lucy
referringExpression: She reflected a moment and then said

quoteText: A drawing-room, pray? With no view?
subQuotationList: ['A drawing-room, pray? With no view?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Yes, with no view, I fancy. Why not?
subQuotationList: ['Yes, with no view, I fancy. Why not?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I'd rather, that you connected me with the open
air.
subQuotationList: ["I'd rather,", 'that you connected me with the open\nair.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Oh, Cecil, whatever do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Cecil, whatever do you mean?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The Sacred Lake!
subQuotationList: ['The Sacred Lake!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Why do you call it that?
subQuotationList: ['Why do you call it that?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I can't remember why. I suppose it comes out of some book. It's only a
puddle now, but you see that stream going through it? Well, a good deal
of water comes down after heavy rains, and can't get away at once, and
the pool becomes quite large and beautiful. Then Freddy used to bathe
there. He is very fond of it.
subQuotationList:
["I can't remember why. I suppose it comes out of some book. It's only a
puddle now, but you see that stream going through it? Well, a good deal
of water comes down after heavy rains, and can't get away at once, and
the pool becomes quite large and beautiful. Then Freddy used to bathe
there. He is very fond of it."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: And you?
subQuotationList: ['And you?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I bathed
here, too, till I was found out. Then there was a row.
subQuotationList: ['I bathed\nhere, too, till I was found out. Then there was a row.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Who found you out?
subQuotationList: ['Who found you out?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Charlotte, She was stopping with us.
Charlotte--Charlotte.
subQuotationList: ['Charlotte,', 'She was stopping with us.\nCharlotte--Charlotte.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Poor girl!
subQuotationList: ['Poor girl!']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Lucy!
subQuotationList: ['Lucy!']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Yes, I suppose we ought to be going,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, I suppose we ought to be going,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy, I want to ask something of you that I have never asked before.
subQuotationList: ['Lucy, I want to ask something of you that I have never asked before.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: What, Cecil?
subQuotationList: ['What, Cecil?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Hitherto never--not even that day on the lawn when you agreed to marry
me--
subQuotationList: ['Hitherto never--not even that day on the lawn when you agreed to marry\nme--']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Yes?
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Up to now I have never kissed you.
subQuotationList: ['Up to now I have never kissed you.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: No--more you have,
subQuotationList: ['No--more you have,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Then I ask you--may I now?
subQuotationList: ['Then I ask you--may I now?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Of course, you may, Cecil. You might before. I can't run at you, you
know.
subQuotationList: ["Of course, you may, Cecil. You might before. I can't run at you, you\nknow."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Emerson was the name, not Harris.
subQuotationList: ['Emerson was the name, not Harris.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What name?
subQuotationList: ['What name?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: The old man's.
subQuotationList: ["The old man's."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What old man?
subQuotationList: ['What old man?']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: That old man I told you about. The one Mr. Eager was so unkind to.
subQuotationList: ['That old man I told you about. The one Mr. Eager was so unkind to.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I cannot think
what people are doing, but it is extremely fortunate
for the children.
subQuotationList: ['I cannot think\nwhat people are doing,', 'but it is extremely fortunate\nfor the children.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Oh, it has been such a nuisance--first he, then they--no one knowing
what they wanted, and everyone so tiresome.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, it has been such a nuisance--first he, then they--no one knowing\nwhat they wanted, and everyone so tiresome.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
But they really are coming now, I wrote to Miss
Teresa a few days ago--she was wondering how often the butcher called,
and my reply of once a month must have impressed her favourably. They
are coming. I heard from them this morning.
subQuotationList:
['But they really are coming now,', 'I wrote to Miss
Teresa a few days ago--she was wondering how often the butcher called,
and my reply of once a month must have impressed her favourably. They
are coming. I heard from them this morning.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Teresa']], [['Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Teresa']]]

quoteText:
I shall hate those Miss Alans! Just because
they're old and silly one's expected to say 'How sweet!' I hate
their 'if'-ing and 'but'-ing and 'and'-ing. And poor Lucy--serve her
right--worn to a shadow.
subQuotationList:
['I shall hate those Miss Alans!', "Just because
they're old and silly one's expected to say 'How sweet!' I hate
their 'if'-ing and 'but'-ing and 'and'-ing. And poor Lucy--serve her
right--worn to a shadow."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Well, if they are coming--No, Minnie, not Saturn.
subQuotationList: ['Well, if they are coming--No, Minnie, not Saturn.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
If they are coming, Sir Harry will let them move
in before the twenty-ninth, and he will cross out the clause about
whitewashing the ceilings, because it made them nervous, and put in the
fair wear and tear one.--That doesn't count. I told you not Saturn.
subQuotationList:
["If they are coming, Sir Harry will let them move
in before the twenty-ninth, and he will cross out the clause about
whitewashing the ceilings, because it made them nervous, and put in the
fair wear and tear one.--That doesn't count. I told you not Saturn."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Teresa'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Miss Teresa'], ['Minnie Beebe']]]

quoteText: Saturn's all right for bumble-puppy, Minnie, don't you listen to her.
subQuotationList: ["Saturn's all right for bumble-puppy,", "Minnie, don't you listen to her."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Saturn doesn't bounce.
subQuotationList: ["Saturn doesn't bounce."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Saturn bounces enough.
subQuotationList: ['Saturn bounces enough.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: No, he doesn't.
subQuotationList: ["No, he doesn't."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Well; he bounces better than the Beautiful White Devil.
subQuotationList: ['Well; he bounces better than the Beautiful White Devil.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Hush, dear,
subQuotationList: ['Hush, dear,']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
But look at Lucy--complaining of Saturn, and all the time's got the
Beautiful White Devil in her hand, ready to plug it in. That's right,
Minnie, go for her--get her over the shins with the racquet--get her
over the shins!
subQuotationList:
["But look at Lucy--complaining of Saturn, and all the time's got the
Beautiful White Devil in her hand, ready to plug it in. That's right,
Minnie, go for her--get her over the shins with the racquet--get her
over the shins!"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
The name of this ball is Vittoria
Corombona, please.
subQuotationList: ['The name of this ball is Vittoria\nCorombona, please.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
referringExpression: Mr Beebe picked it up and said

quoteText: I wish the Miss Alans could see this,
subQuotationList: ['I wish the Miss Alans could see this,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Who are the Miss Alans?
subQuotationList: ['Who are the Miss Alans?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: They have taken Cissie Villa.
subQuotationList: ['They have taken Cissie Villa.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: That wasn't the name--
subQuotationList: ["That wasn't the name--"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Wasn't what name?
subQuotationList: ["Wasn't what name?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Alan wasn't the name of the people Sir Harry's let to.
subQuotationList: ["Alan wasn't the name of the people Sir Harry's let to."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Nonsense, Freddy! You know nothing about it.
subQuotationList: ['Nonsense, Freddy! You know nothing about it.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Nonsense yourself! I've this minute seen him. He said to me:
subQuotationList: ["Nonsense yourself! I've this minute seen him. He said to me:"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
I said, 'ooray, old boy!'
and slapped him on the back
subQuotationList: ["I said, 'ooray, old boy!'\nand slapped him on the back"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Exactly. The Miss Alans?
subQuotationList: ['Exactly. The Miss Alans?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Rather not. More like Anderson.
subQuotationList: ['Rather not. More like Anderson.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Oh, good gracious, there isn't going to be another muddle! Do you notice, Lucy, I'm always right? I said
don't interfere with Cissie Villa. I'm always right. I'm quite uneasy at
being always right so often.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, good gracious, there isn't going to be another muddle!", "Do you notice, Lucy, I'm always right? I said\ndon't interfere with Cissie Villa. I'm always right. I'm quite uneasy at\nbeing always right so often."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
It's only another muddle of Freddy's. Freddy doesn't even know the name
of the people he pretends have taken it instead.
subQuotationList: ["It's only another muddle of Freddy's. Freddy doesn't even know the name\nof the people he pretends have taken it instead."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Yes, I do. I've got it. Emerson.
subQuotationList: ["Yes, I do. I've got it. Emerson."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: What name?
subQuotationList: ['What name?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Emerson. I'll bet you anything you like.
subQuotationList: ["Emerson. I'll bet you anything you like."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
What a weathercock Sir Harry is, I wish I had
never bothered over it at all.
subQuotationList: ['What a weathercock Sir Harry is,', 'I wish I had\nnever bothered over it at all.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Emerson, Freddy? Do you know what Emersons they are?
subQuotationList: ['Emerson, Freddy? Do you know what Emersons they are?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText: I don't know whether they're any Emersons,
subQuotationList: ["I don't know whether they're any Emersons,"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I trust they are the right sort of person. All right, Lucy
subQuotationList: ['I trust they are the right sort of person. All right, Lucy']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I see you looking down your nose and thinking your
mother's a snob. But there is a right sort and a wrong sort, and it's
affectation to pretend there isn't.
subQuotationList: ["I see you looking down your nose and thinking your\nmother's a snob. But there is a right sort and a wrong sort, and it's\naffectation to pretend there isn't."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Emerson's a common enough name,
subQuotationList: ["Emerson's a common enough name,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I was merely going to remark, Freddy, that I trusted they were no
relations of Emerson the philosopher, a most trying man. Pray, does that
satisfy you?
subQuotationList: ['I was merely going to remark, Freddy, that I trusted they were no\nrelations of Emerson the philosopher, a most trying man. Pray, does that\nsatisfy you?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Oh, yes, And you will be satisfied, too, for they're
friends of Cecil; so you and the other country
families will be able to call in perfect safety.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, yes,', "And you will be satisfied, too, for they're\nfriends of Cecil; so", 'you and the other country\nfamilies will be able to call in perfect safety.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: CECIL?
subQuotationList: ['CECIL?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Don't be rude, dear, Lucy, don't screech.
It's a new bad habit you're getting into.
subQuotationList: ["Don't be rude, dear,", "Lucy, don't screech.\nIt's a new bad habit you're getting into."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: But has Cecil--
subQuotationList: ['But has Cecil--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Friends of Cecil's,
subQuotationList: ["Friends of Cecil's,"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
But Cecil's Emersons--they can't possibly be the
same ones--there is that--
subQuotationList: ["But Cecil's Emersons--they can't possibly be the\nsame ones--there is that--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
The Emersons who were at Florence, do you mean? No, I don't suppose it
will prove to be them. It is probably a long cry from them to friends
of Mr. Vyse's. Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch, the oddest people! The queerest
people! For our part we liked them, didn't we?
subQuotationList:
["The Emersons who were at Florence, do you mean? No, I don't suppose it
will prove to be them. It is probably a long cry from them to friends
of Mr. Vyse's. Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch, the oddest people! The queerest
people! For our part we liked them, didn't we?"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

There was a great scene over some violets. They picked violets and
filled all the vases in the room of these very Miss Alans who have
failed to come to Cissie Villa. Poor little ladies! So shocked and so
pleased. It used to be one of Miss Catharine's great stories. it began. They found the whole room a mass of
blue--vases and jugs--and the story ends with It is all very difficult. Yes, I always connect those
Florentine Emersons with violets.

speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Fiasco's done you this time,
subQuotationList: ["Fiasco's done you this time,"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
These particular Emersons consisted of a father and a son--the son
a goodly, if not a good young man; not a fool, I fancy, but very
immature--pessimism, et cetera. Our special joy was the father--such a
sentimental darling, and people declared he had murdered his wife.
subQuotationList:
['These particular Emersons consisted of a father and a son--the son
a goodly, if not a good young man; not a fool, I fancy, but very
immature--pessimism, et cetera. Our special joy was the father--such a

quoteText:
Murdered his wife? Lucy, don't desert us--go
on playing bumble-puppy. Really, the Pension Bertolini must have been
the oddest place. That's the second murderer I've heard of as being
there. Whatever was Charlotte doing to stop? By-the-by, we really must
ask Charlotte here some time.
subQuotationList:
['Murdered his wife?', "Lucy, don't desert us--go
on playing bumble-puppy. Really, the Pension Bertolini must have been

quoteText: Oh, don't go!
subQuotationList: ["Oh, don't go!"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
I must go, Don't be silly. You always overdo it
when you play.
subQuotationList: ['I must go,', "Don't be silly. You always overdo it\nwhen you play."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Harris!
subQuotationList: ['Harris!']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Cecil!
subQuotationList: ['Cecil!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Hullo! I was hoping you'd come. I heard you all
bear-gardening, but there's better fun up here. I, even I, have won a
great victory for the Comic Muse. George Meredith's right--the cause of
Comedy and the cause of Truth are really the same; and I, even I, have
found tenants for the distressful Cissie Villa. Don't be angry! Don't be
angry! You'll forgive me when you hear it all.
subQuotationList:
['Hullo!', "I was hoping you'd come. I heard you all
bear-gardening, but there's better fun up here. I, even I, have won a
great victory for the Comic Muse. George Meredith's right--the cause of
Comedy and the cause of Truth are really the same; and I, even I, have
found tenants for the distressful Cissie Villa. Don't be angry! Don't be
angry! You'll forgive me when you hear it all."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I have heard, Freddy has told us. Naughty Cecil! I suppose
I must forgive you. Just think of all the trouble I took for nothing!
Certainly the Miss Alans are a little tiresome, and I'd rather have nice
friends of yours. But you oughtn't to tease one so.
subQuotationList:
['I have heard,', "Freddy has told us. Naughty Cecil! I suppose
I must forgive you. Just think of all the trouble I took for nothing!
Certainly the Miss Alans are a little tiresome, and I'd rather have nice
friends of yours. But you oughtn't to tease one so."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Friends of mine? But, Lucy, the whole joke is to come!
Come here. Do you know where
I met these desirable tenants? In the National Gallery, when I was up to
see my mother last week.
subQuotationList:
['Friends of mine?', 'But, Lucy, the whole joke is to come!
Come here.', 'Do you know where
I met these desirable tenants? In the National Gallery, when I was up to
see my mother last week.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
What an odd place to meet people! I don't quite
understand.
subQuotationList: ['What an odd place to meet people!', "I don't quite\nunderstand."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
In the Umbrian Room. Absolute strangers. They were admiring Luca
Signorelli--of course, quite stupidly. However, we got talking, and they
refreshed me not a little. They had been to Italy.
subQuotationList: ['In the Umbrian Room. Absolute strangers. They were admiring Luca\nSignorelli--of course, quite stupidly. However, we got talking, and they\nrefreshed me not a little. They had been to Italy.']
speaker: Cecil
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Cecil', 'George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

quoteText: But, Cecil--
subQuotationList: ['But, Cecil--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
In the course of conversation they said that they wanted a country
cottage--the father to live there, the son to run down for week-ends.
I thought, 'What a chance of scoring off Sir Harry!' and I took
their address and a London reference, found they weren't actual
blackguards--it was great sport--and wrote to him, making out--
subQuotationList:
["In the course of conversation they said that they wanted a country
cottage--the father to live there, the son to run down for week-ends.
I thought, 'What a chance of scoring off Sir Harry!' and I took
their address and a London reference, found they weren't actual
blackguards--it was great sport--and wrote to him, making out--"]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: Cecil! No, it's not fair. I've probably met them before--
subQuotationList: ["Cecil! No, it's not fair. I've probably met them before--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Perfectly fair. Anything is fair that punishes a snob. That old man
will do the neighbourhood a world of good. Sir Harry is too disgusting
with his 'decayed gentlewomen.' I meant to read him a lesson some time.
No, Lucy, the classes ought to mix, and before long you'll agree with
me. There ought to be intermarriage--all sorts of things. I believe in
democracy--
subQuotationList:
["Perfectly fair. Anything is fair that punishes a snob. That old man
will do the neighbourhood a world of good. Sir Harry is too disgusting
with his 'decayed gentlewomen.' I meant to read him a lesson some time.
No, Lucy, the classes ought to mix, and before long you'll agree with
me. There ought to be intermarriage--all sorts of things. I believe in
democracy--"]

had no business to undo my work about the Miss Alans, and make me look
ridiculous. You call it scoring off Sir Harry, but do you realize that
it is all at my expense? I consider it most disloyal of you.

subQuotationList: ['Her music always was wonderful.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Yes, but she is purging off the Honeychurch taint, most excellent
Honeychurches, but you know what I mean. She is not always quoting
servants, or asking one how the pudding is made.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, but she is purging off the Honeychurch taint, most excellent\nHoneychurches, but you know what I mean. She is not always quoting\nservants, or asking one how the pudding is made.']

quoteText: Italy has done it.
subQuotationList: ['Italy has done it.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Perhaps, It is just possible. Cecil, mind you marry her next January.
She is one of us already.
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps,', 'It is just possible. Cecil, mind you marry her next January.\nShe is one of us already.']
speaker: Mrs. Vyse

quoteText:
But her music! The style of her! How she kept to
Schumann when, like an idiot, I wanted Beethoven. Schumann was right for
this evening. Schumann was the thing. Do you know, mother, I shall have
our children educated just like Lucy. Bring them up among honest country
folks for freshness, send them to Italy for subtlety, and then--not
till then--let them come to London. I don't believe in these London
educations--
subQuotationList:
['But her music!', "The style of her! How she kept to
Schumann when, like an idiot, I wanted Beethoven. Schumann was right for

folks for freshness, send them to Italy for subtlety, and then--not

speaker: Lucy

You
should have heard us talking about you, dear. He admires you more than
ever. Dream of that.

subQuotationList: ["I've brought someone to see you."]

subQuotationList: ["I'll be down in a minute."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Are these people great readers? Are they that
sort?
subQuotationList: ['Are these people great readers?', 'Are they that\nsort?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
I fancy they know how to read--a rare accomplishment. What have they
got? Byron. Exactly. A Shropshire Lad. Never heard of it. The Way of
All Flesh. Never heard of it. Gibbon. Hullo! dear George reads German.
Um--um--Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, and so we go on. Well, I suppose your
generation knows its own business, Honeychurch.
subQuotationList:
['I fancy they know how to read--a rare accomplishment. What have they

I know. Isn't it jolly? I like that. I'm certain that's the old man's
doing.

speaker: Mr. Beebe

subQuotationList: ["The same as Lucy's got."]

Yes, very, She and Cecil are thicker

subQuotationList: ["That's good hearing."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

Lucy used to be nearly as stupid as I am, but it'll be very different
now, mother thinks. She will read all kinds of books.

subQuotationList: ['So will you.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

Only medical books. Not books that you can talk about afterwards. Cecil

are all kinds of things in it that we have never noticed. Cecil says--

What on earth are those people doing upstairs? Emerson--we think we'll
come another time.

speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, a neighbour.
subQuotationList: ['Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, a neighbour.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
How d'ye do? Come and have
a bathe.
subQuotationList: ["How d'ye do? Come and have\na bathe."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Oh, all right,
subQuotationList: ['Oh, all right,']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
That's the best conversational opening I've ever heard. But I'm afraid
it will only act between men. Can you picture a lady who has been
introduced to another lady by a third lady opening civilities with 'How
do you do? Come and have a bathe'? And yet you will tell me that the
sexes are equal.
subQuotationList:
["That's the best conversational opening I've ever heard. But I'm afraid
it will only act between men. Can you picture a lady who has been
introduced to another lady by a third lady opening civilities with 'How
do you do? Come and have a bathe'? And yet you will tell me that the
sexes are equal."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I tell you that they shall be, Good afternoon, Mr. Beebe. I tell you they shall
be comrades, and George thinks the same.
subQuotationList: ['I tell you that they shall be,', 'Good afternoon, Mr. Beebe. I tell you they shall\nbe comrades, and George thinks the same.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: We are to raise ladies to our level?
subQuotationList: ['We are to raise ladies to our level?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
The Garden of Eden, which you
place in the past, is really yet to come. We shall enter it when we no
longer despise our bodies.
subQuotationList: ['The Garden of Eden,', 'which you\nplace in the past, is really yet to come. We shall enter it when we no\nlonger despise our bodies.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
In this--not in other things--we men are ahead. We despise the body
less than women do. But not until we are comrades shall we enter the
garden.
subQuotationList: ['In this--not in other things--we men are ahead. We despise the body\nless than women do. But not until we are comrades shall we enter the\ngarden.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: I say, what about this bathe?
subQuotationList: ['I say, what about this bathe?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
I believed in a return to Nature once. But how can we return to
Nature when we have never been with her? To-day, I believe that we must
discover Nature. After many conquests we shall attain simplicity. It is
our heritage.
subQuotationList:
['I believed in a return to Nature once. But how can we return to
Nature when we have never been with her? To-day, I believe that we must
discover Nature. After many conquests we shall attain simplicity. It is
our heritage.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, whose sister you will remember at
Florence.
subQuotationList: ['Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, whose sister you will remember at\nFlorence.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
How do you do? Very glad to see you, and that you are taking George for
a bathe. Very glad to hear that your sister is going to marry. Marriage
is a duty. I am sure that she will be happy, for we know Mr. Vyse, too.
He has been most kind. He met us by chance in the National Gallery, and
arranged everything about this delightful house. Though I hope I have
not vexed Sir Harry Otway. I have met so few Liberal landowners, and
I was anxious to compare his attitude towards the game laws with the
Conservative attitude. Ah, this wind! You do well to bathe. Yours is a
glorious country, Honeychurch!
subQuotationList:
['How do you do? Very glad to see you, and that you are taking George for
a bathe. Very glad to hear that your sister is going to marry. Marriage
is a duty. I am sure that she will be happy, for we know Mr. Vyse, too.
He has been most kind. He met us by chance in the National Gallery, and
arranged everything about this delightful house. Though I hope I have
not vexed Sir Harry Otway. I have met so few Liberal landowners, and
I was anxious to compare his attitude towards the game laws with the
Conservative attitude. Ah, this wind! You do well to bathe. Yours is a

quoteText:
Not a bit! I must--that is to say, I have to--have
the pleasure of calling on you later on, my mother says, I hope.
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit!', 'I must--that is to say, I have to--have\nthe pleasure of calling on you later on, my mother says, I hope.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
CALL, my lad? Who taught us that drawing-room twaddle? Call on your
grandmother! Listen to the wind among the pines! Yours is a glorious
country.

speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Mr. Emerson, he will call, I shall call; you or your son will return
our calls before ten days have elapsed. I trust that you have realized
about the ten days' interval. It does not count that I helped you with
the stair-eyes yesterday. It does not count that they are going to bathe
this afternoon.
subQuotationList:
["Mr. Emerson, he will call, I shall call; you or your son will return
our calls before ten days have elapsed. I trust that you have realized
about the ten days' interval. It does not count that I helped you with
the stair-eyes yesterday. It does not count that they are going to bathe

quoteText:
Yes, go and bathe, George. Why do you dawdle talking? Bring them back
to tea. Bring back some milk, cakes, honey. The change will do you good.
George has been working very hard at his office. I can't believe he's
well.
subQuotationList:
["Yes, go and bathe, George. Why do you dawdle talking? Bring them back
to tea. Bring back some milk, cakes, honey. The change will do you good.
George has been working very hard at his office. I can't believe he's
well."]

quoteText:
Do you really want this bathe? It is only a pond,
don't you know. I dare say you are used to something better.
subQuotationList: ['Do you really want this bathe?', "It is only a pond,\ndon't you know. I dare say you are used to something better."]

quoteText:
And what a coincidence that you should meet Mr. Vyse! Did you realize
that you would find all the Pension Bertolini down here?
subQuotationList: ['And what a coincidence that you should meet Mr. Vyse! Did you realize\nthat you would find all the Pension Bertolini down here?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: I did not. Miss Lavish told me.
subQuotationList: ['I did not. Miss Lavish told me.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
When I was a young man, I always meant to write a 'History of
Coincidence.'
subQuotationList: ["When I was a young man, I always meant to write a 'History of\nCoincidence.'"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Though, as a matter of fact, coincidences are much rarer than we
suppose. For example, it isn't purely coincidentally that you are here
now, when one comes to reflect.
subQuotationList: ["Though, as a matter of fact, coincidences are much rarer than we\nsuppose. For example, it isn't purely coincidentally that you are here\nnow, when one comes to reflect."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
It is. I have reflected. It is Fate. Everything is Fate. We are flung
together by Fate, drawn apart by Fate--flung together, drawn apart. The
twelve winds blow us--we settle nothing--
subQuotationList: ['It is. I have reflected. It is Fate. Everything is Fate. We are flung\ntogether by Fate, drawn apart by Fate--flung together, drawn apart. The\ntwelve winds blow us--we settle nothing--']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: You have not reflected at all,
subQuotationList: ['You have not reflected at all,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Italy.
subQuotationList: ['Italy.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
And where did you meet Mr. Vyse, who is going to marry Miss
Honeychurch?
subQuotationList: ['And where did you meet Mr. Vyse, who is going to marry Miss\nHoneychurch?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: National Gallery.
subQuotationList: ['National Gallery.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Looking at Italian art. There you are, and yet you talk of coincidence
and Fate. You naturally seek out things Italian, and so do we and our
friends. This narrows the field immeasurably we meet again in it.
subQuotationList: ['Looking at Italian art. There you are, and yet you talk of coincidence\nand Fate. You naturally seek out things Italian, and so do we and our\nfriends. This narrows the field immeasurably we meet again in it.']

quoteText:
It is Fate that I am here, But you can call it
Italy if it makes you less unhappy.
subQuotationList: ['It is Fate that I am here,', 'But you can call it\nItaly if it makes you less unhappy.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
And so for this and for other reasons my 'History of Coincidence' is
still to write.
subQuotationList: ["And so for this and for other reasons my 'History of Coincidence' is\nstill to write."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
We are all so glad that you
have come.
subQuotationList: ['We are all so glad that you\nhave come.']

Aren't those masses of willow-herb splendid? I love willow-herb in
seed. What's the name of this aromatic plant?
subQuotationList: ["Aren't those masses of willow-herb splendid? I love willow-herb in\nseed. What's the name of this aromatic plant?"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

These abrupt changes of vegetation--this little spongeous tract of
water plants, and on either side of it all the growths are tough or
brittle--heather, bracken, hurts, pines. Very charming, very charming.
subQuotationList: ['These abrupt changes of vegetation--this little spongeous tract of\nwater plants, and on either side of it all the growths are tough or\nbrittle--heather, bracken, hurts, pines. Very charming, very charming.']

speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Goal!
subQuotationList: ['Goal!']

subQuotationList: ['Pass!']

subQuotationList: ['Take care my watch!']

Oh, poor Mr. Beebe! Was that his waistcoat we left in the path? Cecil,

Oh, look--don't look! Oh, poor Mr.

And me, I've swallowed one, I've
swallowed a pollywog. It wriggleth in my tummy. I shall die--Emerson you
beast, you've got on my bags.

colds come of not drying thoroughly.

subQuotationList: ['Hullo, Miss Honeychurch! Hullo!']

quoteText: Bow, Lucy; better bow. Whoever is it? I shall bow.
subQuotationList: ['Bow, Lucy; better bow. Whoever is it? I shall bow.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I will bow, I will not shake hands with him.
That will be just the proper thing.
subQuotationList: ['I will bow,', 'I will not shake hands with him.\nThat will be just the proper thing.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Lucy, is anything the matter
with Cecil?
subQuotationList: ['Lucy,', 'is anything the matter\nwith Cecil?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: No, I don't think so, mother; Cecil's all right.
subQuotationList: ["No, I don't think so, mother; Cecil's all right."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Perhaps he's tired.
subQuotationList: ["Perhaps he's tired."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Because otherwise
subQuotationList: ['Because otherwise']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: because otherwise I cannot account for him.
subQuotationList: ['because otherwise I cannot account for him.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: I do think Mrs. Butterworth is rather tiresome, if you mean that.
subQuotationList: ['I do think Mrs. Butterworth is rather tiresome, if you mean that.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Cecil has told you to think so. You were devoted to her as a little
girl, and nothing will describe her goodness to you through the typhoid
fever. No--it is just the same thing everywhere.
subQuotationList: ['Cecil has told you to think so. You were devoted to her as a little\ngirl, and nothing will describe her goodness to you through the typhoid\nfever. No--it is just the same thing everywhere.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Let me just put your bonnet away, may I?
subQuotationList: ['Let me just put your bonnet away, may I?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Surely he could answer her civilly for one half-hour?
subQuotationList: ['Surely he could answer her civilly for one half-hour?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Cecil has a very high standard for people, It's part of his ideals--it is really that that makes
him sometimes seem--
subQuotationList: ['Cecil has a very high standard for people,', "It's part of his ideals--it is really that that makes\nhim sometimes seem--"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, rubbish! If high ideals make a young man rude, the sooner he gets
rid of them the better,
subQuotationList: ['Oh, rubbish! If high ideals make a young man rude, the sooner he gets\nrid of them the better,']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Now, mother! I've seen you cross with Mrs. Butterworth yourself!
subQuotationList: ["Now, mother! I've seen you cross with Mrs. Butterworth yourself!"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Not in that way. At times I could wring her neck. But not in that way.
No. It is the same with Cecil all over.
subQuotationList: ['Not in that way. At times I could wring her neck. But not in that way.\nNo. It is the same with Cecil all over.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
By-the-by--I never told you. I had a letter from Charlotte while I was
away in London.
subQuotationList: ['By-the-by--I never told you. I had a letter from Charlotte while I was\naway in London.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Since Cecil came back from London, nothing appears to please him.
Whenever I speak he winces;--I see him, Lucy; it is useless to
contradict me. No doubt I am neither artistic nor literary nor
intellectual nor musical, but I cannot help the drawing-room furniture;
your father bought it and we must put up with it, will Cecil kindly
remember.
subQuotationList:
['Since Cecil came back from London, nothing appears to please him.
Whenever I speak he winces;--I see him, Lucy; it is useless to
contradict me. No doubt I am neither artistic nor literary nor
intellectual nor musical, but I cannot help the drawing-room furniture;
your father bought it and we must put up with it, will Cecil kindly
remember.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I--I see what you mean, and certainly Cecil oughtn't to. But he does
not mean to be uncivil--he once explained--it is the things that upset
him--he is easily upset by ugly things--he is not uncivil to PEOPLE.
subQuotationList: ["I--I see what you mean, and certainly Cecil oughtn't to. But he does\nnot mean to be uncivil--he once explained--it is the things that upset\nhim--he is easily upset by ugly things--he is not uncivil to PEOPLE."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Is it a thing or a person when Freddy sings?
subQuotationList: ['Is it a thing or a person when Freddy sings?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
You can't expect a really musical person to enjoy comic songs as we
do.
subQuotationList: ["You can't expect a really musical person to enjoy comic songs as we\ndo."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Then why didn't he leave the room? Why sit wriggling and sneering and
spoiling everyone's pleasure?
subQuotationList: ["Then why didn't he leave the room? Why sit wriggling and sneering and\nspoiling everyone's pleasure?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: We mustn't be unjust to people,
subQuotationList: ["We mustn't be unjust to people,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Go and dress, dear; you'll be late.
subQuotationList: ["Go and dress, dear; you'll be late."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: All right, mother--
subQuotationList: ['All right, mother--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Don't say
subQuotationList: ["Don't say"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: and stop. Go
subQuotationList: ['and stop. Go']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Oh, dear, what shall I do, what shall I do?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, dear, what shall I do, what shall I do?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I say, those are topping people.
subQuotationList: ['I say, those are topping people.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
My dear baby, how tiresome you've been! You have no business to take
them bathing in the Sacred Lake; it's much too public. It was all right for
you but most awkward for everyone else. Do be more careful. You forget
the place is growing half suburban.
subQuotationList:
["My dear baby, how tiresome you've been! You have no business to take
them bathing in the Sacred Lake; it's much too public. It was all right for
you but most awkward for everyone else. Do be more careful. You forget
the place is growing half suburban."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I say, is anything on to-morrow week?
subQuotationList: ['I say, is anything on to-morrow week?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Not that I know of.
subQuotationList: ['Not that I know of.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Then I want to ask the Emersons up to Sunday tennis.
subQuotationList: ['Then I want to ask the Emersons up to Sunday tennis.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Oh, I wouldn't do that, Freddy, I wouldn't do that with all this
muddle.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, I wouldn't do that, Freddy, I wouldn't do that with all this\nmuddle."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
What's wrong with the court? They won't mind a bump or two, and I've
ordered new balls.
subQuotationList: ["What's wrong with the court? They won't mind a bump or two, and I've\nordered new balls."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I meant it's better not. I really mean it.
subQuotationList: ["I meant it's better not. I really mean it."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Lucy, what a noise you're making! I
have something to say to you. Did you say you had had a letter from
Charlotte?
subQuotationList: ["Lucy, what a noise you're making! I\nhave something to say to you. Did you say you had had a letter from\nCharlotte?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
referringExpression: Mrs Honeychurch opened her door and said

quoteText: Yes. I really can't stop. I must dress too.
subQuotationList: ["Yes. I really can't stop. I must dress too."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: How's Charlotte?
subQuotationList: ["How's Charlotte?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: All right.
subQuotationList: ['All right.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy!
subQuotationList: ['Lucy!']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
You've a bad habit of hurrying away in the middle of one's sentences.
Did Charlotte mention her boiler?
subQuotationList: ["You've a bad habit of hurrying away in the middle of one's sentences.\nDid Charlotte mention her boiler?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Her WHAT?
subQuotationList: ['Her WHAT?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Don't you remember that her boiler was to be had out in October, and
her bath cistern cleaned out, and all kinds of terrible to-doings?
subQuotationList: ["Don't you remember that her boiler was to be had out in October, and\nher bath cistern cleaned out, and all kinds of terrible to-doings?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I can't remember all Charlotte's worries, I shall
have enough of my own, now that you are not pleased with Cecil.
subQuotationList: ["I can't remember all Charlotte's worries,", 'I shall\nhave enough of my own, now that you are not pleased with Cecil.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Come
here, old lady--thank you for putting away my bonnet--kiss me.
subQuotationList: ['Come\nhere, old lady--thank you for putting away my bonnet--kiss me.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Lucy, what's Emerson like?
subQuotationList: ["Lucy, what's Emerson like?"]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I saw him in Florence,
subQuotationList: ['I saw him in Florence,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Is he the clever sort, or is he a decent chap?
subQuotationList: ['Is he the clever sort, or is he a decent chap?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Ask Cecil; it is Cecil who brought him here.
subQuotationList: ['Ask Cecil; it is Cecil who brought him here.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: He is the clever sort, like myself,
subQuotationList: ['He is the clever sort, like myself,']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText: How well did you know them at the Bertolini?
subQuotationList: ['How well did you know them at the Bertolini?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Oh, very slightly. I mean, Charlotte knew them even less than I did.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, very slightly. I mean, Charlotte knew them even less than I did.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, that reminds me--you never told me what Charlotte said in her
letter.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, that reminds me--you never told me what Charlotte said in her\nletter.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
One thing and another, Among other things, that an awful
friend of hers had been bicycling through Summer Street, wondered if
she'd come up and see us, and mercifully didn't.
subQuotationList: ['One thing and another,', "Among other things, that an awful\nfriend of hers had been bicycling through Summer Street, wondered if\nshe'd come up and see us, and mercifully didn't."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy, I do call the way you talk unkind.
subQuotationList: ['Lucy, I do call the way you talk unkind.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: She was a novelist,
subQuotationList: ['She was a novelist,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: This year, next year, now, never,
subQuotationList: ['This year, next year, now, never,']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I have been thinking, Lucy, of that letter of Charlotte's. How is she?
subQuotationList: ["I have been thinking, Lucy, of that letter of Charlotte's. How is she?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: I tore the thing up.
subQuotationList: ['I tore the thing up.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Didn't she say how she was? How does she sound? Cheerful?
subQuotationList: ["Didn't she say how she was? How does she sound? Cheerful?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Oh, yes I suppose so--no--not very cheerful, I suppose.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, yes I suppose so--no--not very cheerful, I suppose.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Then, depend upon it, it IS the boiler. I know myself how water preys
upon one's mind. I would rather anything else--even a misfortune with
the meat.
subQuotationList: ["Then, depend upon it, it IS the boiler. I know myself how water preys\nupon one's mind. I would rather anything else--even a misfortune with\nthe meat."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: So would I,
subQuotationList: ['So would I,']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
And I have been thinking, surely we could
squeeze Charlotte in here next week, and give her a nice holiday while
plumbers at Tunbridge Wells finish. I have not seen poor Charlotte for
so long.
subQuotationList:
['And I have been thinking,', 'surely we could
squeeze Charlotte in here next week, and give her a nice holiday while
plumbers at Tunbridge Wells finish. I have not seen poor Charlotte for
so long.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Mother, no! It's impossible. We can't have Charlotte on
the top of the other things; we're squeezed to death as it is. Freddy's
got a friend coming Tuesday, there's Cecil, and you've promised to take
in Minnie Beebe because of the diphtheria scare. It simply can't be
done.
subQuotationList:
['Mother, no!', "It's impossible. We can't have Charlotte on
the top of the other things; we're squeezed to death as it is. Freddy's
got a friend coming Tuesday, there's Cecil, and you've promised to take
in Minnie Beebe because of the diphtheria scare. It simply can't be
done."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Honeychurch']], [['Freddy', 'Lucy', 'Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Freddy', 'Lucy', 'Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Freddy'], ['Mr. Floyd'], ['Cecil'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Minnie Beebe']]]

quoteText: Nonsense! It can.
subQuotationList: ['Nonsense! It can.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: If Minnie sleeps in the bath. Not otherwise.
subQuotationList: ['If Minnie sleeps in the bath. Not otherwise.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Minnie can sleep with you.
subQuotationList: ['Minnie can sleep with you.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: I won't have her.
subQuotationList: ["I won't have her."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Then, if you're so selfish, Mr. Floyd must share a room with Freddy.
subQuotationList: ["Then, if you're so selfish, Mr. Floyd must share a room with Freddy."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett,
subQuotationList: ['Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett,']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
It's impossible, I don't want to make difficulties,
but it really isn't fair on the maids to fill up the house so.
subQuotationList: ["It's impossible,", "I don't want to make difficulties,\nbut it really isn't fair on the maids to fill up the house so."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The truth is, dear, you don't like Charlotte.
subQuotationList: ["The truth is, dear, you don't like Charlotte."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
No, I don't. And no more does Cecil. She gets on our nerves. You
haven't seen her lately, and don't realize how tiresome she can be,
though so good. So please, mother, don't worry us this last summer; but
spoil us by not asking her to come.
subQuotationList:
["No, I don't. And no more does Cecil. She gets on our nerves. You
haven't seen her lately, and don't realize how tiresome she can be,
though so good. So please, mother, don't worry us this last summer; but
spoil us by not asking her to come."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Hear, hear!
subQuotationList: ['Hear, hear!']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
This isn't very kind of
you two. You have each other and all these woods to walk in, so full of
beautiful things; and poor Charlotte has only the water turned off and
plumbers. You are young, dears, and however clever young people are, and
however many books they read, they will never guess what it feels like
to grow old.
subQuotationList:
["This isn't very kind of
you two. You have each other and all these woods to walk in, so full of
beautiful things; and poor Charlotte has only the water turned off and
plumbers. You are young, dears, and however clever young people are, and
however many books they read, they will never guess what it feels like
to grow old."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
referringExpression: Mrs Honeychurch with more gravity than usual and with more feeling than she usually permitted herself replied

quoteText:
I must say Cousin Charlotte was very kind to me that year I called on
my bike, She thanked me for coming till I felt like
such a fool, and fussed round no end to get an egg boiled for my tea
just right.
subQuotationList:
['I must say Cousin Charlotte was very kind to me that year I called on
my bike,', 'She thanked me for coming till I felt like
such a fool, and fussed round no end to get an egg boiled for my tea
just right.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
I know, dear. She is kind to everyone, and yet Lucy makes this
difficulty when we try to give her some little return.
subQuotationList: ['I know, dear. She is kind to everyone, and yet Lucy makes this\ndifficulty when we try to give her some little return.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
I
can't help it, mother. I don't like Charlotte. I admit it's horrid of
me.
subQuotationList: ["I\ncan't help it, mother. I don't like Charlotte. I admit it's horrid of\nme."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: From your own account, you told her as much.
subQuotationList: ['From your own account, you told her as much.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Well, she would leave Florence so stupidly. She flurried--
subQuotationList: ['Well, she would leave Florence so stupidly. She flurried--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I suppose Miss Bartlett must come, since she boils eggs so well,
subQuotationList: ['I suppose Miss Bartlett must come, since she boils eggs so well,']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
I didn't mean the egg was WELL boiled, because in
point of fact she forgot to take it off, and as a matter of fact I don't
care for eggs. I only meant how jolly kind she seemed.
subQuotationList: ["I didn't mean the egg was WELL boiled,", "because in\npoint of fact she forgot to take it off, and as a matter of fact I don't\ncare for eggs. I only meant how jolly kind she seemed."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
May me and Lucy get down from
our chairs? We don't want no
dessert.
subQuotationList: ['May me and Lucy get down from\nour chairs?', "We don't want no\ndessert."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
A nice fellow, He will work off his
crudities in time. I rather mistrust young men who slip into life
gracefully.
subQuotationList: ['A nice fellow,', 'He will work off his\ncrudities in time. I rather mistrust young men who slip into life\ngracefully.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: He seems in better spirits. He laughs more.
subQuotationList: ['He seems in better spirits. He laughs more.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Yes, He is waking up.
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', 'He is waking up.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I shall never forgive myself, I have upset everything. Bursting in on young people! But I insist on
paying for my cab up. Grant that, at any rate.
subQuotationList: ['I shall never forgive myself,', 'I have upset everything. Bursting in on young people! But I insist on\npaying for my cab up. Grant that, at any rate.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Just what I've been trying to convince
Cousin Charlotte of, Lucy, for the last half hour.
subQuotationList: ["Just what I've been trying to convince\nCousin Charlotte of, Lucy, for the last half hour."]
speaker: Freddy
referringExpression: her brother in whose memory the boiled egg had already grown unsubstantial exclaimed

quoteText: I do not feel myself an ordinary visitor,
subQuotationList: ['I do not feel myself an ordinary visitor,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
All right, if you'd really rather. Five shillings, and I gave a bob to
the driver.
subQuotationList: ["All right, if you'd really rather. Five shillings, and I gave a bob to\nthe driver."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
But who
am I to give the sovereign to?
subQuotationList: ['But who\nam I to give the sovereign to?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett accepted their moneys and then said

quoteText: Let's leave it all till mother comes back,
subQuotationList: ["Let's leave it all till mother comes back,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, dear; your mother may take quite a long drive now that she is not
hampered with me. We all have our little foibles, and mine is the prompt
settling of accounts.
subQuotationList: ['No, dear; your mother may take quite a long drive now that she is not\nhampered with me. We all have our little foibles, and mine is the prompt\nsettling of accounts.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Please--please--I know I am a sad spoil-sport, but it would make me
wretched. I should practically be robbing the one who lost.
subQuotationList: ['Please--please--I know I am a sad spoil-sport, but it would make me\nwretched. I should practically be robbing the one who lost.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Freddy owes me fifteen shillings, So it will work
out right if you give the pound to me.
subQuotationList: ['Freddy owes me fifteen shillings,', 'So it will work\nout right if you give the pound to me.']
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
Fifteen shillings, How is that, Mr.
Vyse?
subQuotationList: ['Fifteen shillings,', 'How is that, Mr.\nVyse?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Because, don't you see, Freddy paid your cab. Give me the pound, and we
shall avoid this deplorable gambling.
subQuotationList: ["Because, don't you see, Freddy paid your cab. Give me the pound, and we\nshall avoid this deplorable gambling."]
speaker: Cecil

quoteText:
But I don't see that! I don't see why Mr. Vyse is to have the
quid.
subQuotationList: ["But I don't see that!", "I don't see why Mr. Vyse is to have the\nquid."]
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText: But I don't see--
subQuotationList: ["But I don't see--"]
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText:
No, thank you. I'm done. I don't see why--Freddy, don't poke me. Miss
Honeychurch, your brother's hurting me. Ow! What about Mr. Floyd's
ten shillings? Ow! No, I don't see and I never shall see why Miss
What's-her-name shouldn't pay that bob for the driver.
subQuotationList:
["No, thank you. I'm done. I don't see why--Freddy, don't poke me. Miss
Honeychurch, your brother's hurting me. Ow! What about Mr. Floyd's
ten shillings? Ow! No, I don't see and I never shall see why Miss
What's-her-name shouldn't pay that bob for the driver."]
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText:
I had forgotten the driver, Thank you,
dear, for reminding me. A shilling was it? Can any one give me change
for half a crown?
subQuotationList: ['I had forgotten the driver,', 'Thank you,\ndear, for reminding me. A shilling was it? Can any one give me change\nfor half a crown?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: I'll get it,
subQuotationList: ["I'll get it,"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Cecil, give me that sovereign. No, give me up that sovereign. I'll get
Euphemia to change it, and we'll start the whole thing again from the
beginning.
subQuotationList: ["Cecil, give me that sovereign. No, give me up that sovereign. I'll get\nEuphemia to change it, and we'll start the whole thing again from the\nbeginning."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Lucy--Lucy--what a nuisance I am!
subQuotationList: ['Lucy--Lucy--what a nuisance I am!']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Have you told him about him yet?
subQuotationList: ['Have you told him about him yet?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett stopped her wails and said

quoteText:
No, I haven't, Let me see--a
sovereign's worth of silver.
subQuotationList: ["No, I haven't,", "Let me see--a\nsovereign's worth of silver."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, I haven't told Cecil or any one, I promised you I shouldn't. Here is your money--all shillings, except
two half-crowns. Would you count it? You can settle your debt nicely
now.
subQuotationList: ["No, I haven't told Cecil or any one,", "I promised you I shouldn't. Here is your money--all shillings, except\ntwo half-crowns. Would you count it? You can settle your debt nicely\nnow."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Cecil']], [['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett']]]

quoteText:
How dreadful! how more than dreadful, if Mr. Vyse
should come to hear of it from some other source.
subQuotationList: ['How dreadful!', 'how more than dreadful, if Mr. Vyse\nshould come to hear of it from some other source.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Oh, no, Charlotte, George Emerson
is all right, and what other source is there?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, no, Charlotte,', 'George Emerson\nis all right, and what other source is there?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
For instance, the driver. I saw him looking
through the bushes at you, remember he had a violet between his teeth.
subQuotationList: ['For instance, the driver. I saw him looking\nthrough the bushes at you, remember he had a violet between his teeth.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
We shall get the silly affair on our nerves
if we aren't careful. How could a Florentine cab-driver ever get hold of
Cecil?
subQuotationList: ["We shall get the silly affair on our nerves\nif we aren't careful. How could a Florentine cab-driver ever get hold of\nCecil?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: We must think of every possibility.
subQuotationList: ['We must think of every possibility.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Oh, it's all right.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, it's all right."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Or perhaps old Mr. Emerson knows. In fact, he is certain to know.
subQuotationList: ['Or perhaps old Mr. Emerson knows. In fact, he is certain to know.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I don't care if he does. I was grateful to you for your letter, but
even if the news does get round, I think I can trust Cecil to laugh at
it.
subQuotationList: ["I don't care if he does. I was grateful to you for your letter, but\neven if the news does get round, I think I can trust Cecil to laugh at\nit."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: To contradict it?
subQuotationList: ['To contradict it?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: No, to laugh at it.
subQuotationList: ['No, to laugh at it.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Very well, dear, you know best. Perhaps gentlemen are different to what
they were when I was young. Ladies are certainly different.
subQuotationList: ['Very well, dear, you know best. Perhaps gentlemen are different to what\nthey were when I was young. Ladies are certainly different.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Now, Charlotte!
subQuotationList: ['Now, Charlotte!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I am no match for you in conversation, dearest. I
blush when I think how I interfered at Florence, and you so well able
to look after yourself, and so much cleverer in all ways than I am. You
will never forgive me.
subQuotationList:
['I am no match for you in conversation, dearest. I
blush when I think how I interfered at Florence, and you so well able
to look after yourself, and so much cleverer in all ways than I am. You
will never forgive me.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Shall we go out, then. They will smash all the china if we don't.
subQuotationList: ["Shall we go out, then. They will smash all the china if we don't."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Dear, one moment--we may not have this chance for a chat again. Have
you seen the young one yet?
subQuotationList: ['Dear, one moment--we may not have this chance for a chat again. Have\nyou seen the young one yet?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Yes, I have.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, I have.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What happened?
subQuotationList: ['What happened?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: We met at the Rectory.
subQuotationList: ['We met at the Rectory.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: What line is he taking up?
subQuotationList: ['What line is he taking up?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
No line. He talked about Italy, like any other person. It is really all
right. What advantage would he get from being a cad, to put it bluntly?
I do wish I could make you see it my way. He really won't be any
nuisance, Charlotte.
subQuotationList:
["No line. He talked about Italy, like any other person. It is really all
right. What advantage would he get from being a cad, to put it bluntly?
I do wish I could make you see it my way. He really won't be any
nuisance, Charlotte."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Once a cad, always a cad. That is my poor opinion.
subQuotationList: ['Once a cad, always a cad. That is my poor opinion.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Cecil said one day--and I thought it so profound--that
there are two kinds of cads--the conscious and the subconscious.
subQuotationList: ['Cecil said one day--and I thought it so profound--that\nthere are two kinds of cads--the conscious and the subconscious.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Once a cad, always a cad,
subQuotationList: ['Once a cad, always a cad,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
What I mean by subconscious is that Emerson lost his head. I fell into
all those violets, and he was silly and surprised. I don't think we
ought to blame him very much. It makes such a difference when you see a
person with beautiful things behind him unexpectedly. It really does;
it makes an enormous difference, and he lost his head: he doesn't admire
me, or any of that nonsense, one straw. Freddy rather likes him, and
has asked him up here on Sunday, so you can judge for yourself. He has
improved; he doesn't always look as if he's going to burst into
tears. He is a clerk in the General Manager's office at one of the big
railways--not a porter! and runs down to his father for week-ends. Papa
was to do with journalism, but is rheumatic and has retired. There!
Now for the garden.
subQuotationList:
["What I mean by subconscious is that Emerson lost his head. I fell into
all those violets, and he was silly and surprised. I don't think we
ought to blame him very much. It makes such a difference when you see a
person with beautiful things behind him unexpectedly. It really does;
it makes an enormous difference, and he lost his head: he doesn't admire
me, or any of that nonsense, one straw. Freddy rather likes him, and
