Now for the garden."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Freddy'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

quoteText:
Suppose we
don't talk about this silly Italian business any more. We want you to
have a nice restful visit at Windy Corner, with no worriting.
subQuotationList: ["Suppose we\ndon't talk about this silly Italian business any more. We want you to\nhave a nice restful visit at Windy Corner, with no worriting."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Well, I don't blame them need she go?
subQuotationList: ["Well, I don't blame them", 'need she go?']
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText:
Lucy! Lucy! What's that book? Who's been taking a book out of the shelf
and leaving it about to spoil?
subQuotationList: ["Lucy! Lucy! What's that book? Who's been taking a book out of the shelf\nand leaving it about to spoil?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: It's only the library book that Cecil's been reading.
subQuotationList: ["It's only the library book that Cecil's been reading."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: But pick it up, and don't stand idling there like a flamingo.
subQuotationList: ["But pick it up, and don't stand idling there like a flamingo."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: What! you aren't forgetting your Italy already?
subQuotationList: ["What! you aren't forgetting your Italy already?"]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Lucy--have you a sixpence for Minnie and a shilling for yourself?
subQuotationList: ['Lucy--have you a sixpence for Minnie and a shilling for yourself?']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
It's a special collection--I forget what for. I do beg, no vulgar
clinking in the plate with halfpennies; see that Minnie has a nice
bright sixpence. Where is the child? Minnie! That book's all warped.
(Gracious, how plain you look!) Put it under the Atlas to press.
Minnie!
subQuotationList:
["It's a special collection--I forget what for. I do beg, no vulgar
clinking in the plate with halfpennies; see that Minnie has a nice
bright sixpence. Where is the child? Minnie! That book's all warped.
(Gracious, how plain you look!) Put it under the Atlas to press.
Minnie!"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch--
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch--']
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText: Minnie, don't be late. Here comes the horse
subQuotationList: ["Minnie, don't be late. Here comes the horse"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Where's Charlotte? Run up and hurry her. Why is she
so long? She had nothing to do. She never brings anything but blouses.
Poor Charlotte--How I do detest blouses! Minnie!
subQuotationList: ["Where's Charlotte? Run up and hurry her. Why is she\nso long? She had nothing to do. She never brings anything but blouses.\nPoor Charlotte--How I do detest blouses! Minnie!"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Dear Marian, I am very sorry, but I have no small change--nothing but
sovereigns and half crowns. Could any one give me--
subQuotationList: ['Dear Marian, I am very sorry, but I have no small change--nothing but\nsovereigns and half crowns. Could any one give me--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Yes, easily. Jump in. Gracious me, how smart you look! What a lovely
frock! You put us all to shame.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, easily. Jump in. Gracious me, how smart you look! What a lovely\nfrock! You put us all to shame.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
If I did not wear my best rags and tatters now, when should I wear
them?
subQuotationList: ['If I did not wear my best rags and tatters now, when should I wear\nthem?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Good-bye! Be good!
subQuotationList: ['Good-bye! Be good!']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Introduce me, Unless the young man considers that he
knows me already.
subQuotationList: ['Introduce me,', 'Unless the young man considers that he\nknows me already.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Very much,
subQuotationList: ['Very much,']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
We find, though,
that the Miss Alans were coming, and that we have turned them out. Women
mind such a thing. I am very much upset about it.
subQuotationList: ['We find, though,\nthat the Miss Alans were coming, and that we have turned them out. Women\nmind such a thing. I am very much upset about it.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

quoteText: I believe that there was some misunderstanding,
subQuotationList: ['I believe that there was some misunderstanding,']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Our landlord was told that we should be a different type of person, He
thought we should be artistic. He is disappointed.
subQuotationList: ['Our landlord was told that we should be a different type of person,', 'He\nthought we should be artistic. He is disappointed.']
speaker: George Emerson
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Sir Harry Otway'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson']], [['Sir Harry Otway'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Sir Harry Otway']]]

quoteText:
And I wonder whether we ought to write to the Miss Alans and offer to
give it up. What do you think?
subQuotationList: ['And I wonder whether we ought to write to the Miss Alans and offer to\ngive it up. What do you think?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Oh, stop now you have come,
subQuotationList: ['Oh, stop now you have come,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
So George says. He says that the Miss Alans must go to the wall. Yet it
does seem so unkind.
subQuotationList: ['So George says. He says that the Miss Alans must go to the wall. Yet it\ndoes seem so unkind.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText: There is only a certain amount of kindness in the world,
subQuotationList: ['There is only a certain amount of kindness in the world,']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Yes! That's exactly what I say. Why all
this twiddling and twaddling over two Miss Alans?
subQuotationList: ['Yes!', "That's exactly what I say. Why all\nthis twiddling and twaddling over two Miss Alans?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
There is a certain amount of kindness, just as there is a certain
amount of light, We cast a shadow
on something wherever we stand, and it is no good moving from place to
place to save things; because the shadow always follows. Choose a place
where you won't do harm--yes, choose a place where you won't do very
much harm, and stand in it for all you are worth, facing the sunshine.
subQuotationList:
['There is a certain amount of kindness, just as there is a certain
amount of light,', "We cast a shadow
on something wherever we stand, and it is no good moving from place to
place to save things; because the shadow always follows. Choose a place
where you won't do harm--yes, choose a place where you won't do very
much harm, and stand in it for all you are worth, facing the sunshine."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Oh, Mr. Emerson, I see you're clever!
subQuotationList: ["Oh, Mr. Emerson, I see you're clever!"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Eh--?
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
I see you're going to be clever. I hope you didn't go behaving like
that to poor Freddy.
subQuotationList: ["I see you're going to be clever. I hope you didn't go behaving like\nthat to poor Freddy."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
No, I didn't, He behaved that way to me. It is his
philosophy. Only he starts life with it; and I have tried the Note of
Interrogation first.
subQuotationList: ["No, I didn't,", 'He behaved that way to me. It is his\nphilosophy. Only he starts life with it; and I have tried the Note of\nInterrogation first.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
What DO you mean? No, never mind what you mean. Don't explain. He looks
forward to seeing you this afternoon. Do you play tennis? Do you mind
tennis on Sunday--?
subQuotationList: ["What DO you mean? No, never mind what you mean. Don't explain. He looks\nforward to seeing you this afternoon. Do you play tennis? Do you mind\ntennis on Sunday--?"]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

George mind tennis on Sunday! George, after his education, distinguish
between Sunday--
subQuotationList: ['George mind tennis on Sunday! George, after his education, distinguish\nbetween Sunday--']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Very well, George doesn't mind tennis on Sunday. No more do I. That's
settled. Mr. Emerson, if you could come with your son we should be so
pleased.
subQuotationList: ["Very well, George doesn't mind tennis on Sunday. No more do I. That's\nsettled. Mr. Emerson, if you could come with your son we should be so\npleased."]

And then he wants to give up his house to the
Miss Alans.
subQuotationList: ['And then he wants to give up his house to the\nMiss Alans.']

quoteText: I know,
subQuotationList: ['I know,']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: You know our cousin, Miss Bartlett, You met her with my daughter in Florence.
subQuotationList: ['You know our cousin, Miss Bartlett,', 'You met her with my daughter in Florence.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: Yes, indeed!
subQuotationList: ['Yes, indeed!']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
I--I'll come up
to tennis if I can manage it,
subQuotationList: ["I--I'll come up\nto tennis if I can manage it,"]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
George, don't go, George has been in such good
spirits today, and I am sure he will end by coming up this afternoon.
subQuotationList: ["George, don't go,", 'George has been in such good\nspirits today, and I am sure he will end by coming up this afternoon.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

subQuotationList: ['Yes,', 'I do hope he will.']

The old man hasn't been told;
I knew it was all right.

referringExpression: she went to the carriage and murmured

subQuotationList: ['He has not told, he has not told.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
He has not told his father--to whom he tells all things. It was
not an exploit. He did not laugh at me when I had gone. He does not love me. No. How terrible if he did! But
he has not told. He will not tell.
subQuotationList: ['He has not told his father--to whom he tells all things. It was\nnot an exploit. He did not laugh at me when I had gone.', 'He does not love me. No. How terrible if he did! But\nhe has not told. He will not tell.']

us two for ever. Cecil will never hear.

enormously.

quoteText: Proteges!
subQuotationList: ['Proteges!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:

coming up this afternoon. He is a most interesting man to talk to. Only
don't--
subQuotationList: ["You shall see for yourself how your proteges are. George Emerson is\ncoming up this afternoon. He is a most interesting man to talk to. Only\ndon't--"]
speaker: Lucy

Now play us the other
garden--the one in Parsifal.

Oh, come along Cecil. I'm bad, Floyd's rotten, and so I dare say's
Emerson.

speaker: Freddy
addressees: ['Mr. Vyse', 'Lucy', 'George Emerson', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Minnie Beebe', 'Mr. Floyd', 'Mrs. Honeychurch']

speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Then certainly I won't play,
subQuotationList: ["Then certainly I won't play,"]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I agree with you, Mr. Vyse. You had much better not
play. Much better not.

speaker: Miss Bartlett
referringExpression: Miss Bartlett under the impression that she was snubbing George added

Then it will have to be Lucy, you must fall
back on Lucy. There is no other way out of it. Lucy, go and change your
frock.
subQuotationList: ['Then it will have to be Lucy,', 'you must fall\nback on Lucy. There is no other way out of it. Lucy, go and change your\nfrock.']

referringExpression: he had leant over the parapet by the Arno and said to her

I say, listen to this, Lucy.
Three split infinitives.

speaker: Mr. Vyse
referringExpression: He would stroll round the precincts of the court and call out

speaker: Lucy

quoteText: The scene is laid in Florence.
subQuotationList: ['The scene is laid in Florence.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
What fun, Cecil! Read away. Come, Mr. Emerson, sit down after all your
energy.
subQuotationList: ['What fun, Cecil! Read away. Come, Mr. Emerson, sit down after all your\nenergy.']

quoteText:
You--and are
you tired?

speaker: George Emerson
referringExpression: He jumped over the net and sat down at her feet asking

speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['Do you mind being beaten?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Yes.
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I don't see you're such
a splendid player, though. The light was behind you, and it was in my
eyes.
subQuotationList: ["I don't see you're such\na splendid player, though. The light was behind you, and it was in my\neyes."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I never said I was.

speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: Why, you did!
subQuotationList: ['Why, you did!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: You didn't attend.
subQuotationList: ["You didn't attend."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
You said--oh, don't go in for accuracy at this house. We all
exaggerate, and we get very angry with people who don't.
subQuotationList: ["You said--oh, don't go in for accuracy at this house. We all\nexaggerate, and we get very angry with people who don't."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Leonora? Is Leonora the heroine? Who's the book by?
subQuotationList: ["Leonora? Is Leonora the heroine? Who's the book by?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Joseph Emery Prank.
subQuotationList: ['Joseph Emery Prank.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
indeed! Why it's Miss
Lavish! It's Miss Lavish's novel, and she's publishing it under somebody
else's name.
subQuotationList: ["indeed! Why it's Miss\nLavish! It's Miss Lavish's novel, and she's publishing it under somebody\nelse's name."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Who may Miss Lavish be?
subQuotationList: ['Who may Miss Lavish be?']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

subQuotationList: ['Oh, a dreadful person--Mr. Emerson, you remember Miss Lavish?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Of course I do. I saw her the day I arrived at Summer

No wonder the
novel's bad, I never liked Miss Lavish. But I suppose one
ought to read it as one's met her.

quoteText:
All modern books are bad, Every one writes
for money in these days.

speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Oh, Cecil--!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Cecil--!']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: It is so. I will inflict Joseph Emery Prank on you no longer.

subQuotationList: ['How do you like this view of ours, Mr. Emerson?']

speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: What do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Because they're all alike. Because all that matters in them is distance
and air.
subQuotationList: ["Because they're all alike. Because all that matters in them is distance\nand air."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: H'm!
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: My father
subQuotationList: ['My father']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
says
that there is only one perfect view--the view of the sky straight over
our heads, and that all these views on earth are but bungled copies of
it.
subQuotationList:

that there is only one perfect view--the view of the sky straight over
our heads, and that all these views on earth are but bungled copies of

speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
He told us another day that views are really crowds--crowds of trees
and houses and hills--and are bound to resemble each other, like human
crowds--and that the power they have over us is sometimes supernatural,
for the same reason.
subQuotationList:
['He told us another day that views are really crowds--crowds of trees
and houses and hills--and are bound to resemble each other, like human
crowds--and that the power they have over us is sometimes supernatural,
for the same reason.']

For a crowd is more than the people who make it up. Something gets
added to it--no one knows how--just as something has got added to those
hills.

speaker: George Emerson

What a splendid idea! I shall enjoy hearing your father
talk again. I'm so sorry he's not so well.
subQuotationList: ['What a splendid idea!', "I shall enjoy hearing your father\ntalk again. I'm so sorry he's not so well."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: No, he isn't well.
subQuotationList: ["No, he isn't well."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
There's an absurd account of a view in this book, Also

subQuotationList: ['There are violets. I cannot believe it is a coincidence. Charlotte,\nCharlotte, how could you have told her? I have thought before speaking;\nit must be you.']

Oh, Lucy, dearest girl--she hasn't

speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['So you did tell?']

I did just happen--when I had tea with her at Rome--in the course of

But Charlotte--what about the promise you gave me when we were packing?
Why did you tell Miss Lavish, when you wouldn't even let me tell
mother?
subQuotationList: ["But Charlotte--what about the promise you gave me when we were packing?\nWhy did you tell Miss Lavish, when you wouldn't even let me tell\nmother?"]

subQuotationList: ['Why did you tell her, though? This is a most serious thing.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Cecil happened to read out the passage aloud to me and to Mr. Emerson;
it upset Mr. Emerson and he insulted me again. Behind Cecil's back. Ugh!
Is it possible that men are such brutes? Behind Cecil's back as we were
walking up the garden.

subQuotationList: ['What is to be done now? Can you tell me?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh, Lucy--I shall never forgive myself, never to my dying day. Fancy if
your prospects--

I know, I see now why you wanted me
to tell Cecil, and what you meant by You knew that
you had told Miss Lavish, and that she was not reliable.

However, What's done's done. You have put me
in a most awkward position. How am I to get out of it?
subQuotationList: ['However,', "What's done's done. You have put me\nin a most awkward position. How am I to get out of it?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
He must--that man must have such a setting down that he won't forget.
And who's to give it him? I can't tell mother now--owing to you. Nor
Cecil, Charlotte, owing to you. I am caught up every way. I think I
shall go mad. I have no one to help me. That's why I've sent for you.
What's wanted is a man with a whip.
subQuotationList:
["He must--that man must have such a setting down that he won't forget.
And who's to give it him? I can't tell mother now--owing to you. Nor
Cecil, Charlotte, owing to you. I am caught up every way. I think I
shall go mad. I have no one to help me. That's why I've sent for you.
What's wanted is a man with a whip."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Yes--but it's no good agreeing. What's to be DONE. We women go
maundering on. What DOES a girl do when she comes across a cad?
subQuotationList: ["Yes--but it's no good agreeing. What's to be DONE. We women go\nmaundering on. What DOES a girl do when she comes across a cad?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I always said he was a cad, dear. Give me credit for that, at all
events. From the very first moment--when he said his father was having a
bath.
subQuotationList: ['I always said he was a cad, dear. Give me credit for that, at all\nevents. From the very first moment--when he said his father was having a\nbath.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Oh, bother the credit and who's been right or wrong! We've both made a
muddle of it. George Emerson is still down the garden there, and is he
to be left unpunished, or isn't he? I want to know.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, bother the credit and who's been right or wrong! We've both made a\nmuddle of it. George Emerson is still down the garden there, and is he\nto be left unpunished, or isn't he? I want to know."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You were ready enough at the Bertolini when you rushed me off to Rome.
Can't you speak again to him now?
subQuotationList: ["You were ready enough at the Bertolini when you rushed me off to Rome.\nCan't you speak again to him now?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Willingly would I move heaven and earth--
subQuotationList: ['Willingly would I move heaven and earth--']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
I want something more definite, Will you
speak to him? It is the least you can do, surely, considering it all
happened because you broke your word.
subQuotationList: ['I want something more definite,', 'Will you\nspeak to him? It is the least you can do, surely, considering it all\nhappened because you broke your word.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Never again shall Eleanor Lavish be a friend of mine.
subQuotationList: ['Never again shall Eleanor Lavish be a friend of mine.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Yes or no, please; yes or no.
subQuotationList: ['Yes or no, please; yes or no.']
speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['It is the kind of thing that only a gentleman can settle.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

Very well, No one will help me. I
will speak to him myself.

I seem to bring nothing

You go down to the others, Charlotte and I will give Mr.
Emerson all he wants. Where's mother?
subQuotationList: ['You go down to the others,', "Charlotte and I will give Mr.\nEmerson all he wants. Where's mother?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: She's started on her Sunday writing. She's in the drawing-room.
subQuotationList: ["She's started on her Sunday writing. She's in the drawing-room."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: That's all right. You go away.
subQuotationList: ["That's all right. You go away."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I can't
have it, Mr. Emerson. I cannot even talk to you. Go out of this house,
and never come into it again as long as I live here-- I hate a row. Go please.
subQuotationList: ["I can't\nhave it, Mr. Emerson. I cannot even talk to you. Go out of this house,\nand never come into it again as long as I live here--", 'I hate a row. Go please.']

quoteText: What--
subQuotationList: ['What--']

subQuotationList: ['No discussion.']

subQuotationList: ["But I can't--"]
speaker: George Emerson

subQuotationList: ['Go, please. I do not want to call in Mr. Vyse.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You don't mean, you don't
mean that you are going to marry that man?
subQuotationList: ["You don't mean,", "you don't\nmean that you are going to marry that man?"]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
You are
merely ridiculous,
subQuotationList: ['You are\nmerely ridiculous,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You cannot live with Vyse. He's
only for an acquaintance. He is for society and cultivated talk. He
should know no one intimately, least of all a woman.
subQuotationList: ["You cannot live with Vyse. He's\nonly for an acquaintance. He is for society and cultivated talk. He\nshould know no one intimately, least of all a woman."]
speaker: George Emerson
referringExpression: his words rose gravely over hers

quoteText: Have you ever talked to Vyse without feeling tired?
subQuotationList: ['Have you ever talked to Vyse without feeling tired?']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText: I can scarcely discuss--
subQuotationList: ['I can scarcely discuss--']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, but have you ever? He is the sort who are all right so long as
they keep to things--books, pictures--but kill when they come to
people. That's why I'll speak out through all this muddle even now. It's
shocking enough to lose you in any case, but generally a man must
deny himself joy, and I would have held back if your Cecil had been a
different person. I would never have let myself go. But I saw him first
in the National Gallery, when he winced because my father mispronounced
the names of great painters. Then he brings us here, and we find it
is to play some silly trick on a kind neighbour. That is the man all
over--playing tricks on people, on the most sacred form of life that
he can find. Next, I meet you together, and find him protecting and
teaching you and your mother to be shocked, when it was for YOU to
settle whether you were shocked or no. Cecil all over again. He daren't
let a woman decide. He's the type who's kept Europe back for a thousand
years. Every moment of his life he's forming you, telling you what's
charming or amusing or ladylike, telling you what a man thinks womanly;
and you, you of all women, listen to his voice instead of to your own.
So it was at the Rectory, when I met you both again; so it has been
the whole of this afternoon. Therefore--not

quoteText:
because the book made me do that, and I wish to goodness I had more
self-control. I'm not ashamed. I don't apologize. But it has frightened
you, and you may not have noticed that I love you. Or would you have
told me to go, and dealt with a tremendous thing so lightly? But
therefore--therefore I settled to fight him.
subQuotationList:
["because the book made me do that, and I wish to goodness I had more

quoteText:
You say Mr. Vyse wants me to listen to him, Mr. Emerson. Pardon me for
suggesting that you have caught the habit.
subQuotationList: ['You say Mr. Vyse wants me to listen to him, Mr. Emerson. Pardon me for\nsuggesting that you have caught the habit.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Yes, I have, I'm the same kind of
brute at bottom. This desire to govern a woman--it lies very deep, and
men and women must fight it together before they shall enter the garden.
But I do love you surely in a better way than he does.
subQuotationList:
['Yes, I have,', "I'm the same kind of
brute at bottom. This desire to govern a woman--it lies very deep, and
men and women must fight it together before they shall enter the garden.
But I do love you surely in a better way than he does."]
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Yes--really in a better way. I want you to have your own thoughts even
when I hold you in my arms.
subQuotationList: ['Yes--really in a better way. I want you to have your own thoughts even\nwhen I hold you in my arms.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
Lucy, be
quick--there's no time for us to talk now--come to me as you came in the
spring, and afterwards I will be gentle and explain. I have cared
for you since that man died. I cannot live without you, I
thought; but I meet you again when all
the world is glorious water and sun. As you came through the wood I
saw that nothing else mattered. I called. I wanted to live and have my
chance of joy.
subQuotationList:
["Lucy, be
quick--there's no time for us to talk now--come to me as you came in the
spring, and afterwards I will be gentle and explain. I have cared
for you since that man died. I cannot live without you,", 'I
thought;', 'but I meet you again when all
the world is glorious water and sun. As you came through the wood I
saw that nothing else mattered. I called. I wanted to live and have my
chance of joy.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
And Mr. Vyse? Does he not
matter? That I love Cecil and shall be his wife shortly? A detail of no
importance, I suppose?
subQuotationList: ['And Mr. Vyse?', 'Does he not\nmatter? That I love Cecil and shall be his wife shortly? A detail of no\nimportance, I suppose?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: May I ask what you intend to gain by this exhibition?
subQuotationList: ['May I ask what you intend to gain by this exhibition?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: It is our last chance. I shall do all that I can.
subQuotationList: ['It is our last chance. I shall do all that I can.']
speaker: George Emerson

quoteText:
You wouldn't stop us this
second time if you understood, I have been into the dark, and
I am going back into it, unless you will try to understand. It is being young, It is being certain that Lucy cares for me
really. It is that love and youth matter intellectually.
subQuotationList:
["You wouldn't stop us this
second time if you understood,", 'I have been into the dark, and
I am going back into it, unless you will try to understand.', 'It is being young,', 'It is being certain that Lucy cares for me

quoteText:
Well, he amuses me, Either I'm mad, or else he is, and I'm inclined to think it's the
latter. One more fuss through with you, Charlotte. Many thanks. I think,
though, that this is the last. My admirer will hardly trouble me again.
subQuotationList: ['Well, he amuses me,', "Either I'm mad, or else he is, and I'm inclined to think it's the\nlatter. One more fuss through with you, Charlotte. Many thanks. I think,\nthough, that this is the last. My admirer will hardly trouble me again."]

quoteText:
Well, it isn't everyone who could boast such a conquest, dearest, is
it? Oh, one oughtn't to laugh, really. It might have been very serious.
But you were so sensible and brave--so unlike the girls of my day.
subQuotationList: ["Well, it isn't everyone who could boast such a conquest, dearest, is\nit? Oh, one oughtn't to laugh, really. It might have been very serious.\nBut you were so sensible and brave--so unlike the girls of my day."]

quoteText: Let's go down to them.
subQuotationList: ["Let's go down to them."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Hullo, Lucy! There's still light enough for another set, if you two'll
hurry.
subQuotationList: ["Hullo, Lucy! There's still light enough for another set, if you two'll\nhurry."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Mr. Emerson has had to go.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Emerson has had to go.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
What a nuisance! That spoils the four. I say, Cecil, do play, do,
there's a good chap. It's Floyd's last day. Do play tennis with us, just
this once.
subQuotationList: ["What a nuisance! That spoils the four. I say, Cecil, do play, do,\nthere's a good chap. It's Floyd's last day. Do play tennis with us, just\nthis once."]
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
My dear Freddy, I am no athlete. As you well
remarked this very morning, I plead guilty to being such a chap, and will not
inflict myself on you.
subQuotationList: ['My dear Freddy, I am no athlete. As you well\nremarked this very morning,', 'I plead guilty to being such a chap, and will not\ninflict myself on you.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I am very sorry about it, I have carefully thought things
over. We are too different. I must ask you to release me, and try to
forget that there ever was such a foolish girl.
subQuotationList: ['I am very sorry about it,', 'I have carefully thought things\nover. We are too different. I must ask you to release me, and try to\nforget that there ever was such a foolish girl.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Different--how--how--
subQuotationList: ['Different--how--how--']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I haven't had a really good education, for one thing, My Italian trip came too late, and
I am forgetting all that I learnt there. I shall never be able to talk
to your friends, or behave as a wife of yours should.
subQuotationList: ["I haven't had a really good education, for one thing,", 'My Italian trip came too late, and\nI am forgetting all that I learnt there. I shall never be able to talk\nto your friends, or behave as a wife of yours should.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I don't understand you. You aren't like yourself. You're tired, Lucy.
subQuotationList: ["I don't understand you. You aren't like yourself. You're tired, Lucy."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Tired! That is exactly like you. You
always think women don't mean what they say.
subQuotationList: ['Tired!', "That is exactly like you. You\nalways think women don't mean what they say."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Well, you sound tired, as if something has worried you.
subQuotationList: ['Well, you sound tired, as if something has worried you.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
What if I do? It doesn't prevent me from realizing the truth. I can't
marry you, and you will thank me for saying so some day.
subQuotationList: ["What if I do? It doesn't prevent me from realizing the truth. I can't\nmarry you, and you will thank me for saying so some day."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: You had that bad headache yesterday--All right
subQuotationList: ['You had that bad headache yesterday--All right']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I see it's much more than headaches. But give me a
moment's time.
subQuotationList: ["I see it's much more than headaches. But give me a\nmoment's time."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
You must excuse me if I say stupid
things, but my brain has gone to pieces. Part of it lives three minutes
back, when I was sure that you loved me, and the other part--I find it
difficult--I am likely to say the wrong thing.
subQuotationList:
['You must excuse me if I say stupid
things, but my brain has gone to pieces. Part of it lives three minutes
back, when I was sure that you loved me, and the other part--I find it
difficult--I am likely to say the wrong thing.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
There are days when one sees clearly, and this is one of them. Things
must come to a breaking-point some time, and it happens to be to-day. If
you want to know, quite a little thing decided me to speak to you--when
you wouldn't play tennis with Freddy.
subQuotationList:
["There are days when one sees clearly, and this is one of them. Things
must come to a breaking-point some time, and it happens to be to-day. If
you want to know, quite a little thing decided me to speak to you--when
you wouldn't play tennis with Freddy."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I never do play tennis, I never
could play. I don't understand a word you say.
subQuotationList: ['I never do play tennis,', "I never\ncould play. I don't understand a word you say."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
You can play well enough to make up a four. I thought it abominably
selfish of you.
subQuotationList: ['You can play well enough to make up a four. I thought it abominably\nselfish of you.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
No, I can't--well, never mind the tennis. Why couldn't you--couldn't
you have warned me if you felt anything wrong? You talked of our wedding
at lunch--at least, you let me talk.
subQuotationList: ["No, I can't--well, never mind the tennis. Why couldn't you--couldn't\nyou have warned me if you felt anything wrong? You talked of our wedding\nat lunch--at least, you let me talk."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I knew you wouldn't understand, I might have
known there would have been these dreadful explanations. Of course,
it isn't the tennis--that was only the last straw to all I have been
feeling for weeks. Surely it was better not to speak until I felt
certain. Often before I have wondered if
I was fitted for your wife--for instance, in London; and are you fitted
to be my husband? I don't think so. You don't like Freddy, nor my
mother. There was always a lot against our engagement, Cecil, but all
our relations seemed pleased, and we met so often, and it was no good
mentioning it until--well, until all things came to a point. They have
to-day. I see clearly. I must speak. That's all.
subQuotationList:
["I knew you wouldn't understand,", "I might have
known there would have been these dreadful explanations. Of course,
it isn't the tennis--that was only the last straw to all I have been
feeling for weeks. Surely it was better not to speak until I felt
certain.", "Often before I have wondered if
I was fitted for your wife--for instance, in London; and are you fitted

to-day. I see clearly. I must speak. That's all."]
speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Vyse']], [], [['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Freddy'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Mr. Vyse', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Cecil', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Vyse', 'Lucy']]]

quoteText:
I cannot think you were right, I cannot tell
why, but though all that you say sounds true, I feel that you are not
treating me fairly. It's all too horrible.
subQuotationList: ['I cannot think you were right,', "I cannot tell\nwhy, but though all that you say sounds true, I feel that you are not\ntreating me fairly. It's all too horrible."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: What's the good of a scene?
subQuotationList: ["What's the good of a scene?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: No good. But surely I have a right to hear a little more.
subQuotationList: ['No good. But surely I have a right to hear a little more.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Don't open the window; and you'd better draw the curtain, too; Freddy
or any one might be outside.
subQuotationList: ["Don't open the window; and you'd better draw the curtain, too; Freddy\nor any one might be outside."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I really think we had better
go to bed, if you don't mind. I shall only say things that will make me
unhappy afterwards. As you say it is all too horrible, and it is no good
talking.
subQuotationList:
["I really think we had better
go to bed, if you don't mind. I shall only say things that will make me
unhappy afterwards. As you say it is all too horrible, and it is no good
talking."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
But I love you, and I did think you loved
me!
subQuotationList: ['But I love you, and I did think you loved\nme!']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I did not, I thought I did at first. I am sorry, and ought
to have refused you this last time, too.
subQuotationList: ['I did not,', 'I thought I did at first. I am sorry, and ought\nto have refused you this last time, too.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
You don't love me, evidently. I dare say you are right not to. But it
would hurt a little less if I knew why.
subQuotationList: ["You don't love me, evidently. I dare say you are right not to. But it\nwould hurt a little less if I knew why."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Because
subQuotationList: ['Because']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
you're the sort
who can't know any one intimately.
subQuotationList: ["you're the sort\nwho can't know any one intimately."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I don't mean exactly that. But you will question me, though I beg you
not to, and I must say something. It is that, more or less. When we
were only acquaintances, you let me be myself, but now you're always
protecting me. I won't be protected. I will choose
for myself what is ladylike and right. To shield me is an insult. Can't
I be trusted to face the truth but I must get it second-hand through
you? A woman's place! You despise my mother--I know you do--because
she's conventional and bothers over puddings; but, oh goodness! conventional, Cecil, you're that, for you may
understand beautiful things, but you don't know how to use them; and you
wrap yourself up in art and books and music, and would try to wrap up
me. I won't be stifled, not by the most glorious music, for people are
more glorious, and you hide them from me. That's why I break off my
engagement. You were all right as long as you kept to things, but when
you came to people--
subQuotationList:
["I don't mean exactly that. But you will question me, though I beg you
not to, and I must say something. It is that, more or less. When we
were only acquaintances, you let me be myself, but now you're always
protecting me.", "I won't be protected. I will choose

speaker: Lucy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Vyse', 'Lucy']], [['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch']], [['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse']]]

quoteText: It is true.
subQuotationList: ['It is true.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: True on the whole,
subQuotationList: ['True on the whole,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: True, every word. It is a revelation. It is--I.
subQuotationList: ['True, every word. It is a revelation. It is--I.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Anyhow, those are my reasons for not being your wife.
subQuotationList: ['Anyhow, those are my reasons for not being your wife.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It is true. I
fell to pieces the very first day we were engaged. I behaved like a cad
to Beebe and to your brother. You are even greater than I thought. I'm not going to worry you. You are far too good to
me. I shall never forget your insight; and, dear, I only blame you for
this: you might have warned me in the early stages, before you felt
you wouldn't marry me, and so have given me a chance to improve. I have
never known you till this evening. I have just used you as a peg for
my silly notions of what a woman should be. But this evening you are a
different person: new thoughts--even a new voice--
subQuotationList:
['It is true. I
fell to pieces the very first day we were engaged. I behaved like a cad
to Beebe and to your brother. You are even greater than I thought.', "I'm not going to worry you. You are far too good to
me. I shall never forget your insight; and, dear, I only blame you for
this: you might have warned me in the early stages, before you felt
you wouldn't marry me, and so have given me a chance to improve. I have
never known you till this evening. I have just used you as a peg for
my silly notions of what a woman should be. But this evening you are a
different person: new thoughts--even a new voice--"]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: What do you mean by a new voice?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean by a new voice?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I mean that a new person seems speaking through you,
subQuotationList: ['I mean that a new person seems speaking through you,']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
If you think I am in love with
someone else, you are very much mistaken.
subQuotationList: ['If you think I am in love with\nsomeone else, you are very much mistaken.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Of course I don't think that. You are not that kind, Lucy.
subQuotationList: ["Of course I don't think that. You are not that kind, Lucy."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Oh, yes, you do think it. It's your old idea, the idea that has kept
Europe back--I mean the idea that women are always thinking of men. If
a girl breaks off her engagement, everyone says:
subQuotationList: ["Oh, yes, you do think it. It's your old idea, the idea that has kept\nEurope back--I mean the idea that women are always thinking of men. If\na girl breaks off her engagement, everyone says:"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It's disgusting,
brutal! As if a girl can't break it off for the sake of freedom.
subQuotationList: ["It's disgusting,\nbrutal! As if a girl can't break it off for the sake of freedom."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I may have said that in the past. I shall never
say it again. You have taught me better.
subQuotationList: ['I may have said that in the past. I shall never\nsay it again. You have taught me better.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Of
course, there is no question of 'someone else' in this, no 'jilting' or
any such nauseous stupidity. I beg your pardon most humbly if my words
suggested that there was. I only meant that there was a force in you
that I hadn't known of up till now.
subQuotationList:
["Of
course, there is no question of 'someone else' in this, no 'jilting' or
any such nauseous stupidity. I beg your pardon most humbly if my words
suggested that there was. I only meant that there was a force in you
that I hadn't known of up till now."]
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
All right, Cecil, that will do. Don't apologize to me. It was my
mistake.
subQuotationList: ["All right, Cecil, that will do. Don't apologize to me. It was my\nmistake."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
It is a question between ideals, yours and mine--pure abstract ideals,
and yours are the nobler. I was bound up in the old vicious notions,
and all the time you were splendid and new.
subQuotationList: ['It is a question between ideals, yours and mine--pure abstract ideals,\nand yours are the nobler. I was bound up in the old vicious notions,\nand all the time you were splendid and new.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I must
actually thank you for what you have done--for showing me what I really
am. Solemnly, I thank you for showing me a true woman. Will you shake
hands?
subQuotationList:
['I must
actually thank you for what you have done--for showing me what I really
am. Solemnly, I thank you for showing me a true woman. Will you shake
hands?']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Of course I will, Good-night, Cecil. Good-bye. That's all right. I'm sorry
about it. Thank you very much for your gentleness.
subQuotationList: ['Of course I will,', "Good-night, Cecil. Good-bye. That's all right. I'm sorry\nabout it. Thank you very much for your gentleness."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: Let me light your candle, shall I?
subQuotationList: ['Let me light your candle, shall I?']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Thank you. Good-night again. God bless you, Lucy!
subQuotationList: ['Thank you. Good-night again. God bless you, Lucy!']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: Good-bye, Cecil.
subQuotationList: ['Good-bye, Cecil.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: So you're off for a minute, Mr. Vyse?
subQuotationList: ["So you're off for a minute, Mr. Vyse?"]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Yes,
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I was coming to show you this delightful letter from those friends
of Miss Honeychurch.
subQuotationList: ['I was coming to show you this delightful letter from those friends\nof Miss Honeychurch.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Isn't it wonderful? Isn't it
romance? Most certainly they will go to Constantinople. They are taken
in a snare that cannot fail. They will end by going round the world.
subQuotationList: ["Isn't it wonderful? Isn't it\nromance? Most certainly they will go to Constantinople. They are taken\nin a snare that cannot fail. They will end by going round the world."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

quoteText:
Isn't Romance capricious! I never notice it in you young people; you
do nothing but play lawn tennis, and say that romance is dead, while the
Miss Alans are struggling with all the weapons of propriety against the
terrible thing.
subQuotationList:
["Isn't Romance capricious! I never notice it in you young people; you
do nothing but play lawn tennis, and say that romance is dead, while the
Miss Alans are struggling with all the weapons of propriety against the
terrible thing."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
So
they call it out of decency, but in their hearts they want a pension
with magic windows opening on the foam of perilous seas in fairyland
forlorn! No ordinary view will content the Miss Alans. They want the
Pension Keats.
subQuotationList:
['So
they call it out of decency, but in their hearts they want a pension
with magic windows opening on the foam of perilous seas in fairyland
forlorn! No ordinary view will content the Miss Alans. They want the
Pension Keats.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

quoteText:
I'm awfully sorry to interrupt, Mr. Beebe, but have you
any matches?
subQuotationList: ["I'm awfully sorry to interrupt, Mr. Beebe,", 'but have you\nany matches?']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: I have,
subQuotationList: ['I have,']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText: You have never met these Miss Alans, have you, Mr. Vyse?
subQuotationList: ['You have never met these Miss Alans, have you, Mr. Vyse?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Never.
subQuotationList: ['Never.']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
Then you don't see the wonder of this Greek visit. I haven't been
to Greece myself, and don't mean to go, and I can't imagine any of my
friends going. It is altogether too big for our little lot. Don't you
think so? Italy is just about as much as we can manage. Italy is heroic,
but Greece is godlike or devilish--I am not sure which, and in either
case absolutely out of our suburban focus. All right, Freddy--I am
not being clever, upon my word I am not--I took the idea from another
fellow; and give me those matches when you've done with them.
subQuotationList:
["Then you don't see the wonder of this Greek visit. I haven't been
to Greece myself, and don't mean to go, and I can't imagine any of my
friends going. It is altogether too big for our little lot. Don't you
think so? Italy is just about as much as we can manage. Italy is heroic,
but Greece is godlike or devilish--I am not sure which, and in either
case absolutely out of our suburban focus. All right, Freddy--I am
not being clever, upon my word I am not--I took the idea from another
fellow; and give me those matches when you've done with them."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I was saying, if
our poor little Cockney lives must have a background, let it be Italian.
Big enough in all conscience. The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel for
me. There the contrast is just as much as I can realize. But not the
Parthenon, not the frieze of Phidias at any price; and here comes the
victoria.
subQuotationList:
['I was saying, if
our poor little Cockney lives must have a background, let it be Italian.
Big enough in all conscience. The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel for
me. There the contrast is just as much as I can realize. But not the
Parthenon, not the frieze of Phidias at any price; and here comes the
victoria.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: You're quite right, Greece is not for our little lot
subQuotationList: ["You're quite right,", 'Greece is not for our little lot']
speaker: Mr. Vyse

quoteText:
I'm so glad you
only talked about books. Cecil's hard hit. Lucy won't marry him. If
you'd gone on about her, as you did about them, he might have broken
down.
subQuotationList:
["I'm so glad you
only talked about books. Cecil's hard hit. Lucy won't marry him. If
you'd gone on about her, as you did about them, he might have broken
down."]
speaker: Freddy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Vyse'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Beebe'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Mr. Vyse']]]

quoteText: But when--
subQuotationList: ['But when--']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Late last night. I must go.
subQuotationList: ['Late last night. I must go.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText: Perhaps they won't want me down there.
subQuotationList: ["Perhaps they won't want me down there."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: No--go on. Good-bye.
subQuotationList: ['No--go on. Good-bye.']
speaker: Freddy

quoteText:
Thank goodness! It was the one foolish thing she ever
did. Oh, what a glorious riddance!
subQuotationList: ['Thank goodness!', 'It was the one foolish thing she ever\ndid. Oh, what a glorious riddance!']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, how do you do, Mr. Beebe? Gracious what a mess everything is! Look
at my scarlet pompoms, and the wind blowing your skirts about, and the
ground so hard that not a prop will stick in, and then the carriage
having to go out, when I had counted on having Powell, who--give every
one their due--does tie up dahlias properly.
subQuotationList:
['Oh, how do you do, Mr. Beebe? Gracious what a mess everything is! Look
at my scarlet pompoms, and the wind blowing your skirts about, and the
ground so hard that not a prop will stick in, and then the carriage
having to go out, when I had counted on having Powell, who--give every
one their due--does tie up dahlias properly.']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: How do you do?
subQuotationList: ['How do you do?']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText: Here, Lennie, the bass,
subQuotationList: ['Here, Lennie, the bass,']
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Come for a walk with me, You have worried them as much
as they can stand. Mrs. Honeychurch, I only called in aimlessly. I shall
take her up to tea at the Beehive Tavern, if I may.
subQuotationList: ['Come for a walk with me,', 'You have worried them as much\nas they can stand. Mrs. Honeychurch, I only called in aimlessly. I shall\ntake her up to tea at the Beehive Tavern, if I may.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, must you? Yes do.--Not the scissors, thank you, Charlotte, when
both my hands are full already--I'm perfectly certain that the orange
cactus will go before I can get to it.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, must you? Yes do.--Not the scissors, thank you, Charlotte, when\nboth my hands are full already--I'm perfectly certain that the orange\ncactus will go before I can get to it."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText:
Yes, Charlotte, I don't want you--do go; there's nothing to stop about
for, either in the house or out of it.
subQuotationList: ["Yes, Charlotte, I don't want you--do go; there's nothing to stop about\nfor, either in the house or out of it."]
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

quoteText: It is terrible, this havoc among the flowers,
subQuotationList: ['It is terrible, this havoc among the flowers,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
It is always terrible when the promise of months is destroyed in a
moment,
subQuotationList: ['It is always terrible when the promise of months is destroyed in a\nmoment,']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
Perhaps we ought to send Miss Honeychurch down to her mother. Or will
she come with us?
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps we ought to send Miss Honeychurch down to her mother. Or will\nshe come with us?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: I think we had better leave Lucy to herself, and to her own pursuits.
subQuotationList: ['I think we had better leave Lucy to herself, and to her own pursuits.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
They're angry with Miss Honeychurch because she was late for
breakfast, and Floyd has gone, and Mr. Vyse has
gone, and Freddy won't play with me. In fact, Uncle Arthur, the house is
not AT ALL what it was yesterday.
subQuotationList:
["They're angry with Miss Honeychurch because she was late for
breakfast,", "and Floyd has gone, and Mr. Vyse has
gone, and Freddy won't play with me. In fact, Uncle Arthur, the house is
not AT ALL what it was yesterday."]
speaker: Minnie Beebe

quoteText: Don't be a prig, Go and put on your boots.
subQuotationList: ["Don't be a prig,", 'Go and put on your boots.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
How do you do? Miss Bartlett and Minnie are coming with me to tea at
the Beehive. Would you come too?
subQuotationList: ['How do you do? Miss Bartlett and Minnie are coming with me to tea at\nthe Beehive. Would you come too?']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: I don't think I will, thank you.
subQuotationList: ["I don't think I will, thank you."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: No, I didn't suppose you would care to much.
subQuotationList: ["No, I didn't suppose you would care to much."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: How delicate those Sonatas are!
subQuotationList: ['How delicate those Sonatas are!']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Miss Honeychurch!
subQuotationList: ['Miss Honeychurch!']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Yes.
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I met them on the hill. Your brother told me.
subQuotationList: ['I met them on the hill. Your brother told me.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Oh he did?
subQuotationList: ['Oh he did?']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I needn't say that it will go no further.
subQuotationList: ["I needn't say that it will go no further."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Mother, Charlotte, Cecil, Freddy, you,
subQuotationList: ['Mother, Charlotte, Cecil, Freddy, you,']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
If you'll let me say so, I am very glad, and I am certain that you have
done the right thing.
subQuotationList: ["If you'll let me say so, I am very glad, and I am certain that you have\ndone the right thing."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: So I hoped other people would think, but they don't seem to.
subQuotationList: ["So I hoped other people would think, but they don't seem to."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I could see that Miss Bartlett thought it unwise.
subQuotationList: ['I could see that Miss Bartlett thought it unwise.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: So does mother. Mother minds dreadfully.
subQuotationList: ['So does mother. Mother minds dreadfully.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I am very sorry for that,
subQuotationList: ['I am very sorry for that,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: And Freddy minds.
subQuotationList: ['And Freddy minds.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Still, Freddy never hit it off with Vyse much, did he? I gathered that
he disliked the engagement, and felt it might separate him from you.
subQuotationList: ['Still, Freddy never hit it off with Vyse much, did he? I gathered that\nhe disliked the engagement, and felt it might separate him from you.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Boys are so odd.
subQuotationList: ['Boys are so odd.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
I have had an
absurd letter from Miss Alan. That was really what brought me over. I
thought it might amuse you all.
subQuotationList: ['I have had an\nabsurd letter from Miss Alan. That was really what brought me over. I\nthought it might amuse you all.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: How delightful!
subQuotationList: ['How delightful!']
speaker: Lucy

subQuotationList: ['Going abroad? When do they start?']

subQuotationList: ["No, he didn't."]

subQuotationList: ["Because I do hope he won't go gossiping."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Oh,
do tell me more about the Miss Alans! How perfectly splendid of them to
go abroad!
subQuotationList: ['Oh,\ndo tell me more about the Miss Alans! How perfectly splendid of them to\ngo abroad!']

quoteText:
I want them to start from Venice, and go in a cargo steamer down the
Illyrian coast!
subQuotationList: ['I want them to start from Venice, and go in a cargo steamer down the\nIllyrian coast!']

subQuotationList: ["Oh, delightful! I wish they'd take me."]

Has Italy filled you with the fever of travel? Perhaps George Emerson
is right. He says that
subQuotationList: ['Has Italy filled you with the fever of travel? Perhaps George Emerson\nis right. He says that']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, not Italy, but Constantinople. I have always longed to go to
Constantinople. Constantinople is practically Asia, isn't it?
subQuotationList: ["Oh, not Italy, but Constantinople. I have always longed to go to\nConstantinople. Constantinople is practically Asia, isn't it?"]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
with Delphi, perhaps, if the roads
are safe.
subQuotationList: ['with Delphi, perhaps, if the roads\nare safe.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
I didn't realize that you and the Miss Alans were still such friends,
after Cissie Villa.
subQuotationList: ["I didn't realize that you and the Miss Alans were still such friends,\nafter Cissie Villa."]
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
Oh, that's nothing; I assure you Cissie Villa's nothing to me; I would
give anything to go with them.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, that's nothing; I assure you Cissie Villa's nothing to me; I would\ngive anything to go with them."]
speaker: Lucy

Would your mother spare you again so soon? You have scarcely been home
three months.
subQuotationList: ['Would your mother spare you again so soon? You have scarcely been home\nthree months.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
She MUST spare me! I simply MUST
go away. I have to. Don't you see that I HAVE to go away? I didn't realize at the time--and
of course I want to see Constantinople so particularly.
subQuotationList: ['She MUST spare me!', 'I simply MUST\ngo away. I have to.', "Don't you see that I HAVE to go away? I didn't realize at the time--and\nof course I want to see Constantinople so particularly."]

speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText: Yes, yes. I knew you'd understand.
subQuotationList: ["Yes, yes. I knew you'd understand."]
speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Yes, of course; to go to Constantinople until they are used to the idea
and everything has calmed down.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, of course; to go to Constantinople until they are used to the idea\nand everything has calmed down.']
speaker: Lucy

quoteText: I am afraid it has been a bothersome business,
subQuotationList: ['I am afraid it has been a bothersome business,']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

quoteText:
No, not at all. Cecil was very kind indeed; only--I had better tell
you the whole truth, since you have heard a little--it was that he is
so masterful. I found that he wouldn't let me go my own way. He would
improve me in places where I can't be improved. Cecil won't let a woman
decide for herself--in fact, he daren't. What nonsense I do talk! But
that is the kind of thing.

It is what I gathered from my own observation of Mr. Vyse; it is what I
gather from all that I have known of you. I do sympathize and agree

mother, and all the money she spent on me last spring. You all think
much too highly of me. I wish you weren't so kind.

she might yet reveal depths of strangeness, if not of
meaning.

We had much better let the matter

subQuotationList: ['I wonder.']

quoteText: Quite so.
subQuotationList: ['Quite so.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

I do implore absolute secrecy. A chance word to a chattering friend,

quoteText: Exactly.
subQuotationList: ['Exactly.']

quoteText:
We shan't have
rain, but we shall have darkness, so let us hurry on. The darkness last
night was appalling. I have been thinking, Miss Bartlett, and, unless you
very much object, I would like to reopen that discussion. Nothing about the past. I know little and care less about that; I am
absolutely certain that it is to your cousin's credit. She has acted
loftily and rightly, and it is like her gentle modesty to say that we
think too highly of her. But the future. Seriously, what do you think of
this Greek plan? I don't know whether
you overheard, but she wants to join the Miss Alans in their mad career.
It's all--I can't explain--it's wrong.

There I cannot agree with you. In it
I spy Lucy's salvation.

desire a change.
subQuotationList: ['It is natural, surely--after such painful scenes--that she should\ndesire a change.']

quoteText:
So she says herself, and since another
lady agrees with her, I must own that I am partially convinced. Perhaps
she must have a change. I have no sisters or--and I don't understand
these things. But why need she go as far as Greece?
subQuotationList:
["So she says herself, and since another
lady agrees with her, I must own that I am partially convinced. Perhaps
she must have a change. I have no sisters or--and I don't understand
these things. But why need she go as far as Greece?"]

quoteText:
You may well ask that, Why Greece?
(What is it, Minnie dear--jam?) Why not Tunbridge Wells? Oh, Mr. Beebe!
I had a long and most unsatisfactory interview with dear Lucy this
morning. I cannot help her. I will say no more. Perhaps I have already
said too much. I am not to talk. I wanted her to spend six months with
me at Tunbridge Wells, and she refused.
subQuotationList:
['You may well ask that,', 'Why Greece?
(What is it, Minnie dear--jam?) Why not Tunbridge Wells? Oh, Mr. Beebe!
I had a long and most unsatisfactory interview with dear Lucy this
morning. I cannot help her. I will say no more. Perhaps I have already
said too much. I am not to talk. I wanted her to spend six months with
me at Tunbridge Wells, and she refused.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

quoteText:
But my feelings are of no importance. I know too well that I get on
Lucy's nerves. Our tour was a failure. She wanted to leave Florence, and
when we got to Rome she did not want to be in Rome, and all the time I
felt that I was spending her mother's money--.
subQuotationList:
["But my feelings are of no importance. I know too well that I get on

when we got to Rome she did not want to be in Rome, and all the time I
felt that I was spending her mother's money--."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

Let us keep to the future, though, I want your
advice.
subQuotationList: ['Let us keep to the future, though,', 'I want your\nadvice.']
speaker: Mr. Beebe

Very well, I for one will help her to go to Greece.
Will you?

quoteText:
It is absolutely necessary, I know--I know. She must not stop here a moment, and we must
keep quiet till she goes. I trust that the servants know nothing.
Afterwards--but I may have said too much already. Only, Lucy and I are
helpless against Mrs. Honeychurch alone. If you help we may succeed.
Otherwise--
subQuotationList:
['It is absolutely necessary,', 'I know--I know.', 'She must not stop here a moment, and we must

let us go back now, and settle the whole thing up.

marry do well, but they that refrain do better.

breaking with Vyse?

I am sorry I

But, of course, you know all about these things, and you have Mr. Vyse
to help you. A gentleman is such a stand-by.

No one will see Lucy off, She doesn't
like it.

quoteText: No, I hate seeings-off,
subQuotationList: ['No, I hate seeings-off,']
speaker: Lucy

Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch, you aren't going? It is such a pleasure to have

That's all right. We just got
through that time.

quoteText:
I should be told, dear, that I am
unsympathetic. But I cannot see why you didn't tell your friends about

unpleasant.

unsympathetic. But I cannot see why you didn't tell your friends about

Because I settled with Cecil not to announce it until I left England. I
shall tell them then. It's much pleasanter. How wet it is! Let's turn in

Oh, well, let it be shop, then. Let's go to Mudie's. I'll buy a
guide-book.

You know, Lucy, you and Charlotte and Mr. Beebe all tell me I'm
so stupid, so I suppose I am, but I shall never understand this
hole-and-corner work. You've got rid of Cecil--well and good, and I'm
thankful he's gone, though I did feel angry for the minute. But why not
announce it? Why this hushing up and tip-toeing?
subQuotationList:
["You know, Lucy, you and Charlotte and Mr. Beebe all tell me I'm
so stupid, so I suppose I am, but I shall never understand this

answer me; she would rather be with those inquisitive old maids than

answer me; she would rather be with those inquisitive old maids than

I do not love George; I broke off my engagement
because I did not love George; I must go to Greece because I do not
love George; it is more important that I should look up gods in the

very badly.

because I did not love George; I must go to Greece because I do not

quoteText:
And mess with typewriters and latch-keys, And agitate and scream, and be carried off kicking by the police. And
call it a Mission--when no one wants you! And call it Duty--when
it means that you can't stand your own home! And call it Work--when
thousands of men are starving with the competition as it is! And then
to prepare yourself, find two doddering old ladies, and go abroad with
them.

quoteText:
Very well. Take your independence and be gone. Rush up and down and
round the world, and come back as thin as a lath with the bad food.
Despise the house that your father built and the garden that he planted,
and our dear view--and then share a flat with another girl.

me that you are in a muddle.
subQuotationList: ['My dear, I am worried about you. It seems to\nme', 'that you are in a muddle.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson
referringExpression: He heard her in silence and then said

quoteText:
Take an old man's word; there's nothing worse than a muddle in all the
world. It is easy to face Death and Fate, and the things that sound
so dreadful. It is on my muddles that I look back with horror--on the
things that I might have avoided. We can help one another but little. I
used to think I could teach young people the whole of life, but I know
better now, and all my teaching of George has come down to this: beware
of muddle. Do you remember in that church, when you pretended to be
annoyed with me and weren't? Do you remember before, when you refused
the room with the view? Those were muddles--little, but ominous--and I
am fearing that you are in one now.
subQuotationList:
["Take an old man's word; there's nothing worse than a muddle in all the
world. It is easy to face Death and Fate, and the things that sound
so dreadful. It is on my muddles that I look back with horror--on the
things that I might have avoided. We can help one another but little. I
used to think I could teach young people the whole of life, but I know
better now, and all my teaching of George has come down to this: beware
of muddle. Do you remember in that church, when you pretended to be
annoyed with me and weren't? Do you remember before, when you refused
the room with the view? Those were muddles--little, but ominous--and I
am fearing that you are in one now."]
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
You're shocked, but I mean to shock you. It's the only hope at times. I
can reach you no other way. You must marry, or your life will be wasted.
You have gone too far to retreat. I have no time for the tenderness, and
the comradeship, and the poetry, and the things that really matter, and
for which you marry. I know that, with George, you will find them, and
that you love him. Then be his wife. He is already part of you. Though
you fly to Greece, and never see him again, or forget his very name,
George will work in your thoughts till you die. It isn't possible to
love and to part. You will wish that it was. You can transmute love,
ignore it, muddle it, but you can never pull it out of you. I know by
experience that the poets are right: love is eternal.

quoteText:
I only wish poets would say this, too: love is of the body; not
the body, but of the body. Ah! the misery that would be saved if we
confessed that! Ah! for a little directness to liberate the soul! Your
soul, dear Lucy! I hate the word now, because of all the cant with which
superstition has wrapped it round. But we have souls. I cannot say how
they came nor whither they go, but we have them, and I see you ruining
yours. I cannot bear it. It is again the darkness creeping in; it
is hell.
subQuotationList:
['I only wish poets would say this, too: love is of the body; not
the body, but of the body. Ah! the misery that would be saved if we
confessed that! Ah! for a little directness to liberate the soul! Your
soul, dear Lucy! I hate the word now, because of all the cant with which
superstition has wrapped it round. But we have souls. I cannot say how
they came nor whither they go, but we have them, and I see you ruining
yours. I cannot bear it. It is again the darkness creeping in; it
is hell.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
What nonsense I have talked--how
abstract and remote! And I have made you cry! Dear girl, forgive my
prosiness; marry my boy. When I think what life is, and how seldom love
is answered by love--Marry him; it is one of the moments for which the
world was made.

world was made.']
speaker: Mr. Emerson

quoteText:
Now it is all dark. Now Beauty and Passion seem never to have existed.
I know. But remember the mountains over Florence and the view. Ah, dear,
if I were George, and gave you one kiss, it would make you brave. You
have to go cold into a battle that needs warmth, out into the muddle
that you have made yourself; and your mother and all your friends
will despise you, oh, my darling, and rightly, if it is ever right to
despise. George still dark, all the tussle and the misery without a word
from him. Am I justified?

quoteText: Mean what, George?

speaker: Lucy

quoteText:
Is it this? Is this possible? I'll put a marvel to you.
That your cousin has always hoped. That from the very first moment we
met, she hoped, far down in her mind, that we should be like this--of
course, very far down. That she fought us on the surface, and yet she
hoped. I can't explain her any other way. Can you? Look how she kept me
alive in you all the summer; how she gave you no peace; how month after
month she became more eccentric and unreliable. The sight of us haunted
her--or she couldn't have described us as she did to her friend. There
are details--it burnt. I read the book afterwards. She is not frozen,
Lucy, she is not withered up all through. She tore us apart twice, but
in the rectory that evening she was given one more chance to make us
happy. We can never make friends with her or thank her. But I do believe
that, far down in her heart, far below all speech and behaviour, she is
glad.
